<FIRST>u w AM-GrayFinances 6thLd-Writethru a0402-a0403K-3Ki</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Gray Finances, 6th Ld-Writethru, a0402-a0403-a0404,620</SECOND>
<HEAD>URGENT</HEAD>
<HEAD>FBI Conducting Preliminary Investigation of Gray's Office</HEAD>
<HEAD>EDS: COMBINES pvs takes; no pickup</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By STEVEN KOMAROW</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The FBI is conducting a preliminary inquiry
into allegations of payroll padding on the staff of Rep. William
Gray, a Pennsylvania Democrat who is seeking a leadership post in
the House, sources said Tuesday night.
   Gray, who is seeking the majority whip position in anticipation
of the expected resignation of House Speaker Jim Wright, confirmed
earlier in the day that he had been approached by two
Philadelphia-based FBI agents on Monday.
   But Gray denounced as an ``outrageous lie'' a televised report
that he was under criminal investigation.
   The congressman said that he had been specifically told by the
agents that he was neither a target nor a subject of a criminal
investigation.
   But government sources, speaking on condition of anonymity,
confirmed a CBS News report that the FBI was conducting a
preliminary inquiry into allegations regarding personnel and
expenditures in the congressman's office.
   One source said there were allegations of a no-show employee
being kept on Gray's payroll. The source stressed, however, that
the FBI's inquiry was at this point preliminary and agents did not
know whether it would lead to a full-scale criminal investigation.
   Though Gray denied that he was a target or subject, under the
FBI's definition of a preliminary inquiry, no one is a subject or
target of such a probe.
   ``I was told over and over again that I was not under
investigation,'' Gray said in a statement to reporters, adding that
FBI agents told him Monday that an employee or employees of his
office had been under investigation for several months.
   ``We pledged to provide any materials or documents to assist in
this investigation,'' Gray said, denying that he was in any way
uncooperative.
   Gray is chairman of the House Democratic Caucus and a candidate
for the House majority whip post being opened up by the planned
resignation of Rep. Tony Coelho, D-Calif. The report comes as
Democrats await the expected resignation of Wright, who faces 69
charges by the House ethics committee.
   ``As I am in the midst of a leadership race in which some have
said I am the front runner, I have to question the sources of these
leaks and their motives as well as their timing,'' Gray said.
   CBS said FBI agents visited Gray this past weekend seeking his
cooperation. ``It was not forthcoming,'' CBS said, adding that the
sources said subpoenas likely would be issued within weeks.
   Gray disputed the CBS account.
   ``On Memorial Day I was contacted for the first time by two
agents assigned to the FBI's office in Philadelphia,'' Gray said.
``During the conversation with the agents I was told over and over
again that I was not under investigation nor the target of an
investigation. I was told that the bureau was looking into
allegations about an employee or employees and that they had been
looking into these allegations for the past four to five months.''
   Gray, the highest ranking black in Congress, appeared on a CBS
program Sunday and said he was confident the Democratic
congressional leadership, recently rocked by ethical problems of
Wright and a questionable financial deal involving Coelho, was
headed for better times.
   ``I know that all of us feel very confident,'' Gray said. ``I
know this member feels very confident, that there are no problems.''
   Coelho announced on Saturday that he will leave the House on
June 15 and Wright is expected to resign possibly as early as
Wednesday.
</TEXT>
