<FILEID>AP-NR-05-30-89 0036EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r p PM-SenateRecruits     05-30 0581</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Senate Recruits,580</SECOND>
<HEAD>GOP Lining Up Strong Candidates for 1990 Senate Race</HEAD>
<HEAD>An AP News Analysis</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DONALD M. ROTHBERG</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Political Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Republicans have a clear lead over the
Democrats so far in the critical contest to recruit strong
candidates for 1990 Senate races.
   Democrats control the Senate with a 55-45 majority, a narrow
enough margin to make each contested seat the object of intense
struggle.
   The Democrats' efforts to widen their majority suffered another
setback Friday when former presidential nominee Walter F. Mondale
announced he would not challenge GOP Sen. Rudy Boschwitz.
   ``It's a lot easier deciding when to get into politics as
opposed to when to leave,'' the former vice president told a news
conference that dashed the hopes of Democrats that he would take on
Boschwitz.
   ``I certainly do have a sense of relief,'' said Boschwitz, who
has raised more than $1 million for his re-election campaign and
appears unlikely to face a serious challenge.
   A poll taken for Mondale had shown him leading Boschwitz by 9
points.
   It was the second time in eight days the Democrats saw their
dreams of capturing a GOP Senate seat slip away.
   On May 18, Sen. Nancy Kassebaum, R-Kan., announced she would
seek a third term. The senator had once said she would retire after
two terms and her announcement came after prolonged speculation
that she would stick to that plan. Kassebaum is regarded as
unbeatable.
   The year started shakily for the Republicans when Sens. Gordon
Humphrey of New Hampshire and William Armstrong of Colorado
announced they wouldn't run for re-election.
   Even without Humphrey on the ballot, the Democrats are given
little chance of breaking the Republican hold on the voters of New
Hampshire.
   Rep. Ben Nighthorse Campbell looked like the best Democratic
candidate to bid for Armstrong's seat, but he surprised Colorado
Democrats by announcing he would not run.
   By contrast with Democratic disappointments, the Republicans
have Rep. Tom Tauke, their strongest potential candidate, already
running hard against Sen. Tom Harkin of Iowa.
   In addition, Rep. Claudine Schneider looks virtually certain to
challenge Democratic Sen. Claiborne Pell of Rhode Island. An
extremely popular liberal Republican with a strong environmental
record, Schneider passed up a chance to challenge Pell in 1984. But
this time she gives every sign of being ready to take on the
70-year-old chairman of the Senate Foreign Relations Committee.
   Win or lose, Schneider is by far the best candidate the
Republicans could field.
   Another Republican woman who is strongly considering a Senate
race is Rep. Lynn Martin of Illinois, who would challenge
Democratic Sen. Paul Simon.
   Martin recently formed an exploratory committee, and Republicans
hope voters became disenchanted with Simon after his unsuccessful
bid for the 1988 Democratic presidential nomination.
   Democrats are still hoping that Gov. Gerald Baliles of Virginia,
whose term expires this year, will decide to challenge GOP Sen.
John Warner.
   While the Republicans can claim a few more recruitment successes
than the Democrats, they appear unlikely to field viable candidates
against such Democrats as Sens. Albert Gore Jr. of Tennessee, Bill
Bradley of New Jersey, Sam Nunn of Georgia, Joseph Biden of
Delaware and David Pryor of Arkansas.
   On the Republican side, safe incumbents appear to be Thad
Cochran of Mississippi, William Cohen of Maine, Pete Domenici of
New Mexico, Phil Gramm of Texas, James McClure of Idaho and Alan
Simpson of Wyoming.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>EDITOR'S NOTE </NOTE>
<TEXT>
   Donald M. Rothberg is the chief political writer
of The Associated Press.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890530-0014 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-05-30-89 0039EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r w PM-MemorialDay-Capital     05-30 0603</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Memorial Day-Capital,590</SECOND>
<HEAD>Thousands of Americans Go to Capital to Honor War Dead</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto WX6</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Vice President Dan Quayle laid a wreath at the
Tomb of the Unknowns, two Soviet veterans paid their respects at
the Vietnam memorial and thousands of people flocked to the capital
to honor America's war dead.
   Almost perfect weather with clear blue skies, temperatures in
the 80s and a gentle breeze served as backdrop to the 120th
Memorial Day services at Arlington National Cemetery, where 200,000
veterans are buried _ each tombstone marked by an American flag for
the holiday.
   On a smaller scale, eight wreaths at the Vietnam memorial
honored the women who died in that conflict.
   In brief, somber ceremonies at the Tomb of the Unknowns, Quayle
placed the wreath of flowers before the four graves _ each
representing unidentified casualties from World War I, World War
II, the Korean War and the Vietnam War.
   The observance began with a 19-gun artillery salute. A drummer
from the U.S. Army Band sounded four muffled ruffles, followed by a
bugler blowing taps and then 30 seconds of silence.
   Addressing more than 5,000 people, many in shorts and T-shirts,
Quayle called the war dead ``our nation's true heroes, the solid
pillars upon which our freedom rests.''
   The national cemetery is the resting place for ``Americans for
whom the words duty, honor and country are not just a phrase. They
were a way of life,'' said Quayle, whose military record became the
subject of controversy last year because he had avoided serving in
the Vietnam War by joining the Indiana National Guard in the late
1960s.
   Across the Potomac River in the shadows of the Lincoln Memorial,
several thousand Vietnam veterans mingled and talked about
America's most recent war. Some have made the trip to the Vietnam
Veterans Memorial each Memorial Day since the monument, a
chevron-shaped wall with the names of 58,156 war dead and missing
in action etched in its black granite, was dedicated in 1982.
   The monument, which has become the most popular in Washington,
attracts more than 3.6 million visitors a year, according to the
National Park Service.
   This Memorial Day, the ceremony was aimed at honoring the women
who died in Vietnam. Eight wreaths were placed at locations where
the names of eight women, casualties of the war, are etched into
the wall.
   Veterans who were influential in getting the monument built,
reminded the audience that most Vietnam veterans returned from the
war zone to a country that was at best indifferent and at times
hostile.
   ``Our nation can never again abandon our soldiers,'' declared
Ronald Gibbs, a member of the Vietnam Veterans Memorial Fund board
of directors. ``If we must send our youth off to battle, let's
stand by them to the end with moral conviction and support.''
   Among the thousands of visitors to the Vietnam Veterans Memorial
on Monday were a Soviet general who fought in World War II and a
veteran of the Soviet fighting in Afghanistan.
   Lt. Gen. Vladamir Orlov, chief of a World War II veterans group
in the Soviet Union, and Mikhail Vishnyakov, a veteran of the
fighting in Afghanistan, marveled at the impact of the Vietnam
memorial.
   The two even traced some of the names, according to John
Wheeler, a Vietnam veteran who helped arrange the visit.
   The Soviet Union's military struggle in Afghanistan, from which
the country was forced to withdraw after years of fighting, has
been compared to the U.S. military involvement in Vietnam.
   The Soviet Union provided supplies and weapons to the North
Vietnamese and Viet Cong during the Vietnam War.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
