<FIRST>u i AM-China 4thLd-Writethru a0685 05-30 0911</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-China, 4th Ld-Writethru, a0685,0933</SECOND>
<HEAD>Independent Unionists Claim Leaders Arrested; Statue Erected</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: LEADS with 4 grafs to UPDATE with standoff outside police headquarters.
Picks up 4th pvs, `Earlier, students ...' ^LaserPhoto BEJ9</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By TERRIL JONES</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BEIJING (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Members of a new independent labor union said
Tuesday that police arrested three of their leaders, the latest
sign the government was getting tough with non-student participants
in the pro-democracy movement.
   About 1,000 students and workers gathered outside police
headquarters, near Tiananmen Square, to protest the reported
arrests. The Public Security Bureau said it had no knowledge of the
arrests.
   Union members carried a banner reading ``do not secretly arrest
people. Let the people know.'' Worker representatives who entered
the building to ask about the three men said police refused to
acknowledge the arrests.
   Police also told them the demonstration was illegal and that
they intended to clear the area. Police with video cameras filmed
demonstrators, who said they would not leave.
   Earlier, students at the square unveiled a 33-foot-high
``Goddess of Democracy'' statue, inspiring some to pursue their
sit-in while others prepared to leave the square to seek new focus
for the 6-week-old movement.
   Zhao Pinglu, head of the Beijing Independent Workers' Union,
said police Monday grabbed one union leader, a 27-year-old official
with the national airlines, and two others, both Ministry of
Railways employees, disappeared and were assumed to have been
arrested.
   The independent trade union claims 3,000 members. It was formed
May 19 in defiance of a government ban on all but the official All
China Federation of Trade Unions.
   Party hardliners who have wrested control in a power struggle
touched off by the student protests have taken the line that the
students are well-intentioned but that non-students who are
misleading them will be punished.
   Workers who joined demonstrations or supported the movement are
being fined or having their pay docked. Others are being threatened
with losing their jobs.
   Hundreds of students from outside Beijing said they would return
home Tuesday to spread the word of the students' dramatic appeal
for a freer and more open China.
   Thousands more pledged to continue their occupation of the
square _ begun May 13 _ until China's legislature, the National
People's Congress, convenes on June 20. About 10,000 students now
are living in a squatters' camp on the vast square.
   More than 100,000 cheering supporters crammed into the central
square Monday night to see the ``Goddess of Democracy,'' based on
the Statue of Liberty in New York, being wheeled in.
   Students from the Central Academy of Fine Arts brought three
sections of the statue into the square as firecrackers burst
overhead. The statue of a woman in flowing robes holding aloft a
torch lies on a line between Mao Tse-tung's portrait on the
entrance to the Forbidden City and a monument to revolutionary
heroes on the square. The statue is made of plaster of Paris and
styrofoam.
   ``Here is a new symbol for China,'' said a worker at a machine
tool factory. ``This is even greater than your Statue of Liberty,''
another worker said to an American reporter.
   That symbol of unity came as student leaders quarreled over the
direction of their movement. Earlier, student leaders proposed that
occupation of the square end Tuesday, but were overruled by other
activists, including many from outside Beijing.
   Representatives from about 200 schools held a midnight meeting
Monday but failed to iron out differences.
   One student leader said they agreed on four demands _ that the
May 20 declaration of martial law in Beijing be rescinded, that all
troops in the Beijing suburbs be removed, that there be no
retribution against students and that the state-run press report
honestly on their movement.
   However, some argued these should be conditions for leaving the
square while others said they should be prerequisites for opening
talks with the government.
   The student leader said, ``Most people were against leaving
Tiananmen because at this point no concrete achievement has been
realized with the government.''
   The students have been holding regular protests since April 15
to demand democratic reforms and an end to corruption by officials.
   The official People's Daily prominently played a letter from
seven intellectuals recalling the tragic 1966-76 Cultural
Revolution.
   ``We ask all comrades who in those 10 year of catastrophic
terror lost loved ones, wasted their youth and suffered hardship to
call on their sense of responsibility to history and society. Warn
your sons and loved ones not to allow a repeat of this tragedy of
history.''
   Conservatives who appear to have won a power struggle over
moderates in the government continued efforts to snuff out the
democratic movement.
   Peng Zhen, former chairman of China's legislature, told a
political forum that while students' intentions were to help the
government correct mistakes, ``conspirators and bad elements'' were
manipulating the students, the official Xinhua News Agency reported.
   Peng, 86, was the latest member of China's old guard to back the
hard-line position of senior leader Deng Xiaoping and Premier Li
Peng.
   Li declared martial law in Beijing May 20 to try and end massive
demonstrations that drew up to 1 million people. Troops were
stopped by Beijing residents who poured into the streets to block
army trucks.
   The Communist Party's reformist chief, Zhao Ziyang, has been
fired and placed under house arrest for his sympathies with the
students, and several other liberal-leaning bureaucrats and party
functionaries are expected to be punished, according to Chinese
sources.
</TEXT>
