<FIRST>r a AM-IndianCollege     05-30 0282</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Indian College,0290</SECOND>
<HEAD>Indian School President Cleared of Wrongdoing</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LAWRENCE, Kan. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The president of a federally run Indian
college was scheduled to resume his duties Tuesday after being
cleared of allegations that he showed favoritism to his daughter, a
student there.
   The Bureau of Indian Affairs announced last week that Dr. Gerald
Gipp had been cleared of any wrongdoing related to claims of
conflict of interest during his tenure at Haskell Indian Junior
College.
   Gipp will continue serve there for about a month before being
transferred to new post in Washington at his own request, according
to the Indian Affairs bureau, which operates the school.
   W. Pat Ragsdale, acting assistant secretary of the BIA, said in
a statement issued in Washington that Gipp had decided to request
reassignment because of the controversy.
   Gipp was removed temporarily from the presidency of Haskell last
fall after Don Bread, a Haskell teacher, filed a complaint. Bread
charged that Gipp had directed his assistant dean of instruction in
1987 to pressure Bread into changing a failing grade he had given
Gipp's daughter, Denise, so she could graduate that year.
   Bread's complaint said the grade later was changed to a D
without his knowledge.
   Miss Gipp later worked in the Haskell admissions and records
office, where she eventually received a $600 bonus, which also was
investigated by the BIA.
   Gipp denied any wrongdoing and said his daughter had taken part
in a special summer session offered to students who could not
graduate because they had failed a required course.
   Gipp has been working in the bureau's Washington office since he
was removed at Haskell, which serves about 800 students from tribes
throughout the country.
</TEXT>
