<FIRST>u a AM-QuadrupleSlaying 4thLd-Writethru a0681 05-30 0680</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Quadruple Slaying, 4th Ld-Writethru, a0681,0697</SECOND>
<HEAD>Authorities Arrest Man in Slaying of Four</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: SUBS grafs 14-17, bgn, `Marcello was...,' with 6 grafs to UPDATE
with witnesses saying he had job but was forced to quit, quote from prosecutor.
RECASTS lead to conform. Picks up penultimate graf, `Mrs. BonGiovanni ...'</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SPRINGFIELD, N.J. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A young man described by neighbors as a
Yale graduate frustrated by unemployment stabbed his mother and
three other people to death at his home on Memorial Day,
authorities said.
   Rolando Marcello, 23, was arrested by state police after a high
speed chase that ended when the suspect left his car and jumped off
a 40-foot bridge in an attempt to elude capture, said Union County
Prosecutor John H. Stamler.
   Two of the victims were Marcello's mother, Anita Marcello, 51,
and his brother Raymond, 20, Stamler said at a news conference late
Monday.
   Two others, Nelson Paiva, 20, a family friend from neighboring
Union, and a Mark Dennis, 36, a neighbor who attempted to stop
Paiva's slaying, were also killed. All four died of multiple stab
wounds.
   Another neighbor, Richard Hartmann, was in guarded condition at
Overlook Hospital in Summit.
   Authorities said that neighbors at a holiday barbeque Monday
afternoon saw Marcello chasing Paiva with a large knife outside his
white two-story home in this suburban community about 25 miles west
of New York City.
   Janice BonGiovanni, who lives across the street in the neatly
kept neighborhood, said she first thought it was a joke when he saw
the man, who goes by the name of Rolly, wrestling on the ground
with other neighborhood men.
   ``They were on the ground. I thought they were fooling around
until I saw a knife in his hand,'' she said. ``It was a 10-inch
knife, it was like a dagger.''
   She said Marcello had Hartmann on the ground but the latter got
away. The other man, apparently Dennis, did not.
   Then ``Rolly ran into the house, came out again, opened the door
of the car and said, `What have I done, what have I done?''' she
said.
   Mrs. BonGiovanni said he then drove away in his car while
clutching a brown garbage bag.
   Marcello apparently tried to ditch the car and steal a pickup
truck but could not get it started, Stamler said. He then
succesfully stole a Volkswagen and took off heading west on Route
22.
   The high speed chase took them 20 miles to neighboring Somerset
County before Marcello abandoned his car and jumped off a highway
bridge over the Lanington River. State troopers called
reinforcements and eventually found him exhausted under a stand of
trees at about 8 p.m.
   Marcello was described as the oldest son of a family of longtime
Springfield residents originally from the Philippines.
   Neighbors said he had been depressed recently because after
graduating from Yale University with a business degree, he had been
able to work only a short time in an internship with Chemical Bank
in New York before illness forced him to drop out. The nature of
the illness was not immediately known.
   One neighbor, Steve Galluzzo, said ``the whole family was very
low key and respectful people.''
   ``I think he (Marcello) was depressed,'' he said. ``For a while
he was at top of his class in Yale but when he got out into the
business world I don't know what happened.''
   Prosecutors confirmed that Marcello had attended Yale and then
worked for a time as a commercial loan officer for Chemical Bank.
Stamler and other officials could not say if he had been working
recently.
   ``It appears that he was unhappy but I don't know if it was over
his employment,'' Stamler said.
   Mrs. BonGiovanni said his mother lived with her four sons in the
same house for about 15 years. She said the mother was a nurse at
Newark University Hospital and that the father died about 10 years
ago.
   Marcello was charged with four counts of murder and one count of
aggravated assault, Stamler said. He was being held in the Union
County Jail pending his arraignment.
</TEXT>
