<FILEID>AP-NR-05-30-89 0113EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i PM-SameNames     05-30 0326</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Same Names,0337</SECOND>
<HEAD>Experts Puzzle Over Task of Making Maps Match</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By CLARE NULLIS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>GENEVA (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Is it London or Londres? Peking or Beijing?
   U.N. experts have spent 30 years trying to come up with single
spellings for geographical names worldwide, but they say trying to
make maps match may be a losing effort.
   They struggle through 3,000 different languages, including about
250 official ones, in their search for uniform names, says Canadian
Henri Dorion, chairman of the U.N. Group of Experts on Geographical
Names.
   The group held its twice-annual meeting in Geneva last week.
   Before an internationally recognized name for a town can be
adopted, a national standard must be agreed upon. That poses
problems for countries like the Soviet Union, which has about 100
languages, Dorion explains.
   He accepts that the task will occupy his grandchildrens'
generation and doubts complete standardization will ever be
achieved.
   ``We recognize that, for example, the French will continue to
call London `Londres' and we are not trying to change that, but we
would like to limit the number of different transliterations,'' he
said.
   The experts say their little-known efforts have yielded
practical benefits, especially in improving communications.
   Bunny Lewis, a British member of the group, cited a recent
example in Sudan.
   ``If you are engaged in famine relief and you have to collect
the names of the villages to distribute food and those villages are
randomly spelled, what do you do about it?
   ``The answer is that you make new maps and you arrive at a
standard way of writing all those names of villages,'' Lewis told a
news conference.
   The new Roman-script transliteration of Chinese, adopted by the
United Nations in 1977, has been the most successful, Dorion said.
   ``The Chinese system is on the way to being accepted by
everybody. Although we still see some variations such as Peking,
more and more we are seeing Beijing in everyday usage,'' he said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890530-0023 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-05-30-89 0114EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i PM-SummitScene     05-30 0691</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Summit Scene,690</SECOND>
<HEAD>Bush Jogs During Summit Respite, Ministers Miss Dinner</HEAD>
<HEAD>With PM-Summit Rdp Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ROBERT J. WIELAARD</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BRUSSELS, Belgium (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   When you're George Bush and you find
yourself back at your 18th century chateau with 90 minutes to spare
before the next formal event of the 40th anniversary NATO summit,
what do you do?
   Put on a T-shirt and shorts and go jogging around the
Stuyvenberg Palace, what else?
   The American president is two weeks' shy of his 65th birthday,
but he still likes to get in a relaxing run whenever he can, and
that's what he did after returning late Monday afternoon from five
hours of talks with his counterparts from the 15 other NATO nations.
   It may have helped him work up an appetite for the evening
repast that followed at the Val Duchesse, another palatial estate
where the menu for what was described as a working dinner included:
lobster salad with sauce au corial and caviar; pigeon de Bresse en
cocotte with hearts of artichoke, and layered pastries with
strawberries and raspberries.
   The presidents presumably fared better on this score than did
their prime ministers, who canceled their own dinner at the Val
Duchesse while working into the wee hours to hammer out a
compromise on nuclear missile negotiating strategy.
   A pool of American reporters allowed in to the Val Duchesse to
witness the dinner arrivals found itself cooling its heels
beforehand at NATO headquarters while waiting for NATO escorts to
accompany them to the event in the mansion, located in a thickly
wooded park.
   The reporters, accustomed to being screened and sped on their
way to President Bush's events by Secret Service agents, found that
wasn't good enough in Brussels. As one wrote in a pool report, ``It
was explained NATO security would not allow the Secret Service to
sweep us, nor allow the U.S. press bus to enter the Val Duchesse
grounds.''
   ``The White House is not running this, NATO is,'' the advance
person explained.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   The media were not the only ones subject to stringent security
for the NATO summit.
   More than 1,300 local and state police have been pressed into
service to maintain security throughout the Belgian capital for the
two-day summit.
   As Bush and the leaders of the other 15 alliance nations arrived
at the sprawling NATO complex, a helicopter hovered overhead and
sharpshooters stood atop the low-rise, pastel-yellow building.
   For Brussels _ a city of one million that is also home for the
12-nation European Economic Community _ it's another summit,
another round of pomp and protection that is now almost commonplace
here.
   If it weren't for the odd motorcade whizzing by, the Brussels
citizenry would not know a summit was under way.
   There are no flags in the streets, no banners, no bunting and
certainly no crowds.
   In fact, when Bush and the other leaders lunched Monday with
King Baudouin, only 200 people bothered to stop in the Royal Park
to see what all those limousines were doing in front of their
monarch's downtown palace across the street.
   And what was billed as a big anti-NATO demonstration turned into
only a small scale protest outside the main NATO entrance,
punctuated by the sounds of a dozen drum-beating Buddhist monks
across the street.
   Not a year passes without Brussels hosting an EEC or NATO summit.
   On Monday, a warm and sunny day, security was tightest at the
NATO complex as the summit participants arrived in a quick
succession of limousines, accompanied by hundreds of police
outriders.
   In all, some 1,600 journalists have converged on Brussels to
cover NATO's 40th anniversary summit that is grappling with the
issue of the future of nuclear missiles in Europe.
   And while East-West issues may be on many front pages, not
everyone knows what NATO is all about.
   At the downtown hotel where the summit's main press center is
situated, an elderly tourist from Baltimore, Md., told a U.S.
embassy official, ``And I'm so delighted to hear people speak
American here.''
   Then, pointing to the official's ``NATO Summit,'' she added:
``I've seen that word NATO before. What does it mean?''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
