<FIRST>r a PM-Lites     05-30 0482</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Lites,0498</SECOND>
<HEAD>On The Light Side</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Where else but in Southern California would a
1950s-style car wash be deemed a ``cultural landmark.''
   The car wash, plus a gas station and coffee shop, are in the way
of a developer's plans to build a mini-mall in the San Fernando
Valley suburb of Studio City.
   But when neighbors heard of plans to bulldoze the 28-year-old
car wash, which is built around three 55-foot-tall steel girders
arched in the style of an old McDonald's outlet, they fought back.
   Last week, they persuaded the city Cultural Heritage Commission
to temporarily block the development while the commission weighs
arguments that the car wash, which doesn't even have a name, forms
the ``Gateway to Studio City.''
   ``We in the valley want to retain some of our culture and
heritage,'' said Jack McGrath, a political consultant who launched
the campaign to save the car wash.
   The Arba Group of Los Angeles plans to demolish the car wash to
make way for a two-story, $15 million shopping center. Company
officials refused to comment on the protests last week.
   About 100 area residents rallied at the gas station Sunday to
protest the planned demolition.
   Others in the neighborhood aren't sure what to make of the fuss.
   ``It's not a cultural monument,'' said resident William Griffis.
``But it certainly is a handy place to get your car washed.''
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>ATLANTA (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Making chocolate- or tangerine-flavored peanut
pudding was a snap, but peanut-based cheese spread was a tougher
nut to crack.
   Food scientists at the University of Georgia came up with those
examples of peanut creativity as part of a government-supported
effort to develop low-cost, high-protein foods for the Third World.
The foods also are low in saturated fat and cholesterol, qualities
that might sell them to U.S. consumers as well.
   And the taste is, well, ``quite acceptable,'' Dr. Anna A.V.
Resurreccion, associate professor of food science, said in a recent
interview. She began developing the products three years ago under
a grant from the U.S. Department of Agriculture.
   For the peanut pudding, Resurreccion and her colleagues pressed
peanut kernels to remove some of the oil and ground up the
remaining material. They added hot water and a coagulating agent to
get a slab of peanut curd about the consistency of tofu. Finally,
they mixed in sweeteners and flavorings.
   The pudding contains 160 calories per serving. But it has 50
percent protein by weight _ 10 times as much as a serving of
milk-based chocolate pudding with the same number of calories.
   Making peanut-based cheese spread was more complicated. Uncooked
peanuts were chopped, soaked in warm water and dried slowly to keep
them from developing the usual flavor of roasted nuts. Then they
were ground, salted and mixed with commercially available cheese
flavoring.
   The spread has a longer shelf life and twice the protein of
dairy-based products.
</TEXT>
