<DOCNO> AP890530-0028 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-05-30-89 0256EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a PM-Buddhist-AIDS     05-30 0689</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Buddhist-AIDS,0708</SECOND>
<HEAD>Buddhist Leader in Retreat Amid AIDS Reports</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Also in Tuesday AMs report.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By SANDY SHORE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BOULDER, Colo. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The leader of an international Buddhist
community is in seclusion seeking guidance from the teachings of
his 2,500-year-old religion amid reports he has AIDS and may have
spread it among his followers.
   Church leaders refuse to confirm or deny the allegations
swirling around Osel Tendzin, a man from New Jersey who rose to
become the leader of a Buddhist community, or reports that he
refused to step down.
   The 45-year-old father of four went last fall into religious
retreat _ a traditional Buddhist practice. Meditation, he said, is
``the best medicine.''
   Tendzin has been vague about the allegations, but some Buddhists
in the 3,500-member Vajradhatu community have said he admitted in a
tape played for them that he is suffering from acquired immune
deficiency syndrome.
   ``Although the faults of myself and others are the cause of this
apparent confusion, this situation has provided a means for
purifying whatever negative karma has been accumulated,'' he was
reported as saying in a Jan. 17 letter to his followers.
   Church officials say he is expected to remain in retreat in the
San Diego area at least through the end of the summer.
   Tendzin is unavailable for comment, but remains in touch with
church officials indirectly, Martin Janowitz, a member of the
Vajradhatu board of directors in Halifax, Nova Scotia, said last
week.
   Tenzin's followers are uncertain what the future holds as weeks
and months go by without a word.
   One of them, John McClellan, said the group is split between
those who believe Tendzin ``acted in a way unfitting for a group
like ours, but nonetheless feel he has just made mistakes,'' and
those who think he has gone ``so far beyond any reasonable standard
of human behavior that they can no longer practice under his
direction.''
   Born Thomas Rich, Tendzin was raised in Passaic, N.J. After
dropping out of Fordham University, he met Vidyadhara, the
Venerable Chogyam Trungpa, in 1971 and became the Tibetan Buddhist
leader's top student.
   Trungpa established Vajradhatu at Boulder in the 1970s and
founded the Naropa Institute, an accredited liberal arts college
combining Eastern and Western studies. Vajradhatu's headquarters
later were moved to Halifax.
   Trungpa ``made a great leap from one culture to another,'' said
Rick Fields, former editor of a Buddhist newspaper and author of a
history of Buddhism in America. ``One of the marks of his genius
was to meet this culture on its own ground.''
   The Vajradhatu has about 3,500 members internationally,
including 800 in Boulder. It's a diverse group of mostly non-Asians
who live ``normal, family lives,'' Fields said.
   Trungpa gave Rich the Buddhist name Osel Tendzin, which
translates as ``radiant holder of the teachings,'' Janowitz said.
Before he died in 1987, Trungpa named Tendzin his successor.
   Reports of Tendzin's illness began surfacing late last year. In
a Dec. 22 story, The Daily Camera quoted sources in the Boulder
Buddhist community who said Tendzin admitted in a tape recording
that he has AIDS and may have spread the disease. The disease is
most often spread through sexual intercourse, or sharing of tainted
needles by intravenous drug abusers.
   In January, The Daily Camera reported that the Vajradhatu board
asked Tendzin to give up his duties for a year. But Tendzin
refused, saying it would ``vioilate the oath I took with my guru.''
He also indicated that meditation during his retreat may improve
his health.
   Tendzin's wife, Lila, and their four children have stayed at
their home in Halifax.
   Many church members have said they feel isolated by the lack of
communication and the refusal of church leaders to deal with the
issue. Fields said he resigned as editor of the community's
newspaper because church leaders refused to discuss the problems.
   ``Buddhism teaches compassion for all sentient human beings.
There is a feeling of wanting to help clarify the situation,''
Fields said.
   But McClellan said: ``Nobody intends to give up on the practice.
A lot of people are beginning to feel that it's time to give up on
Vajradhatu.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
