<FIRST>u i AM-Japan-Markets     05-30 0350</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Japan-Markets,0362</SECOND>
<HEAD>Dollar Rises Slightly, Stocks Plunge in Tokyo</HEAD>
<DATELINE>TOKYO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The dollar held its ground against the Japanese yen
Tuesday, while share prices on the Stock Exchange plunged.
   The Nikkei Stock Average of 225 selected issues, which lost
30.79 points the previous day, shed another 83.94 points, or 0.25
percent, to finish trading at 34,076.89.
   The dollar ended trading at 143.10 yen, up 0.22 yen from
Monday's close of 142.88 yen. Opening higher at 143.75 yen, the
currency made a wild fluctuation between 142.20 yen and 144 yen.
   Traders said the Bank of Japan intervened in the market by
selling dollars to halt the currency's further rise against the
yen. The central bank declined to comment on its monetary actions.
   Japanese Finance Minister Tatsuo Murayama early Tuesday told a
news conference that the yen's weakness was a reaction to President
Bush's proposal for a 20 percent U.S. troop reduction in Europe.
   Bush proposed the reduction to western leaders in response to
Soviet President Mikhail S. Gorbachev's initial pledge for cuts in
the level of Warsaw Pact forces.
   Murayama also hinted at the possibility of a discount rate hike
by the central bank, which has long been expected.
   A key Bank of Japan committee is expected to meet Tuesday. Local
news reports say the central bank plans to raise the official
discount rate by 0.75 percentage points on Wednesday.
   On the stock exchange, dealers said the yen's weakness on the
foreign exchange market largely discouraged Japanese investors'
buying interst.
   Yoshio Shimoyama, a dealer with Nikko Securities in Tokyo, said
market players stepped off to the sidelines as soon as the dollar
hit the morning's high of 144 yen mark.
   ``Unless the yen's movement gets stable, stock market can't
expect large gains,'' he said.
   The majority of market players avoided making major moves
Tuesday before a series of releases of U.S. economic indicators,
including the May jobless rate, to be reported Friday, he said.
   ``Players are also interested in the West German Federal bank
meeting Thursday, to see if it would make any changes in monetary
policies,'' Shimoyama said.
</TEXT>
