<FIRST>r i PM-Japan-DiscountRate     05-30 0113</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Japan-Discount Rate,0114</SECOND>
<HEAD>Japan Raises Discount Rate for First Time in 9 Years</HEAD>
<DATELINE>TOKYO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Japan's central bank today announced it will raise
its official discount rate by 0.75 percentage points to 3.25
percent, reversing the easy money policy it maintained for almost a
decade.
   The decision, which clearly shows the central bank's intention
to combat inflation, will also lead to rises in interest and
lending rates from commercial banks, and housing loans starting in
mid-June.
   Effective Wednesday, the official discount rate, the Bank of
Japan's lending rate to commercial banks, rises to 3.25 percent
from the current 2.5 percent, the lowest among the Group of Seven
industrial nations, officials said.
</TEXT>
