<FIRST>u i PM-Japan-Markets     05-30 0368</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Japan-Markets,0380</SECOND>
<HEAD>Dollar Rises, Stock Prices Declined</HEAD>
<DATELINE>TOKYO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The dollar rose in Tokyo today despite intervention
by the central bank and an increase in the bank's official discount
rate, while stock prices declined.
   The Bank of Japan announced today that it will raise its
discount rate by 0.75 percentage points to 3.25 percent, effective
Wednesday.
   In currency dealings, the dollar closed at 143.10 yen, up 0.22
yen from Monday's closing of 142.88 yen. After opening higher at
143.75 yen, the currency fluctuated wildly between 142.20 and
144.00 yen.
   Traders said the Bank of Japan sold dollars intermittently in an
attempt to halt the U.S. currency's further rise agaisnt the yen.
The central bank sold a total of about $1 billion during the day,
they said. The bank does not normally comment on its market
interventions.
   Mitsuhiko Kinugasa, a trader with Daiwa Bank in Tokyo, said
trading today was ``very rough'' with wide fluctuations.
   ``At around noon, market players sold the dollar all at once
after a rumor that the United States might ease its monetary
policy, which participants thought would lower interst rates,'' he
said, citing the day's low of 142.20 yen.
   But he said the market generally continued to favor
dollar-buying because ``the wide interest rate gap between the
United States and Japan is still there.''
   He said the Bank of Japan's decision to raise its official
discount rate did not affect the market because it had been
expected for some time.
   Dollar-selling by some participants for profit taking also
prompted the afternoon losses, he said.
   But the dollar rose again due to a belief that the United States
was unlikely to cut its discount rate to lower the dollar, dealers
said.
   On the Tokyo Stock Exchange, the 225-issue Nikkei Stock Average,
which lost 30.79 points on Monday, fell another 83.94 points or
0.25 percent, finishing the day at 34,076.89.
   Dealers said the index's loss was largely due to the yen's
weakness against the dollar.
   A trader with a major securities firm, who spoke on condition of
anonymity, said trading was directionless due to the reluctance of
participants to make major moves because of uncertainties over the
foreign exchange market and discount rate hike.
</TEXT>
