<FIRST>r a PM-Higgins-MemorialDay     05-30 0236</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Higgins-Memorial Day,0240</SECOND>
<HEAD>Hostage's Wife Says Her Duty is Survival</HEAD>
<HEAD>Retransmitting to CORRECT category code.</HEAD>
<DATELINE>QUANTICO, Va. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Marine Maj. Robin Higgins, whose husband
has been held hostage in the Middle East since February 1988,
believes her main duty now is to survive.
   Marine Lt. Col. William R. Higgins, 44, is being held hostage in
southern Lebanon, where he was serving as part of a United Nations
peacekeeping force. Col. Higgins, whose captors in December accused
him of spying for Israel, is one of nine Americans being held in
Lebanon.
   ``For the past 15 months, I have been seeking the answers to
questions of survival and solace at a very personal level,'' Maj.
Higgins, 38, told the Memorial Day audience Monday of about 500
persons at the Marine base south of Washington, D.C.
   Many of the base's visitors came to visit the graves of family
members. Some placed flowers on the graves and others said they
came to hear Maj. Higgins speak because they admired her courage.
   Maj. Higgins said she has drawn strength from Winston
Churchill's words on honor, courage and good sense, and from a
bracelet she wears with an inscription from the book of Hebrews
which says ``Remember them that are in bonds, as bound with them;
and them which suffer adversity, as being yourselves also in the
body.''
   ``This is my shield,'' said Maj. Higgins, a Pentagon public
affairs officer.
</TEXT>
