<FIRST>r a PM-Houdini'sLegacy     05-30 0646</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Houdini's Legacy,0667</SECOND>
<HEAD>Houdini's Legacy Boosts Hometown Image</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOHN SOLOMON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>APPLETON, Wis. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Appleton simply can't escape the magic of
Harry Houdini, and local boosters hope his legacy of daring escapes
from straitjackets and handcuffs will snare outsiders to his
hometown.
   ``Houdini is our favorite son, there's no doubting that,'' said
businessman Tom Boldt, who is leading the effort to win wider
recognition for Appleton as the magician's hometown.
   Boosters have named a municipal park, an elementary school and a
cafe after Houdini, organized an annual Halloween seance to attempt
to contact his spirit, and set up walking tours and museum exhibits
to foster his memory more than 60 years after his death.
   ``We needed something to get people to stop in Appleton for a
while,'' said museum curator Christopher Miller.
   Previously, the Fox River city of 65,000 was best known as a
stopover for tourists headed to Lake Michigan's Door Peninsula, or
as the hometown of the late Sen. Joseph McCarthy, who was censured
by the Senate in the 1950s.
   ``McCarthy is really not a fun topic. But Houdini is all about
fun,'' Miller said.
   The campaign received a boost earlier this year when businessman
Sydney H. Radner, 69, of Holyoke, Mass., agreed to lease his
collection of Houdini handcuffs, personal letters, billboards,
photographs and personal letters to Miller's Outagamie County
Museum.
   Radner, a magic historian and one-time performer, collected the
artifacts from Houdini's brother, Theo Hardeen, in the 1930s and
1940s.
   Miller selected about 10 percent of Radner's collection for a
permanent two-room Houdini exhibit on the second floor of the
museum. The exhibit opened April 6.
   In a telephone interview from Massachusetts, Radner said Houdini
boostesr have shown the same flare for publicity that the late
magician had.
   ``It's hard to say what he'd be doing today if he were still
alive, but you could be darn sure he would in the top of the news
because that's the type of person he was,'' Radner said. ``Appleton
is doing just that, putting him in the top of the news again.''
   Houdini, whose real name was Erich Weiss, was born April 6,
1874, to Cecilia and Rabbi Mayer Samuel Weiss. His actual
birthplace has been disputed because an 1880 U.S. census form lists
it as Budapest, Hungary.
   Boldt, Radner and other Houdini enthusiasts have found insurance
policies and a death certificate listing Erich's birthplace as
Appleton.
   ``That's not a big thing with me,'' Boldt said. ``What is big
for me is that Houdini consistently throughout his career mentioned
Appleton as his hometown.''
   Houdini lived in Appleton until he was about 9.
   In show business, ``Houdini stayed at the top of the vaudeville
circuit for the entire time, which almost spans 30 years,'' Miller
said. ``When he died, vaudeville died.''
   Houdini died October 31, 1926 in a Detroit hospital, nine days
after he was struck in the stomach while performing in Montreal.
   The Society of American Magicians, which Houdini served as
president, the Houdini Club of Wisconsin in Milwaukee, and the
Houdini Hall of Fame, which opened 18 years ago in Niagara Falls,
kept interest in the man alive.
   Boldt's family construction company received permission in 1985
to build a downtown public park and statue. Houdini Plaza centers
around an abstract six-ton statue called ``Metamorphosis,''
honoring the magician's escape feats.
   The city's efforts gained more attention in 1986 when Boldt
hosted the annual Harry Houdini Halloween Seance. Despite the
services of a professional psychic and artifacts from Radner's
collection, no one has heard from Houdini's spirit.
   But Boldt says that's far from a failure. Houdini had said that
if he died, he wanted relatives and friends to hold a seance each
Oct. 31 to prove that no such spiritual contact can be made.
   ``Every time they fail, it again proves that what Houdini was
doing was correct,'' Boldt said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
