<FIRST>u i PM-Dollar-Gold     05-30 0323</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Dollar-Gold,0340</SECOND>
<HEAD>Dollar Up, Gold Down</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The dollar rose in early European trading today,
but eased slightly following the Deutsche Bundesbank's announcement
of central bank intervention in the market. Gold prices fell.
   Foreign currency dealers said trading remained thin following
Monday's holidays in the United States and Britain.
   The West German central bank confirmed it sold dollars in the
open foreign exchange market early in the session, and said it was
joined by the Bank of Italy and the Bank of England.
   The Bank of Japan intervened in earlier Asian trading and said
it will raise its official discount rate by 0.75 percentage points
to 3.25 percent on Wednesday.
   In Tokyo, where trading ends before Europe's business day
begins, the dollar rose 0.22 yen to a closing 143.10 yen. Later, in
London, it was quoted at 143.45 yen.
   Other dollar rates at midmorning compared with late Monday's
European rates:
   _2.0105 West German marks, up from 2.0101
   _1.7570 Swiss francs, up from 1.7550
   _6.8070 French francs, up from 6.8025
   _2.2683 Dutch guilders, up from 2.2625
   _1,453 Italian lire, down from 1,454
   _1.2078 Canadian dollars, up from 1.2047
   In London, it cost $1.5655 to buy one pound, compared with
$1.5710 late Monday in Europe.
   Gold prices drifted lower in response to the dollar's continuing
strength, bullion dealers said.
   ``The market is very quiet with little investor interest,'' said
one dealer, explaining why the precious metal hadn't encountered
greater selling pressure from the dollar's buoyancy.
   Gold opened in London at a bid price of $362.40 a troy ounce,
down from $363.75 late Friday. At midmorning, the city's five major
bullion dealers fixed a recommended price of $362.10.
   In Zurich, the bid price was $362.35 compared with $363.35 at
midafternoon Monday.
   Earlier, in Hong Kong, gold fell 43 cents to close at a bid
$362.73.
   Silver was quoted in London at a bid price of $5.21 a troy
ounce, down from Friday's $5.27.
</TEXT>
