<FIRST>r i PM-Soviet-NATO     05-30 0339</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Soviet-NATO,0350</SECOND>
<HEAD>Chervov Says Moscow Studying Bush Proposals</HEAD>
<HEAD>With PM-Summit Reaction, Bjt</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MOSCOW (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Soviet military experts are carefully analyzing
President Bush's proposals for troop cuts in Europe, a senior
military spokesman said today after Mikhail S. Gorbachev announced
plans to cut the defense budget.
   Lt. Gen. Nikolai Chervov, a member of the Soviet general staff,
made the comments to the official news agency Tass.
   He was quoted as saying that Bush's proposals to cut U.S.
conventional forces in Western Europe and reach swift East-West
agreement on even deeper cuts by 1993 ``need to be carefully
analyzed.''
   ``We have all long been waiting for the United States to answer
arms proposals put forward by the Soviet Union and other socialist
countries.
   ``Certainly, the United States could not keep silent
indefinitely,'' he was quoted as saying. ``Washington's silence was
beginning to draw criticism in many NATO capitals.''
   He noted that Bush's proposals also included combat aircraft and
helicopter reductions for the first time. Initially, the North
Atlantic Treaty Organization refused to include those weapons
categories in its proposals to the Vienna talks on reducing
conventional arms across Europe.
   Gorbachev today made no direct response to Bush's proposals in a
95-minute speech to the new Congress of People's Deputies.
   But he did acknowledge that the Soviet Union spends $118 billion
on defense, nearly four times what it officially claimed as
recently as October, and pledged spending will be reduced by $15.3
billion by the end of 1991.
   Both superpowers have now proposed specific troop and weapons
reductions, which could set the stage for detailed negotiations at
the Vienna talks rather than continued public diplomacy.
   Moscow has long concealed its true military expenditures,
complicating East-West negotiations on mutual arms reductions. In
October, the official budget for 1989 allocated $32 billion for the
military, the same figure that had been used the previous year.
   Gorbachev said military spending had been frozen in 1987-88,
suggesting that in those years the spending was around the figure
he disclosed today for current defense expenditures.
</TEXT>
