<FIRST>r a PM-Iowa-Truitt     05-30 0469</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Iowa-Truitt,0481</SECOND>
<HEAD>Truitt Wants Apology; Lawyer Wants Congressional Probe</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NORFOLK, Va. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The sailor linked by reports to the
investigation of the USS Iowa disaster says he wants an apology
from the Navy, and a congressman said he plans to inquire how
Kendall L. Truitt was implicated in the fatal blast.
   Rep. Glenn Poshard, D-Ill., said he will grant a request by the
sailor's attorney to investigate the Navy's handling of its probe
as it concerns Truitt, a 21-year-old gunner's mate 3rd class.
   ``There has been tremendous publicity impugning this young
man,'' Poshard said in a telephone interview. ``Somebody had to
give the news media this information. ... If this boy is not
guilty, how is he ever going to recover from this thing? It doesn't
seem appropriate to try someone before the facts are in or in the
press.''
   Meanwhile, Truitt, his wife, Carole, and his attorney, Ellis
Rubin of Miami, went Monday to the Norfolk Naval Base, where the
sailor collected his belongings for a transfer to Mayport, Fla.
   ``I'd like to see a formal apology _ from an identified Navy
spokesman,'' Truitt told reporters outside the gates to the base,
the Iowa's homeport. ``I'm sure this will hurt me in the future and
certainly now. Life will never be the same, I guess, but I'll try
to get it back as close as possible.''
   Accidental causes have not been ruled out in the April 19
explosion that ripped the ship's No. 2 gun turret and killed 47
men, but Navy investigators have reported finding no evidence of
mechanical or electrical problems.
   In recent weeks, news reports based on unnamed sources have said
investigators were examining the relationship between Truitt and
Gunner's Mate Clayton M. Hartwig, 25, who died in the explosion.
   Neither man has been officially named by the Navy as being under
investigation, and Truitt has repeatedly denied any involvement
with the blast.
   A report in The New York Times Monday said investigators now
feel it is unlikely Truitt set off the explosion to kill Hartwig,
who had named Truitt as beneficiary on a $100,000 life insurance
policy. But they say it is possible Hartwig may have set off the
explosion to commit suicide.
   Capt. Paul W. Hanley, an Atlantic Fleet spokesman, said reports
representing the Navy as accusing Truitt or Hartwig are inaccurate.
   ``I emphasize, the Navy has made no allegation, launched no
charges and done nothing to implicate anyone,'' Hanley said.
   Rubin said he was angered with the Navy for hustling his client
on and off the Iowa Monday with no opportunity to visit with
friends or pay respects to fallen comrades.
   ``On this Memorial Day, Kendall Truitt and his wife Carole came
to pay homage to his shipmates who were lost,'' Rubin said. ``He
was not able to do that.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
