<FIRST>d a PM-BRF--GatorHunt     05-30 0122</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-BRF--Gator Hunt,0126</SECOND>
<HEAD>Permit Applications Readied For Annual Hunt</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WEST PALM BEACH, Fla. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The first state alligator hunt in
26 years last September whetted the appetites of thousands of
would-be gator-hunters who can apply starting Thursday for a spot
in a larger hunt this year.
   The hunts help control the state's growing alligator population.
More than a million of the reptiles are believed to range through
state waters.
   The Florida Game and Fresh Water Fish Commission, which will
take permit applications from Thursday through June 15, plans to
raise the number of hunters to between 250 and 260.
   Last year 230 hunters bagged 2,960 alligators. The limit per
hunter will be kept the same as last year at 15.
</TEXT>
