<FIRST>r a PM-Doctor-Fraud     05-30 0475</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Doctor-Fraud,0488</SECOND>
<HEAD>Yugoslav-Born Cancer Specialist Says He is a Political Scapegoat</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ELIZABETH GROAT</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>COLUMBIA, S.C. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A Yugoslav-born cancer specialist
convicted of fraud in Switzerland promised to fight the charges
despite being barred from traveling abroad by a U.S. judge.
   Dr. Rajko Medenica, who became a U.S. citizen last year and
continues his practice from Hilton Head Island, said he will fight
both the Geneva conviction and a 1983 Yugoslavian conviction on
similar charges.
   ``I'm ready to fight, if necessary, for the next 10 or 15
years,'' Medenica told The Associated Press in a telephone
interview from his office on Monday.
   ``But I will fight until the end because this problem, this
dispute between Yugoslavia and the University Hospital in Geneva
... concentrates now on me. I absolutely was used like a
scapegoat.''
   A Swiss jury last week found Medenica, 49, guilty of bilking
Yugoslav social security of some $560,000 while leading a clinic at
a Geneva state hospital. He was sentenced to four years in prison.
   U.S. District Judge Sol Blatt Jr. revoked Medenica's U.S.
passport before the trial, thus prohibiting the doctor from
attending. Blatt said he acted after he learned that Medenica's
patients might be in danger without the doctor's treatment.
   The Swiss government alleged Medenica was responsible for fake
billing while treating patients, including many Yugoslavs, at a
state hospital in Geneva and a private clinic from 1973 through
1981.
   In 1983, he was sentenced in absentia in Yugoslavia to 20 years
in prison on related charges.
   Medenica was released from Swiss investigative custody in 1984
after former South Carolina Gov. John West, whose daughter was
treated for throat cancer by Medenica, persuaded a judge to grant
bond. West also helped raise much of Medenica's $300,000 bail.
   Medenica said Monday that while he agreed with the bills
submitted by the hospital, the Yugoslav general consul and the
hospital arranged the billing system.
   ``All records which concern these (patients) were with the
Yugoslav General Consul. But when these problems appeared in
Switzerland, the General Consul of Yugoslavia closed his door and
left for Yugoslavia and kept all records with him,'' he said.
   The Swiss media has been highly critical of Medenica. A
front-page editorial last week in the Tribune de Geneve accused the
doctor of ``amorality'' and ``unscrupulousness.''
   ``It is catastrophic, because they are not corresponding what I
do for my patients. They never mention that the hospital got 37
million Swiss francs because of my treatments,'' he said of the
media.
   Those testifying in his behalf in Geneva included former world
heavyweight champion boxer Muhammad Ali, who has been treated by
Medenica, and West.
   Medenica received a permanent license to practice medicine in
South Carolina in 1987; the state medical licensing board was aware
of the Yugoslavian conviction and charges pending in Switzerland,
he said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890530-0054 </DOCNO>
