<FIRST>u i PM-Poland-Campaign 1stLd-Writethru   05-30 0722</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Poland-Campaign, 1st Ld - Writethru,a0443,0743</SECOND>
<HEAD>Poland's Most Open Postwar Election Spurs Poster War</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: INSERTS two grafs after 12th, `The Polish-American...' to UPDATE
with Solidarity response to governent accusation; picks up 13th pvs: The
short...</HEAD>
<HEAD>An AP Extra</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DRUSILLA MENAKER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WARSAW, Poland (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Less than a week away from its freest
elections, Communist Poland is papered with Western-style campaign
posters, and authorities are accusing the West of trying to
influence the outcome.
   The red logo of the Solidarity independent labor movement, an
illegal symbol of defiance a few short months ago, is splashed
across posters on shop windows and telephone poles from the capital
to the countryside.
   Communist-backed candidates are putting up their campaign signs,
too.
   From the hasty handout in smudgy type to the color poster of a
smiling candidate and wholesome-looking family, the free-wheeling
poster war for Sunday's vote contrasts sharply with the previously
tame trickle of strictly controlled information.
   Jaws dropped in amazement when the first streetcar rolled
through Warsaw bearing a Solidarity campaign sign with slick
graphics.
   ``This is our main chance, and we must take advantage of it,''
said Anna Dub, who heads Solidarity's publicity effort in Warsaw.
   Under a historic agreement reached last month, opposition
candidates have been allowed to run for all seats in a new, freely
elected 100-member Senate and for 35 percent of the slots in the
existing Sejm, or parliament.
   However, Solidarity had just seven weeks from the day the
government reinstated it after a seven-year ban to organize its
campaign, select candidates and publicize them.
   That campaign has taken a more rancorous tone in its last days,
with the government using the slogan ``Only opposition: that's no
proposition'' to attack Solidarity.
   ``It's beginning to get hot right now,'' Ms. Dub said. ``More
and more attacks in the press, more and more posters in the city.
But we haven't run out of our possibilities yet. And we are
prepared for the last week.''
   On Monday, the government accused the United States and other
Western nations of helping the opposition campaign. In a statement
read on state television, it appealed ``for an immediate halt of
interfering in the electoral campaign by some Western countries.''
   The Polish-American Congress, for example, says it has raised
about $200,000 nationally to support the Solidarity candidates.
   Solidarity responded today by saying that assistance received
from abroad was consistent with Polish law. It accused the
government of twisting the truth to aid its own candidates.
   ``The authors of the (government) statement are well aware of
those facts. But it's not truth that is the point of the statement,
but anti-Solidarity propaganda. They (government) want to scare
those who are undecided,'' the union said in a statement.
   The short campaign timetable had been expected to benefit the
government candidates, who had an organization in place, support of
the state-run media and money. But Solidarity moved quickly.
   Countless volunteers came forward, from squads armed with glue
and brushes placing Solidarity posters even in remote villages to
passers-by who drop off proposed slogans at the Warsaw office.
   Although there is some coverage of Solidarity candidates on
state-run television, the union's weekly television show was barred
May 23.
   Solidarity says it is relying chiefly on posters and leaflets to
publicize its candidates.
   In the capital, it had spent $126,000 going into the last week
of the campaign and planned to finish up by distributing one
leaflet for every 1.5 residents, Ms. Dub said.
   Solidarity has shown both determination and wit in championing
its candidates.
   When some Solidarity posters were torn down, the union responded
with posters in the same place reading: ``Not for tearing down.''
In Polish, that also means, ``It won't wear out.''
   The government candidates claim they have best chance to put
reforms in place. ``We have a realistic program'' and ``With us, it
is surer'' read their posters.
   However, some government candidates have chosen places for their
banners that are unlikely to inspire confidence, such as a Warsaw
renovation project unfinished for nearly a decade.
   And while Solidarity uses its trademark liberally, the Communist
Party posters often leave the candidates' affiliation hazy.
   Wojciech Szymborski, a party worker in charge of the Warsaw
campaign office, said the government wants to be ``more individual
and democratic.''
   Solidarity has suggested it is trying to confuse voters.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
