<DOCNO> AP890530-0058 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-05-30-89 0835EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u i BC-GorbachevExcerpts     05-30 0660</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-Gorbachev Excerpts,2 Takes,0674</SECOND>
<HEAD>Excerpts of Gorbachev's Speech to Congress</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MOSCOW (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Here are excerpts of President Mikhail S.
Gorbachev's speech Tuesday to the Congress of People's Deputies, as
translated by official Radio Moscow:
   THE ECONOMY:
   Naturally we cannot expect immediate changes in the sphere of
life. We must concentrate all of our efforts and attention to, in a
very short period of time, solve the most vital problems. This is
one of the most crucial problems of the Congress and the Supreme
Soviet and the new government, the basis of perestroika in
attaining the transformations in the economic and social sphere.
The idea of working in this field is to turn the economy to the
people, to give proper conditions of living and working to the
people.
   What is the matter, why don't we feel what we have already done,
what is positive? First and foremost because the financial system
has been sort of disintegrated, we have thrown the consumer market
out of balance, creating a shortage of consumer goods.
   This panic evokes dissatisfaction among the people and in our
society.
   We are not living by our means. Our expenditures are higher than
the national income. We have a budget deficit. This is economically
impermissible.
   The rapid growth of consumer goods and services must be
improved, we must supply the people with goods commensurate with
their wages. There are other viewpoints. Some say this problem,
whether we like it or not, must be resolved by applying the market
economy. We do not share such an approach because this immediately
would destroy the entire social system and disrupt the economic
processes in the country.
   We must make full use of all resources, not only in the light,
food, and agriculture industries, but also all sectors of our
economy including engineering, heavy industry and so on, defense
industry.
   In other words, all of our productive capacity must be
reoriented to produce what the people need _ consumer goods.
   ECOLOGY:
   Life also requires a solution to ecological problems. The
situation there is very alarming. In more than 100 cities of the
country, the harmful material in the air is very dangerous. We must
take care of our water resources, the forests.
   Once more I would like to say that all our plans and drafts must
be checked for ecological purity. Also concerning the building of
canals, atomic stations, chemical enterprises, they must be checked
for ecological purity.
   MILITARY AND OTHER BUDGET CUTS:
   We will have to adopt difficult but necesary conditions. We have
to start somewhere, and some things we have to turn down. We must
strictly adhere to the rule that the volume of capital investments
must correspond to the capacities that we have, that is the
material and labor resources. Only in this way can we put an end to
the eruption of construction by the different ministries.
   Another source of resources to improve our social program is to
cut down our military expenditures, to make conversions connected
to the potential of the defense industries for civic needs. For
people who went through the difficult war, defense was of vital
interest, and our Soviet army remains important. But in the world
today there is a possibility to ensure security by political and
diplomatic means. This makes is possible to cut down military
expenditures, to have a new quality of armed forces of the
U.S.S.R., without any detriment to the defense capacity of our
country. In 1989 military expenditures were 77.3 billion rubles
($118 billion). I am announcing this real figure of military
expenditures to the Congress of People's Deputies: 77.3 billion
rubles ($118 billion) for defense. There is a proposal made to
reduce military expenditures already in 1990-1991 by 10 billion
rubles ($15.3 billion), that is by 14 percent, and for the Supreme
Soviet to work out further this complex having in mind our domestic
problems and the tasks of ensuring the defense capacity of our
country.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>MORE</NOTE>
