<FIRST>r i BC-BushTranscript 2ndAdd a0517 05-30 0538</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-Bush Transcript, 2nd Add, a0517,540</SECOND>
<HEAD>BRUSSELS, Belgium: 'til '92.</HEAD>
<TEXT>
   And we have spelled out the procedures for negotiating on NSF _
SNF. And that will come after the agreement on the conventional
forces. And that is the important point.
   I don't believe the lament _ I know we've got a lot of experts
on this side, and I don't want to restrict my questions to those of
us like myself, who are not long-time arms control experts. But I
can tell you that most people in our country don't realize the
imbalance that exists on these conventional forces. And it is
destabilizing.
   And the question is SNF, short-range nuclear forces, where
they've got in terms of launchers _ what, 1,200, or something of
that nature, to our 88 _ why don't they just negotiate _ just
unilaterally reduce to equal numbers? Now, there'd be a good
challenge. So we've got this order set up as to how we're going to
go about it. The alliance has taken a firm position. And so I'm not
going to go into a hypothetical question of that nature.
   Q: On the question of ``partial,'' the word is underlined for
emphasis in the document. Was that done at our behest, or Mrs.
Thatcher's behest, or whose behest?
   Bush: If we can wake up Jim Baker, you'll have to ask him. But I
would simply say there was total agreement on it, and it speaks for
itself. ``Partial'' is partial. And to try to interpret it some
other way misses the boat.
   Q: Mr. President, in light of the fact that you have added
several new weapons categories to the NATO bargaining position ...
the conventional arms talks, is it realistic to suppose that these
talks may be carried out successfully in the brief period of time
that you are now asking?
   Bush: Well, the timetable _ yes, we can meet that timetable.
We've challenged the Soviets to meet us, you might say, the
Alliance. NATO is tasked to be back on September 7th, with our
internals to be farther along. And so I would certainly say yes,
let's do that. We all remember September 7th, don't we?
   Q: Mr. President, you've said that the modernization decision
has been put off until 1992. But you have a commitment to keep the
weapons systems up-to-date. When changes can be made?
   Bush: Not before 1992.
   Q: Mr. President, you've said that your efforts here are not a
public relations battle with Soviet leader Mikhail Gorbachev. But
if this were a battle, who's winning _ yourself or Mr. Gorbachev?
   Bush: Too hypothetical, Ellen, too hypothetical. I've read who
some think is winning, but that was yesterday.
   Q: Do you think that the hammering about your alleged lack of
leadership in the United States should quiet down now as a result
of your performance here?
   Bush: I haven't felt under siege in the United States, because
I've known exactly what we wanted to do. And I made statements to
that effect earlier on, that we were going to have a review and
then have proposals. And we did exactly that. So I will concede
I've read such reports, but they haven't troubled me any.
</TEXT>
