<FIRST>r a PM-MemorialDayRdp 1stLd-Writethru a0489 05-30 0663</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Memorial Day Rdp, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0489,0676</SECOND>
<HEAD>Black Union Soldiers Buried in S.C. as Part of Holiday Observances</HEAD>
<HEAD>With LaserPhotos NWK1, AD1 and WX6</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Inserts one graf after 14th graf, `In a ...,' to add ceremonies
in Chicago area. Picks up in 15th graf, `For many ...'</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DAVID BRIGGS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Black Union soldiers were brought to their final resting place
in South Carolina and Vietnam veterans in Philadelphia preserved a
memorial defaced by vandals as the nation remembered its war dead
in Memorial Day observances.
   ``A lot of people died for our country, and a lot of people are
still dying inside. A little each day, they're dying inside,'' said
Vietnam veteran John Stephens, who attended a memorial service in
Cleveland.
   Americans also took advantage of generally pleasant weather to
celebrate the traditional start of the summer season at parades,
parks, beaches and festivals. An estimated 500,000 people jammed
Los Angeles County beaches, while officials at ``A Taste of
Cincinnati'' reported some 450,000 people attended the three-day
food festival that ended Monday.
   The 47 sailors who died April 19 in an explosion inside one of
the USS Iowa's huge gun turrets were among the honored dead.
President Bush had designated Memorial Day as a national day of
remembrance for the sailors.
   Robert Gedeon prepared a special tribute by placing 47 U.S.
flags on his front lawn in suburban Cleveland.
   ``I always saw Memorial Day as a somber day, but I can't really
describe how bad I feel,'' said Gedeon, who lost his son, Robert
James Gedeon III, in the tragedy. ``It's never going to be the same
around here. Our family is devastated.''
   Emma Bosch, the guest of honor at a parade in New York City,
remembered the 21-year-old son she lost in the Korean War.
   ``I'm proud to be here. I wouldn't miss it. My son is gone 37
years and I've never missed a Memorial Day since I lost him,'' she
said.
   In Beaufort, S.C., Massachusetts Gov. Michael Dukakis placed a
wreath at the graves of 19 Black union soldiers missing in action
since 1863.
   ``The black soldiers of the Massachusetts 54th and 55th
regiments were fighting for their own liberty, to grasp their own
freedom and to ensure both for others of their own race,'' Dukakis
told a crowd of about 4,000.
   The remains of the soldiers, some of whom were from a North
Carolina regiment, were unearthed during road construction two
years ago.
   Veterans in Philadelphia used paint thinner and scrapers to
remove white paint vandals had splashed on the city's Vietnam
Veterans Memorial. Most of the paint was removed before 150 people
gathered for a memorial service.
   ``I know 18 of the guys on these walls _ 18 of them,'' said
Vietnam veteran Buddy Schriver, 50. ``One of them was my next-door
neighbor. You want heroes, here they are.''
   In a brief ceremony at Arlington National Cemetery, a 20-member
military honor guard laid a wreath at the grave of President
Kennedy to mark what would have been his 72nd birthday. In Boston,
the flag flew at half staff at the John F. Kennedy Library.
   In Chicago, more than 100 people gathered at a downtown fountain
dedicated to Vietnam veterans and tossed red and white carnations
into the water. At Fort Sheridan, an Army base north of Chicago,
cannons roared a 21-gun salute; widows, families, soldiers and
veterans laid chrysanthemums and roses along the rows of white
crosses in the cemetery.
   For many, the holiday also was a time for relaxation.
   At Yosemite National Park in the Sierra Nevadas, every
campground and parking space was filled and some arriving motorists
found themselves with a two-hour wait.
   Elsewhere, celebrants packed the Jambalaya Jam festival in
Philadelphia and 700 cyclists participated in the 23rd Annual
Moline Criterium bicycle races in northwestern Illinois.
   While much of the nation enjoyed fair weather, more than 12
inches of snow fell Sunday and Monday at Great Falls in central
Montana.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890530-0063 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-05-30-89 0917EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i BC-BushTranscript 3rdAdd a0525 05-30 1026</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-Bush Transcript, 3rd Add, a0525,1040</SECOND>
<HEAD>BRUSSELS, Belgium: me any.</HEAD>
<TEXT>
   Q: Gorbachev has, apparently for the first time, revealed
specific defense budget figures in Moscow today. He also says he
proposes to cut defense spending by 14 percent over 1990-91. That's
equal to about $17.3 billion. Is that a lot? Is that meaningful?
What do you think about it?
   Bush: Well, this'll help him, this proposal. If he hits our bid,
that should save him a lot of money in the long run, because he has
a disproportionate number of conventional forces. And therein, as
you know, that's where a lot of the expense for defense comes from.
So I don't know, but it sounds like a substantial number to me. But
again, I hadn't seen that.
   I will say this, for those who may wonder what the Soviet
reaction has been. And it's very preliminary, but the initial
contact with our embassy in Moscow was _ I would put fairly
positive. Brent, is that about right?
   Brent Scowcroft (National security adviser): Cautious.
   Bush: Cautious, but wearily (sic) leaning on the side of
interpreting as saying it's positive. In other words, they didn't
really slam the door and come in on a negative vein.
   Q: On that point, Mr. President, wouldn't it seem that if you
want to strike this agreement within even as early as six months,
that there would be a summit meeting with Mr. Gorbachev before the
end of the year?
   Bush: Well, again, I've _ if there was something constructive to
come out of such a meeting, I would certainly be prepared to meet.
And I believe that Secretary Baker has conveyed that to Minister
Shevardnadze.
   Q: Has Mr. Gorbachev responded to your letter of Sunday?
   Bush: No, sir.
   Q: Mr. Bush, you used strong language yesterday about leading
the alliance and leading the world, the free world. That wasn't
your term, but did you feel it was important, if not for yourself,
then for the alliance, for the United States, to assert yourself in
a strong way at this particular summit _ at this time?
   Bush: Yes, I think it is highly important that the United States
to be seen as fully engaged, trying to come up with creative
proposals, and fulfilling its historic leadership responsibilities.
I would like to put it in terms of alliance unity, though, and what
_ all these decisions. There's plenty of room for credit out there,
and I would insist that it's an alliance _ to the degree we got
unanimity, an alliance victory.
   Q: Mr. President, the stress you put on the speed of
negotiations, six months to a year, and a decision can wait till
'92 on ... modernization, are there some progress points, if there
are no negotiations, or progress in the negotiations within a year,
do we re-examine the 1992 deadline?
   Bush: I _ to be honest with you, I don't know the answer to that
question. I expect _ I expect _ huh?
   ... But my own personal view would be that if it became _ if
there were some dramatic change somewhere that changed the thesises
that underline this agreement, that we'd want to review things. But
I'm not predicting that. I want to see it go forward.
   Q: Following ``tangible implementation'' _ that's being read as
obviously not complete implementation. Could you tell us how far
``tangible'' is?
   Bush: No, I can't tell you how far it is. But it has to be so
that you and I would look at it and we'd both agree that there had
been sincere implementation.
   Q: Mr. President, in the comprehensive context, you state that
ground-based missiles will be needed as far as can be foreseen.
Now, even though the modernization decision has been put off, is
there any alternative to modernizing this missile?
   Bush: Is there any alternative to modernizing it? We will cross
that bridge in 1992.
   Q: As you know, Mr. Gorbachev is coming to Bonn soon, and his
operative style has been to try to up the ante when the U.S. makes
a proposal. On your conventional arms proposal, do you think you've
gone down as far as the West can safely go in reducing conventional
forces? And can you go no further than what you proposed yesterday?
   Bush: I see no reason about talking about further cuts and
further reductions when we have just tabled a sound proposal that
addresses ourselves to this enormous imbalance. So I just would
defer on that.
   Q: Mr. President, you were criticized early on for a slow start.
Now this proposal is being described as bold; you yourself said
``revolutionary.'' I wonder if there's any element of ``I told you
so'' in your attitude now to the reaction to this proposal.
   Bush: Not really. Not really. No, this is _ I'm not going to get
into that game with Congress or anyone else.
   Q: Mr. President, looking ahead, what impact do you think your
proposals will have on U.S.-Soviet relations, and specifically on
strategic arms talks?
   Bush: I _ I hope that they have a _ that these proposals have an
ameliorating effect, that things will get only better. I think it's
a serious proposal. I think they see a solid, united alliance, and
that is important in this. And so I would hope that it would have a
good effect on whatever follows on _ in strategic arms reduction
talks follow on.
   I have never doubted _ I've never questioned whether Gorbachev
knew that we were serious and wanted to move forward with him. I've
read speculation on this, but I have reason to believe that he
knows that we have been serious, taking our time to formulate
proposals. I do think that this one will be tangible evidence of
this.
   And so I hope it would lead to _ if a conventional forces talks
can be catalytic for strategic talks, so be it. But I hope that the
seriousness of all of this and the unity of the alliance will be
persuasive to him, to make him know that we do want to go forward.
</TEXT>
