<FIRST>r a PM-PipelineExplosion     05-30 0388</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Pipeline Explosion,0400</SECOND>
<HEAD>City to Fight Pipeline Return</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SAN BERNARDINO, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A few dozen people ended nearly a
week in exile and returned to a neighborhood devastated by a
pipeline explosion, while the city promised a court battle to shut
down the line.
   About 30 of the approximately 170 families evacuated received
permission to return home Monday, police Officer John Montecino
said. By late Monday, only 13 of the 30 families returned to the
area, walking past signs that read: ``Enter at Your Own Risk, City
of San Bernardino.''
   City Attorney James Penman said the city would go to San
Bernardino Superior Court today, seeking a temporary restraining
order to prevent the 14-inch line from reopening.
   However, it's unclear whether the court would have jurisdiction,
he said, because several federal agencies are responsible for
monitoring the line.
   Thursday's explosion killed two people, damaged or destroyed 15
homes and forced 270 people to flee.
   The blast came after pipeline owners had declared the line safe,
despite its position directly under the site of a May 12 train
derailment that killed four and demolished a row of houses.
   Investigators are focusing on the possibility that the train
wreck damaged the pressurized line operated by locally based Calnev
Pipe Line Co.
   Angry city officials have challenged the company, hoping to get
the line routed away from houses.
   But over the weekend, Calnev's parent company announced it will
rebuild the damaged pipeline in the same location, using insulated,
safety-reinforced pipe.
   A two-hour discussion of the matter was held Monday between
representatives of the parent firm, Chicago-based GATX Terminals
Inc., along with Southern Pacific railroad officials and city
negotiators, Penman said. More talks were scheduled today, he added.
   ``We basically explained that we want the line moved west of the
railroad tracks'' and away from the houses that were destroyed or
endangered, Penman said.
   The pipeline owners have argued the move would keep the pipeline
shut down for too long.
   ``The pipeline is very critical to the national defense
system,'' said GATX President Robert Claypoole, noting that the
line supplies Air Force bases in California and Nevada.
   U.S. District Judge David Williams has signed a temporary
restraining order barring the city from interfering with repair or
replacement of the line, which moves gasoline, diesel and jet fuel
to southern Nevada.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
