<FIRST>r i PM-Vietnam-Amerasians     05-30 0210</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Vietnam-Amerasians,0217</SECOND>
<HEAD>Doctor Says Vietnam Demands Money to Allow Treatment of Amerasians</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BANGKOK, Thailand (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Vietnamese officials have demanded that
an American doctor pay them $130,000 before vaccinating Amerasian
children in Vietnam, the doctor said today.
   Dr. Charles Mitchell of Maui, Hawaii, said the Vietnamese
government backed off an earlier agreement to let him treat the
children of U.S. servicemen and Vietnamese mothers in Ho Chi Minh
City.
   Mitchell is the medical director of FACES, a private
Hawaii-based organization dedicated to helping homeless Amerasians
in Vietnam and speeding their resettlement in the United States.
Earlier this year, FACES opened a shelter for Vietnamese-American
children in Ho Chi Minh City.
   Mitchell said that in March he vaccinated 41 Amerasian children
in the city, which formerly was known as Saigon. At the time, Tran
Van Nhiem, of Vietnam's Department of Labor, Social Welfare and
Disabled Veterans, gave Mitchell written authorization to continue
the program.
   But when Mitchell returned two weeks ago, Nhiem demanded
$130,000 to build a children's shelter, Mitchell said in an
interview in Bangkok. Nhiem offered no explanation for his change
of mind, Mitchell said.
   Mitchell said he was uncertain where his program stood but he
would return in a few months to try to pursue the work.
</TEXT>
