<FIRST>r a PM-HolidayTraffic 1stLd-Writethru a0513 05-30 0226</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Holiday Traffic, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0513,0229</SECOND>
<HEAD>More Than 400 Killed in Memorial Day Weekend Traffic Accidents</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Subs 3rd graf to CORRECT end of period from Sunday to Monday.</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Traffic accidents over the long Memorial Day
weekend claimed the lives of more than 400 people, according to
unofficial reports from police throughout the nation.
   The National Safety Council had estimated that between 370 and
470 people would be killed on the nation's streets and highways
over the three-day weekend.
   The holiday travel period began officially at 6 p.m. local time
Friday and ended at midnight local time Monday.
   During that period, 415 people were reported killed in traffic
accidents.
   The highest state toll was reported in California, where 44
people lost their lives. Another 30 fatalities were reported in
Florida, followed by 29 in Ohio and 25 in Texas.
   Five states reported no fatalities. They were: Alaska, Delaware,
Maine, North Dakota and South Dakota.
   Last year, there were 404 traffic fatalities during the Memorial
Day weekend. The Memorial Day record was set in 1968 when 629
people were killed over a four-day weekend. The three-day record of
597 was set in 1969.
   Although gasoline prices have risen dramatically nationwide in
the the past two months, the safety council said it was unable to
say whether that kept more people off the highways.
</TEXT>
