<FILEID>AP-NR-05-30-89 0937EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i PM-Israel     05-30 0594</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Israel,0612</SECOND>
<HEAD>Arab Killed in Lebanon, Jewish Students Reported Involved in Rampage</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ALLYN FISHER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>KIFIL HARITH, Occupied West Bank (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Israeli soldiers and
allied Lebanese militiamen today killed a Palestinian guerrilla who
was trying to slip into Israel from southern Lebanon, the army said.
   Also today, Israel radio reported that students from a Jewish
study center were involved in a West Bank rampage in which a
Palestinian girl died.
   The girl was the 500th Palestinian to die since the uprising
against Israeli occupation of the West Bank and Gaza Strip began on
Dec. 7, 1987. Twenty-two Israelis have died.
   In the Jewish settlement of Ariel, authorities announced that
Palestinians who work in the settlement will have to wear tags
identifying them as ``foreign workers.''
   About 400 Palestinians work in Ariel, a settlement of more than
8,000 Israelis. The Palestinians are mainly residents of villages
in the West Bank, which has been occupied by Israel since its
capture from Jordan in the 1967 Middle East War.
   In today's clash in south Lebanon, an Israeli army official said
a guerrilla dressed in military camouflage was spotted east of the
town of Marjayoun. Army sources, speaking on condition of
anonymity, said the victim was a Palestinian trying to infiltrate
Israel.
   The man was wounded in an exchange of fire with the joint patrol
of Israeli soldiers and Israeli-backed militiamen of the South
Lebanon army, then killed by the militiamen, said the official, who
cannot be identified under briefing rules.
   On Sunday, two guerrillas were killed and two wounded and
captured in Israel's self-proclaimed security zone in southern
Lebanon after several Katyusha rockets were fired into the Israeli
border town of Metulla. An infant was slightly wounded in the
rocket attack.
   The security zone was set up by Israel in 1985 to protect its
northern frontier.
   Also today, a Palestinian man was reported killed in the
occupied West Bank, but there were conflicting reports about his
death.
   The family of the victim, 25-year-old Issa Qudeh of the West
Bank village of Tell, told a Nablus hospital late Monday that he
was shot. But residents of the village said Qudeh died in a fall
from his tractor.
   In the West Bank village of Kifil Harith, villagers said about
30 Jewish settlers went on a rampage Monday that ended in the
shooting death of a teen-age Palestinian girl. The victim, Ibtisam
Abdel Rahim Bozieh, was initially described as being 16, but her
family said she was 13.
   Israel radio said the assault apparently was carried out by
students from a Jewish study center who claimed they were stoned
when they tried to visit the Tomb of Joshua, a site in the village
holy to Jews and Moslems.
   Police officials at the Nablus police station declined comment.
No arrests have been announced.
   The girl's mother, Samia Bozieh, told The Associated Press her
daughter was alone in a front room when the shooting began. The
two-story house is about 30 yards from the tomb.
   ``We heard some shots,'' Mrs. Bozieh said. She said her daughter
said ``Mommy I'm shot here'' and clutched her chest before falling
to the floor.
   Villagers said some Jewish settlers fired wildly in the air with
automatic rifles. Two other villagers were wounded and several
animals also were shot, they said.
   The villagers also said the raiders threw firebombs, burning
wheat fields and olive groves and damaging two houses.
   The rampage in Kifil Harith was the latest in a series of
retaliatory actions by settlers for stonings or firebombings of
Israel-owned cars.
</TEXT>
