<FILEID>AP-NR-05-30-89 0950EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i PM-Iran-Rebels     05-30 0406</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Iran-Rebels,0419</SECOND>
<HEAD>Iranian Rebels on Alert After Khomeini Illness</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By SALAH NASRAWI</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BAGHDAD, Iraq (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Iranian rebels in Iraq were put on alert
following reports that Ayatollah Ruhollah Khomeini's health was
deteriorating, rebel leaders said today.
   Hussein Mehdavi, a senior official of the Mujahedeen Khalq, or
People's Holy Warriors group, told The Associated Press the
movement's military force, the National Liberation Army of Iran,
went on alert Sunday.
   ``The NLA is in a state of military vigilance and will respond
to any new situation that arises from Khomeini's death,'' he said
in an interview at the Mujahedeen's headquarters in the Iraqi
capital.
   The rebels claimed Monday that Khomeini, 86, suffered a heart
attack Saturday while recovering from surgery to stop intestinal
bleeding.
   Tehran Television said Monday that Iran's revolutionary
patriarch suffered a ``mild heart complication'' over the weekend
but was fine and was recovering well from the surgery he underwent
May 23.
   The television report gave no details of the cardiac problem but
said the condition had been ``relieved.''
   Khomeini suffered a heart attack in 1980 and is reported to have
had another one in 1986.
   Mehdavi, the Mujahedeen's ``foreign minister,'' did not say what
the Iranian rebels would do if Khomeini died. But he said the force
that fought alongside the Iraqis against Iran in the latter stages
of the eight-year Iran-Iraq war had been trained to intervene in
Iran and overthrow the Tehran government.
   Mujahedeen leader Massoud Rajavi met with his military
commanders at a base near the Iranian border Saturday. Mujahedeen
sources said they discussed military and political options that
would be opened by Khomeini's death.
   The rebels' military strength never has been disclosed. Last
year it was estimated it had more than 15,000 troops, along with
tanks, artillery and other heavy weapons.
   Weeks before the war cease-fire took effect Aug. 20, the force
launched its biggest operation into western Iran, reaching the city
of Bakhtaran, 90 miles inside the country, before withdrawing
across the Iraqi border.
   The Mujahedeen claimed the operation was a major victory. But
Iran claimed the rebels were driven back with heavy losses.
Nonetheless, the rebel army's ability to thrust so deep into Iran
alarmed Tehran.
   The Mujahedeen were allied with Khomeini during the 1979
revolution that toppled Shah Mohammad Reza Pahlavi. But radicals
turned on the Mujahedeen and other leftist and liberal factions in
1980-81, killing and imprisoning tens of thousands of people.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
