<FIRST>r i PM-Colombia-Bomb     05-30 0225</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Colombia-Bomb,0231</SECOND>
<HEAD>Head of Colombian Secret Police Escapes Injury in Car-Bomb Attack</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BOGOTA, Colombia (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The head of the country's secret police
today escaped injury in a car-bomb attack that killed at least
three people and injured 35, authorities said.
   The bomb, planted in a white Chevrolet Monza, exploded in an
affluent northern neighborhood of Bogota as Gen. Miguel Maza
Marquez passed in his bullet-proof official car, police said.
   Maza Marquez heads the Administrative Department of Security,
the Colombian secret police. Nicknamed ``Kojak'' by his countrymen,
Maza Marquez has been aggressive in investigating the country's
billion-dollar cocaine trafficking industry.
   No one immediately claimed responsibility for the attack.
   Police said the bomb apparently was detonated by remote control.
It reduced the Monza to twisted metal, damaged several buildings
and shattered windows as far as three blocks away. The size or type
of bomb were not immediately known.
   According to police, the bomb killed one of Maza Marquez's
bodyguards. Also killed were a police officer and a woman who
happened to be passing when the explosion occurred.
   Maza Marquez suffered only bruises on the ribs and chest,
authorities at a nearby military hospital said. Seven of his
bodyguards were injured, three of them seriously, police said.
   According to the Bogota National Radio Chain, 35 people were
treated for injuries. Many were cut by flying glass.
</TEXT>
