<FIRST>r i PM-BoatPeople     05-30 0240</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Boat People,0245</SECOND>
<HEAD>Vietnamese Refugees Put on Island Without Shelter</HEAD>
<HEAD>With PM-Asia-Refugees</HEAD>
<DATELINE>HONG KONG (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The government put 109 Vietnamese refugees on a
remote island without shelter today in an effort to cope with the
surging numbers of arriving boat people, officials said.
   ``We have had over 2,300 arrivals over the past three days. Our
accomodation resources have simply been overwhelmed,'' said Hong
Kong refugee coordinator Mike Hanson.
   Officials said 745 boat people arrived today and 109 were towed
to Tai A Chau, an island 20 miles southwest of Hong Kong, because
other refugee facilities were filled.
   Hanson said the boat people would be staying in their boat or on
the dock at Tai A Chau. ``There is one school building which some
people may be able to use, but I think most will not be able to
have covered accomodations,'' he said.
   Hanson said the boat people would remain on the island until the
government could find a place to process them.
   In June, Hong Kong adopted a screening policy that treats all
incoming Vietnamese boat people as illegal immigrants subject to
repatriation unless they can prove they fled political persecution.
   But the policy has not curbed the mounting arrivals of
Vietnamese. For the first five months in 1989, 13,182 boat people
have arrived at the British colony.
   Under international pressure, Vietnam has agreed to attend an
international conference on Indochinese refugees in Geneva on June
13-14.
</TEXT>
