<SECOND>PM-BRF--Prison Incident,0158</SECOND>
<HEAD>Inmates Create Stir Over Food</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CRYSTAL CITY, Texas (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   For the second time in less than a
week, prisoners at privately run detention centers in Texas
squabbled over food and demanded to meet with prison officials.
   One inmate suffered a minor cut on his hand when inmates began
banging on their cells at the Zavala County Detention Center Monday
afternoon, assistant prison administrator L.B. Gamble said.
   Gamble said the disturbance, which lasted about 30 minutes, was
a minor incident. ``They just didn't like what they had to eat
today,'' Gamble said, adding that he was unsure what was on the
menu.
   The disturbance ended, he said, when he agreed to talk to some
inmates.
   On May 23, federal inmates protesting the food and other
conditions at the privately run Eden Detention Center in Eden
refused to return to their dormitories overnight and negotiated
with authorities in the courtyard May 24.
