<FILEID>AP-NR-05-30-89 1048EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i PM-Taiwan     05-30 0313</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Taiwan,0321</SECOND>
<HEAD>Lee Huan Confirmed as Premier</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By SHIRLEY LAI</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>TAIPEI, Taiwan (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Legislators today confirmed veteran
politician Lee Huan as Taiwan's new premier to succeed Yu Kuo-hwa,
who had been criticized for his cautious approach to economic and
political reforms.
   Lee, educated at Columbia University in New York and South
Korea's Dangkook University, is among the most liberal senior
officials of the governing Nationalist Party and takes over as
Taiwan is trying to gain international recognition.
   Younger Nationalist legislators considered his predecessor, the
75-year-old Yu, a liability as the party prepared for December
parliamentary elections. Yu had governed since 1984 and nominated
Lee to succeed him.
   Today's vote in Parliament, where Nationalists hold 254 of the
289 seats, was 217 to 24. Nine votes were declared invalid and 39
legislators were absent.
   All 12 members of the opposition Democratic Progressive Party
voted against Lee's confirmation because they said they first
wanted him to outline his political plans to Parliament.
Legislative officials said Cabinet appointees seldom address the
house before being confirmed.
   Lee, 72, was nominated by his party, whose parliamentary
majority ensured his confirmation.
   He is expected to announce a 25-member Cabinet on Wednesday amid
reports he will make only minor changes. The new premier, who has
been secretary-general of the governing party since 1987, helped
groom a number of incumbent Cabinet ministers. He helped Chiang
Ching-kuo end 38 years of martial law in Taiwan two years ago.
   Newspapers had reported that Lee planned to include a member of
the Democratic Progressive Party in his Cabinet, but the press said
today he changed his mind after objections were raised.
   The appointment would have been unprecedented. The Nationalists
have not included an opponent in a Cabinet since they retreated to
Taiwan in 1949 after losing a civil war in China. Since then, they
have dominated the island's politics.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
