<DOCNO> AP890530-0083 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-05-30-89 1048EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a PM-MosaicsTrial 1stLd-Writethru a0533 05-30 0467</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Mosaics Trial, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0533,0475</SECOND>
<HEAD>Art World Keeping Eye on Indiana Court This Week ^EDs: SUBS 9th graf
to clarify church and republic of Cyprus are suing, sted Turkish Cypriots,
who have filed to intervene. Picks up in 10th graf: `Goldberg's lawyer...</HEAD>
<DATELINE>INDIANAPOLIS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A trial over ownership of four sixth-century
Byzantine mosaics, considered to be worth millions of dollars,
begins today in a case that could have serious impact on art work
considered national treasures.
   On one side are lawyers representing the Greek Orthodox Church
of Cyprus and the Republic of Cyprus, and on the other local art
dealer Peg L. Goldberg.
   The mosaics, each about two feet square, are said to have been
chiseled from the interior of a small church in northern Cyprus
sometime before 1982 and are considered some of the oldest
Christian antiquities.
   Experts see the case as a landmark in the growing worldwide
effort by less-developed nations to reclaim and protect national
treasures.
   The mosaics took a circuitous trail from the Mediterranean
island to Indiana, attracting an exotic cast of characters
including reputed international art smugglers and warring Greek and
Turkish Cypriots.
   It was a year ago when Goldberg learned of the mosaics _ tile
portraits of Jesus as a boy, an archangel and the apostles Matthew
and James.
   Goldberg said she fell in love with the mosaics when shown them
in July 1988 in Geneva by a Turk who claimed to be the former state
archaeologist of Turkish-occupied Cyprus. He assured her they had
been legally exported, she said, and she paid $1.2 million for the
four tiles.
   Turkish Cypriot officials deny his credentials and his claim
that the artworks were legally exported.
   The Greek church and the Republic of Cyprus are suing in U.S.
District Court to get them back. The Turkish breakaway state on
Cyprus has filed a motion to intervene in the case.
   Goldberg's lawyer, Joe C. Emerson, says she acted in good faith
and even if the mosaics were stolen, the six-year statute of
limitations in such cases has expired and she is no longer liable
for prosecution.
   He says officials of the church and the Republic of Cyprus are
at fault for failing to properly notify the international community
of the theft.
   Washington lawyer Thomas R. Kline contends that despite
Goldberg's claim of good faith, the merchandise was stolen and
should be returned to its rightful owners in Cyprus.
   Walter Hopps, director of the Menil Collection in Houston, who
last year solved a similar problem through a loan agreement with
Cyprus, said the lawsuit will become a test case.
   He says if the courts uphold Goldberg, ``...then the possibility
exists that millions and millions of dollars worth of plundered
antiquities will pour into the United States. It will be a horrible
precedent.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890530-0084 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-05-30-89 1051EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r w PM-Scotus-Hildwin     05-30 0224</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Scotus-Hildwin,220</SECOND>
<HEAD>Court Upholds Judge's Ability To Impose Death Sentence</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A state death penalty law does not have to
require juries, instead of judges, to make the specific findings
authorizing imposition of capital punishment, the Supreme Court
ruled today.
   By a 7-2 vote, the justices upheld the death sentence of Florida
death row Paul Hildwin, convicted of a 1985 murder.
   Hildwin had argued that he was denied a fair sentencing trial
because jurors who recommended the death sentence did not make
specific findings of any ``aggravating circumstances.''
   The sentencing judge, however, found four such aggravationg
factors and no mitigating ones in imposing Hildwin's sentence.
   The nation's highest court previously upheld Florida's
sentencing system, ruling in 1984 that a jury trial is not required
on the life-or-death decision.
   ``The Sixth Amendment (guaranteeing fair trials) does not
require that the specific findings authorizing the imposition of
the sentence of death be made by the jury,'' the court ruled today
in an unsigned opinion.
   Justices William J. Brennan and Thurgood Marshall, who oppose
capital punishment under all circumstances, dissented.
   Hildwin was sentenced to death for the Sept. 9, 1985 strangling
of Vronzette Cox. Police said she was raped and killed, and her
body locked inside the trunk of a car left in some Hernando County
woods.
   The case is Hildwin vs. Florida, 88-6066.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
