<FIRST>r i PM-RightsConference     05-30 0453</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Rights Conference,0467</SECOND>
<HEAD>Bulgaria Blames Foreigners for Ethnic Unrest</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ELAINE GANLEY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>PARIS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Bulgaria, seeking to head off criticism of its
treatment of its Turkish minority, took the offensive at an
international human rights conference today and blamed foreigners
for the ethnic unrest.
   Bulgaria is among 35 nations, including the United States,
attending the Conference on the Human Dimension, in which nations
will review human rights progress and take to task countries
accused of abuses.
   Bulgaria, Romania, Czechoslovakia and East Germany are expected
to be singled out during the monthlong conference.
   In one of the first speeches, Bulgarian Foreign Minister Petar
Mladenov went on the offensive, accusing ``foreign circles'' of
being behind recent disturbances in his country.
   Officials in Bulgaria say at least three ethnic Turks have been
killed in clashes with Bulgarian security forces, but Turkish
sources put the number as high as 30.
   Mladenov did not identify a country or group. But the Bulgarian
delegation made available the text of a speech by President Todor
Zhivkov saying ``certain circles in the Republic of Turkey'' have
launched a ``continuously escalating anti-Bulgarian campaign.''
   ``This policy represents a gross interference in the internal
affairs of a sovereign state,'' Zhivkov said.
   The Bulgarian president, whose speech was broadcast Monday,
called on Turkey to open its borders to all ``Bulgarian Moslems''
who want to go there.
   The violence stems from ethnic Turks' opposition to a Bulgarian
assimilation campaign, which includes forcing the country's 900,000
ethnic Turks to change their Moslem names.
   Bulgaria has been deporting ethnic Turks it considers
undesirable. An estimated 300 have been forced to leave, and most
have been sent to Austria and Yugoslavia. Scores have been picked
up by Turkish airliners for resettlement in Turkey.
   The conference that officially opened today is the first of
three dealing with human rights and mandated by the Vienna review
meeting of the Conference on Security and Cooperation in Europe,
which ended in January.
   The conference is made up of all European countries except
Albania, and includes the United States and Canada. All signed the
1975 Helsinki Final Act.
   Unlike previous Helsinki human rights follow-up meetings, the
Paris conference is to examine how well human rights commitments
have been implemented.
   It will also be a testing ground for a mechanism worked out in
Vienna to call attention to human rights abuses within the 35
countries.
   ``In this century, far more people ... have been killed by
violations of human rights than in all the wars of this century,''
Morris B. Abram, who heads the U.S. delegation, said Monday.
   Abram said that Romania was in ``the most flagrant violation of
any of the states signatory to ... the promises of Helsinki.''
</TEXT>
