<FIRST>r i PM-Japan-Politics     05-30 0231</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Japan-Politics,0243</SECOND>
<HEAD>Resistance to Uno Surfaces and May Delay New Government</HEAD>
<DATELINE>TOKYO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Senior politicians today criticized the candidacy
of Foreign Minister Sousuke Uno for prime minister, saying he may
not win back public confidence in the government.
   Voters may not accept Uno because of his close political ties to
former prime minister Yasuhiro Nakasone, under whose 1982-87 tenure
the Recruit Co. influence-pedling scandal occurred, according to
party elder Zenko Suzuki.
   The affair led to public outry against the government.
   The ruling Liberal Democratic Party was expected on Thursday to
choose Uno to succeed Prime Minister Noboru Takeshita, who has said
he will resign to take responsibility for the scandal. Parliament
was to confirm the party choice Friday.
   But an apparent lack of consensus on Uno's candidacy meant the
decision might be delayed, officials said.
   Former Prime Minister Takeo Fukuda suggested today the party
should be ruled by a group rather than one person. Former Deputy
Prime Minister Susumu Nikaido said the party should not hurry in
choosing the next leader, news reports said.
   Takeshita reportedly agreed to examine the proposals and meet
again with party leaders.
   Recruit Co., an information and publishing conglomerate,
allegedly sought government favors through huge political donations
and bargain-priced share sales. Nakasone, Takeshita and ruling
party secretary-general Shintaro Abe are among those linked to the
scandal. Seventeen politicians, bureaucrats and businessmen have
been charged.
</TEXT>
