<FIRST>r i PM-Soviet-NATO     05-30 0231</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Soviet-NATO,0237</SECOND>
<HEAD>Shevardnaze Says Bush Proposal Step in Right Direction</HEAD>
<HEAD>With PM-Summit Rdp, Bjt</HEAD>
<DATELINE>PARIS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Soviet Foreign Minister Eduard Shevardnadze today
called President Bush's proposals for troop cuts in Europe a
serious step in the right direction.
   In his address to the first day of an East-West conference on
human rights, Shevardnadze said the Soviet delegation at Vienna
talks on conventional disarmament would be ready to discuss the
ideas in detail.
   Bush has proposed cutting American and Soviet troops to 275,000
on each side and negotiating new ceilings for tanks, aircraft and
other conventional weapons on the European continent.
   ``We consider the declaration made by President Bush in Brussels
as a serious and important step in the right direction,''
Shevardnadze said.
   Shevardnadze said the Soviet Union had been calling on the
United States to reduce troops and arms in Europe ``in the context
of a reduction of a general level of confrontation on the
continent.''
   In briefer comments to reporters on his arrival, Shevardnaze
said Bush's proposals would be studied carefully.
   But he added, ``It will take time to examine the American
proposals in detail and determine the position of the USSR.''
   Shevardnadze told reporters that Bush's proposal to accelerate
the pace of Vienna negotiations on conventional disarmament was
``attractive,'' but said, ``Only experience will tell how much time
it will take to arrive at mutually acceptable solutions.''
</TEXT>
