<FIRST>u w PM-Scotus-Search 1stLd-Writethru a0560 05-30 0581</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Scotus-Search, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0560,550</SECOND>
<HEAD>Court Lets Stand Decision That Drug Shipment Searched Unlawfully</HEAD>
<HEAD>EDs: SUBS 11th graf pvs bgng, `The police,' with 1 graf to show that
Leichty was a student at Harvey Mudd College, one of the Claremont Colleges
group</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JAMES H. RUBIN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Supreme Court today refused to reinstate
the conviction of a California man who admitted he tried illegally
to ship a drug via air freight.
   The court, without comment, left intact a ruling that police
unlawfully searched the shipment.
   California prosecutors asked the high court to revive Stephen
Edward Leichty's conviction.
   He pleaded no defense to possessing methamphetamine with intent
to sell the drug, and was sentenced to 120 days in jail and three
years probation. Methamphetamine is a stimulant that may not be
sold without a prescription.
   A California appeals court threw out Leichty's conviction last
November.
   The charges against him stemmed from the suspicions of Michael
Brooks, supervisor at an air freight facility at Ontario Airport in
California.
   In September 1986, Brooks smelled ether in an empty five-gallon
plastic container shipped to Leichty. Brooks told Leichty that
shipping ether on an airplane is dangerous and requires special
precautions.
   A few weeks later, Brooks said Leichty came to the terminal with
a package for shipment. The air cargo supervisor said Leichty
seemed to be very nervous and wore dark glasses inside the poorly
lit terminal.
   Brooks, fearing the package might be dangerous, opened it up and
found two soda bottles filled with a yellow liquid. The bottles
were packed in paper and potato chips, possibly to cover up the
liquid's odor. Handwritten labels on the bottles said they
contained model airplane oil.
   Brooks called the police, who conducted inconclusive tests of
the substance at the airport. The bottles then were taken to a Los
Angeles police laboratory where the substance was identified as
methamphetamine oil.
   The police then obtained a warrant to search the dormitory room
of Leichty _ a student at Harvey Mudd College, the all
science-oriented member of the Claremont Colleges group in
Claremont, Calif. _ and found chemical ingredients and apparatus
used to make methamphetamine.
   Leichty admitted he was manufacturing the drug.
   The state appeals court that overturned Leichty's conviction
ruled that police violated his rights when they tested the liquid
at the police laboratory without a court-issued search warrant.
   The appeals court said the police lab tests were not designed
strictly to identify only contraband, as were the less
sophisticated tests at the airport. The police lab tests could
``have revealed the identity of the contents even if it were a
substance in which defendant had a legitimate privacy interest,''
the appeals court said.
   The Supreme Court in 1984 reinstated cocaine-possession
convictions against a Minnesota couple in a similar case. The
convictions stemmed from the suspicions of an air freight worker
who looked inside a damaged carboard box addressed to the couple.
   But the California appeals court said in Leichty's case the
police lab tests were broader than those used to identify cocaine
in the Minnesota case.
   ``There is no evidence that the (Los Angeles police) lab tests
were limited only to those which would reveal the presence of
contraband drugs,'' the state court said.
   The California attorney general's office urged the justices to
use the case to allow police to search without a warrant whenever a
package shipped by a private company is ``obviously contraband.''
   The case is California vs. Leichty, 88-1666.
</TEXT>
