<DOCNO> AP890530-0097 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-05-30-89 1223EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i AM-Soviet-Legislature     05-30 0503</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Soviet-Legislature,0522</SECOND>
<HEAD>Congress, Supreme Soviet to Have New Legislative Oversight</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Soviet, Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ALISON SMALE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MOSCOW (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   President Mikhail S. Gorbachev on Tuesday outlined
a system of legislative oversight that would invest the full-time
legislature and national parliament with broad powers to change the
constitution, question government officials and review state
spending.
   He also said the new legislature, called the Supreme Soviet,
should create a commission that would act as a constitutional court
to ensure the transition to a nation ruled by law and respectful of
individual rights.
   The powers of the new part-time parliament _ the Congress of
People's Deputies _ and of the Supreme Soviet appear aimed at
creating expert, policy-making bodies independent of the Communist
Party bureaucrats who have run the country for decades and whom
Gorbachev blames for slowing his reforms.
   In his speech to the Congress, Gorbachev foresaw the following
powers for the 542-seat Supreme Soviet:
   _ Review of state economic plans and the budget.
   _ Review of appointments to key posts and ambassadorships.
   _ Calling government ministers to account for mistakes.
   _ Ratification of foreign treaties.
   _ Review of privileges for the elite.
   _ Keeping deputies in the 2,250-seat Congress informed of its
activities.
   _ Making and reviewing laws, while passing key legislation to
the Congress or even to the nation for confirmation or rejection by
referendum.
   Gorbachev said the aim of his reforms was to create a system
combining features of the soviets _ the councils set up after the
1917 Bolshevik Revolution _ with experience culled from Western
parliamentary systems.
   For this to work, he said, deputies must receive the practical
means to maintain contact with voters.
   However, he did not specify whether the deputies would be given
offices and full-time staff like members of Western legislatures,
nor did he say how much public access there would be to committee
reviews of economic and state policy.
   Many other details of the reform of the Soviet system, including
the makeup of the committee for constitutional compliance, or
constitutional court, as well as plans to delegate power to the
republics and self-governing regions, were only vaguely outlined by
Gorbachev.
   His speech was filled with a sense of caution instilled by
recognition of mistakes made in the reform effort, the work
involved in drafting or changing at least 50 comprehensive laws,
and the massive economic, ethnic and social woes of his country.
   Reformers such as Boris N. Yeltsin and sociologist Tatyana
Zaslavskaya pronounced the speech too cautious, saying more radical
solutions were needed.
   But some deputies immediately took up his call to question
government ministers and senior planners suspected of failing to
implement his economic reforms to date.
   Arkady P. Yanenko, head of the engineering institute in the
Siberian city of Novosibirsk, criticized the performance of the
Soviet government during the debate period that followed
Gorbachev's speech.
   ``Maybe there is an increase in supplies in the restaurant for
the State Committee of Statistics,'' he quipped, ``but they haven't
got down to us.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
