<FILEID>AP-NR-05-30-89 1250EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i AM-Japan     05-30 0408</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Japan,0422</SECOND>
<HEAD>Takshita Fails to Win Support For Successor</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ERIC TALMADGE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>TOKYO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The effort by Prime Minister Noboru Takeshita to
name a successor ran into trouble Tuesday as two former leaders of
Japan refused to support his choice.
   In a meeting with Takeshita, former prime ministers Takeo Fukuda
and Zenko Suzuki suggested the posts of prime minister and
president of the governing Liberal Democratic Party be held by
different people _ a departure from party practice.
   ``There can only be one prime minister, but one or several
others should assume leadership of the party,'' Fukuda said after
the meeting.
   He said no single person can reverse the crisis caused by an
influence-peddling scandal that has forced Takeshita's resignation.
   Fukuda said Takeshita, who reportedly favors Foreign Minister
Sousuke Uno for both posts, promised to consider the proposal.
   The Liberal Democrats, who have ruled Japan since the party was
founded 34 years ago, have watched the the affair plunge party
popularity to unprecedented lows and fear sharp losses in summer
elections for half the upper house of parliament.
   Takeshita has indicated he hopes to leave office this week.
   But Uno's candidacy was challenged by senior leaders who say he
may not be able to win back public confidence because of his close
political ties to former Prime Minister Yasuhiro Nakasone, under
whose 1982-87 tenure the scandal occurred. The outcry forced
Nakasone to resign from the party Sunday.
   The Executive Council, which sets Liberal Democratic policy,
Tuesday ordered measures to salvage the party's damaged image.
   It said profits from the scandal should be passed on to Japanese
society in an as-yet undefined way, and that members linked to the
affair should be denied government or party posts for an
unspecified period.
   The package left implementation of many reforms to each
politician's discretion.
   ``This is not going to satisfy the people,'' said governing
party legislator Tsuneo Suzuki.
   Osamu Yatabe of the Japan Socialist Party, who led the
parliamentary investigation into the scandal, asked: ``Who do you
think will welcome getting the dirty Recruit money back? The only
way to take responsibility is for all the politicians linked to the
scandal to retire from politics entirely.''
   Recruit Co., an information and publishing conglomerate, is
accused of seeking favors and influence through huge political
donations and bargain-priced share transactions.
   Seventeen people _ two legislators and the rest businessmen and
bureaucrats _ have been charged in the case.
</TEXT>
