<FILEID>AP-NR-05-30-89 1322EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i AM-Zimbabwe     05-30 0381</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Zimbabwe,0391</SECOND>
<HEAD>By-Election Will Test Support For Democracy or One-Party State</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOHN EDLIN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>HARARE, Zimbabwe (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A new political movement that wants to
keep Zimbabwe a multiparty democracy nominated a candidate Tuesday
for a July parliamentary by-election that will be its first test of
popular support.
   The outcome will indicate whether there is a significant
grassroots following for the fledgling Zimbabwe Unity Movement and
its campaign to stop President Robert Mugabe from establishing a
single-party state in one of Africa's few Western-style democracies.
   Mugabe says he will create a one-party government next year by
winning all parliamentary seats. Of the 100 national assembly
legislators only two are in opposition: veteran nationalist
politician Edgar Tekere and businessman Goodson Sithole of the Rev.
Ndabaningi Sithole's splinter Zimbabwe African National Union.
   At the Nomination Court on Tuesday, Harare City Councillor
Ephraim Masawi gave notice he will represent the ruling Zimbabwe
African National Union (Patriotic Front). Businessman Fibion
Mutikori put forward his name for the Unity Movement. They are
contesting the eastern constituency of Dzivaresekwa.
   Tekere, 52, formed the Unity Movement on April 30 after he was
dismissed from the party for denouncing widespread top-level
corruption and accusing party leaders of cultivating a personality
cult around Mugabe. Tekere helped found Mugabe's party in 1963 and
was a member of its policy-making Politburo. He has promised an
honest, democratic and efficient government, and said he will mount
the first challenge to the presidency in national elections to be
held by April 1990 _ the 10th anniversary of Zimbabwe's
independence from Britain.
   Mugabe, who helped fight a bloody seven-year war that led
white-ruled Rhodesia to independence as Zimbabwe, has labeled
Tekere's party ``the joke of the year.''
   But the dissenting nationalist insists he has broad support from
students, labor leaders and peasants disenchanted with corruption,
record unemployment, commodity shortages and inflation.
   The by-election July 4-5 will fill a seat held by Maurice
Nyagumbo, the late senior minister for political affairs who
committed suicide in April after a judicial commission found he was
involved in a racket to buy motor vehicles from a state assembly
plant and sell them at bloated prices.
   Four other Cabinet ministers and a provincial governor resigned
after being linked to the worst scandal to plague Mugabe's
government.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890530-0105 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-05-30-89 1323EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i AM-Korea-US     05-30 0357</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Korea-US,0369</SECOND>
<HEAD>Villagers Attack U.S. Shooting Range</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By C.W. LIM</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SEOUL, South Korea (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Villagers demanding that a U.S. Air
Force bombing range be closed scaled fences and stormed the range,
injuring 10 airmen, military officials said Tuesday.
   About 100 farmers and villagers attacked the Kooni range, about
70 miles southwest of Seoul, on Monday night, said Sgt. Will Baker,
an Air Force spokesman.
   The protesters assaulted military guards with clubs and rocks,
slightly injuring the airmen, he said. A Korean civilian worker
also was beaten, Baker said.
   He said Air Force personnel retreated to a dormitory after one
attacker pulled out a knife. The villagers then hurled rocks
through windows, he said.
   The protesters also damaged 22 military vehicles including
trucks, and looted and ransacked administrative buildings, Baker
said.
   About 450 South Korean riot police arrived about two hours after
the attack began and drove the protesters out, police said. Twenty
villagers were arrested, they said.
   The U.S. Air Force base in the central city of Osan dispatched a
team of 24 security police to the range by helicopter, but there
were no clashes between the security police and the attackers, Air
Force officials said.
   The attack came after villagers were stopped for safety reasons
from working in fields on the edge of the range during a bombing
practice, officials said. Farmers are allowed to use government
land around the range.
   Air Force officials said the attack caused extensive damage, but
gave no figures. South Korean news reports put the damage at about
$250,000.
   Villagers who live near the bombing range have complained of
noise and danger from military jets conducting bombing practice.
   The U.S. Air Force began using the range at the end of the
1950-53 Korean War. The United States has about 43,000 troops in
South Korea under a mutual defense treaty.
   The attack did not appear to be related to calls by some
anti-government groups for the expulsion of U.S. forces from South
Korea.
   South Korean dissidents and radical students have staged violent
anti-U.S. protests to denounce the United States for supporting the
government of President Roh Tae-woo.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
