<FIRST>r a PM-BridgeCollapse 1stLd-Writethru a0573 05-30 0345</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Bridge Collapse, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0573,0350</SECOND>
<HEAD>Officials Detect Two Vehicles; Four People Apparently Missing</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: LEADS with 7 grafs to UPDATE with sonar apparently detecting
two vehicles near bridge, four people apparently missing, divers still
not permitted to enter water. Picks up in 7th graf, `The water ...'</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOHN NOLAN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CINCINNATI (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Officials using sonar today detected what
appear to be two vehicles in a turbulent river where a one-lane,
temporary bridge collapsed last week, the Hamilton County sheriff
said.
   Four people are believed missing as a result of the collapse of
the bridge over the Great Miami River on Friday, said Sheriff Simon
Leis Jr.
   But Leis said the current was still too swift to send in divers
today. They might not be able to enter the river, seven miles west
of Cincinnati, until Thursday, he said.
   A sheriff's department boat equipped with sonar found what they
believe are two vehicles near the bridge, Leis said. Seven boats
and a helicopter searched the river.
   Officials haven't been able to determine how many people died in
the collapse. They had thought a car and a van were swept into the
river, but Leis said the people in the van have since turned up.
   Two women from nearby Green Township, riding together in a car,
were still missing today. They had not come home since Friday
night, said Col. Ramon Hoffbauer of the sheriff's department.
   In addition, Leis said, two other people also were missing.
   The water level has dropped below 12 feet from a high Friday
night of 23 feet, seven feet above flood stage.
   The temporary bridge, located next to a permanent span still
under construction, opened to traffic Dec. 15. The new bridge is to
replace a 94-year-old structure.
   Officials said the combination of the river's current and the
pounding from water-borne debris probably caused the collapse.
Hamilton County engineers said they won't begin their investigation
until the river falls and the current slows.
   The National Transportation Safety Board joined the
investigation Monday, spokesman Alan Pollock said.
</TEXT>
