<FIRST>r w PM-Scotus-Satter 1stLd-Writethru a0564 05-30 0490</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Scotus-Satter, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0564,460</SECOND>
<HEAD>Court Refuses To Reinstate Murder Convictions of South Dakota Man</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Subs grafs 2, The justices, and 8, The South Dakota, to CORRECT
and show state supreme court did not order new trial.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RICHARD CARELLI</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Supreme Court today refused to reinstate
the murder convictions and life sentence of a South Dakota man
accused of murdering two men in Codington County 17 years ago.
   The justices, without comment, let stand a South Dakota Supreme
Court ruling that Steven Satter's statements to a county sheriff
were inadmissible because his rights were not read to him prior to
questioning.
   Satter was convicted of the Aug. 20, 1972 shooting deaths of
Kent Engle and Jerry Bowling at their trailer home near Pelican
Lake. At his trial, Satter contended he had acted in self-defense.
   The two victims' bodies were not located until April 2, 1973,
after Satter, then in the Codington County Jail on burglary
charges, directed Sheriff Curtis Berg to a rockpile along an
abandoned railroad track south of Kranzburg.
   At Satter's trial, Berg testified that he had received an
anonymous telephone call the day before his conversation with
Satter. The caller identified where the bodies were located and
indicated that Satter might be involved.
   After looking for the bodies unsuccessfully, Berg went back to
the jail and questioned Satter, initially about some burglaries in
the area and then about the missing bodies.
   Berg testified that he did not tell Satter before questioning
him about his right to remain silent or have a lawyer's help, nor
warn him that anything he said could be used against him.
   The South Dakota Supreme Court last Jan. 4 threw out Satter's
conviction, ruling that his April 2 statement to Berg should have
been excluded from his trial. The state court also ordered a
pretrial hearing to determine whether later statements Satter made,
after receiving Miranda warnings, are admissible. A circuit judge
will rule on whether Satter is entitled to a new trial.
   The state court also ordered a pretrial hearing to determine
whether statements Satter made to police after his April 2 remarks
to Berg _ all after receiving so-called Miranda warnings _ are
admissible as evidence.
   In the appeal acted on today, state Attorney General Roger
Tellinghuisen relied heavily on a 1985 decision by the nation's
highest court.
   In it, the justices said a criminal suspect's confession to
police given after he was advised of his so-called Miranda rights
may be used as trial evidence even though an earlier confession was
obtained without such warnings.
   Tellinghuisen told the justices that the statements Satter made
to police after April 2 should are admissible under the 1985 ruling.
   The attorney general added that because those statements were
admissible at Satter's first trial, the use of his unlawfully
obtained April 2 argument should have been ruled ``harmless error.''
   The case is Rist vs. Satter, 88-1661.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
