<FIRST>r w AM-US-Poland     05-30 0137</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-US-Poland,130</SECOND>
<HEAD>U.S. Denies Interfering in Polish Election</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The State Department on Tuesday denied charges
by the Polish government that the United States is interfering in
Poland's election campaign.
   ``We're not interfering with the election campaign,'' deputy
spokesman Richard Boucher said.
   Asked about U.S. government funding for opposition candidates,
Boucher noted that Congress authorized $1 million annually for the
Solidarity trade union for at least two years.
   On Monday, the Polish government accused the United States and
other Western nations of helping the opposition campaign. It
appealed ``for an immediate halt to interference in the electoral
campaign by some Western countries.''
   Polish voters next week will elect a new 100-member Senate, with
opposition candidates allowed to run. The opposition also is
allowed to seek 35 percent of the seats in the exisiting Parliament.
</TEXT>
