<FIRST>r i AM-Burma-China     05-30 0510</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Burma-China,0525</SECOND>
<HEAD>Burmese Get New Inspiration from Campaign in China</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-China, Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DAVID BRUNNSTROM</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BANGKOK, Thailand (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The people of Burma, whose own dreams
of democracy were crushed brutally a year ago, are finding new
inspiration in the student uprising in neighboring China.
   The Burmese government's response to protest was much harsher
than China's has been. Soldiers opened fire on crowds of peaceful
demonstrators, killing thousands.
   In September, the military banned all protest.
   About a dozen students defied the ban Thursday and rallied
outside the Rangoon University campus, shouting slogans in support
of the Chinese protest, a Western diplomat reported from the
Burmese capital.
   Tin Oo, chairman of the National League for Democracy, the main
Burmese opposition party, said the next day that police detained
six activists who stuck posters to trees in solidarity with the
Chinese. He said the six had sought legal advice from him.
   Moe Thi Zun, a 24-year-old student leader, said: ``At least the
Chinese government has some respect for the students. In Burma, the
students are just shot down in the streets.''
   He was among those who fled to the Thai border when Burmese
authorities began arresting students who organized demonstrations
in March and April 1988.
   Just as in China this spring, millions of people followed
Burmese university students into the streets, marching and shouting
for an end to more than a quarter-century of repression. They
forced the resignations of three presidents and ended one-party
rule, but the army still runs the country.
   Before leaving Burma, Moe Thi Zun led the Democratic Party for a
New Society, the main student political party.
   At rallies this month, Aung San Suu Kyi, co-leader with Tin Oo
of the National League for Democracy, contrasted the Chinese
attitude with the refusal by Burmese authorities to have any
contact with dissidents. She is campaigning for general elections
the government has promised to hold in May 1990.
   Tin Oo said by telephone from Rangoon: ``We started with a
student movement so everyone has strong feelings for what is
happening in China.'' His reference was to a tradition of student
activism that began with the period leading up to independence from
Great Britain in 1948.
   The official press has printed nothing about developments in
China and the government has made no comment. For information,
Burmese listen to the British Broadcasting Corp. and Voice of
America.
   Events in China have boosted morale among about 3,000 students
who remain in the border area, living in harsh jungle conditions
with ethnic rebels groups who have spent 40 years fighting for
autonomy.
   ``It makes them realize they are not alone,'' Moe Thi Zun said
in an interview. ``They can see there are people like them
struggling for democracy.''
   He said many Burmese students are disturbed by the decline in
news coverage of their struggle.
   ``It is particularly sad because the students in Burma went
through even greater hardships than those in China,'' he said.
``Now it is not worthy of page one even though there are many still
suffering.''
</TEXT>
