<FIRST>r i AM-BRF--Philippines-Children     05-30 0181</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-BRF--Philippines-Children,0187</SECOND>
<HEAD>48 Children Die in Evacuations Centers</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MANILA, Philippines (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Disease killed 48 children this month
in evacuation centers after 35,000 villagers fled their homes to
escape fighting between government troops and communist rebels,
officials said Tuesday.
   Dr. Carlos de la Rama, health officer of Negros Occidental
province, said most of the children died of diarrhea and pneumonia.
Another 4,500 children were suffering from measles, stomach
diseases and malnutrition.
   The villagers began fleeing their homes in April after the
military stepped up operations against the New People's Army on
Negros Island, about 300 miles south of Manila, officials said.
   The military claims at least 42 rebels were killed in clashes.
   Officials said the evacuees had begun to return home after the
military promised to keep them from getting caught in the crossfire.
   Lourdes Cuachon of the Philippine Red Cross said her office
distributed rice, oil and soap to families who have moved back for
the planting season.
   The International Committee of the Red Cross said 130,000 people
were driven from their homes in 1988 because of insurgency violence.
</TEXT>
