<DOCNO> AP890530-0121 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-05-30-89 1412EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u i AM-Soviet-Georgia     05-30 0724</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Soviet-Georgia,0746</SECOND>
<HEAD>Georgian Officials Defend Themselves on Tbilisi Crackdown</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Soviet, Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MARK J. PORUBCANSKY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MOSCOW (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The former Communist Party chief and military
commander of Soviet Georgia defended themselves Tuesday against
blistering accusations they ordered a fatal military assault on
demonstrators in Tbilisi.
   The debate over the April 9 military action against a
pro-independence demonstration in the Georgian capital aroused far
more passion among the 2,250 members of the Congress of People's
Deputies than President Mikhail S. Gorbachev's policy speech hours
earlier.
   Tamaz Gamkrelidze, director of Georgia's Institute of Eastern
Studies, won a round of stormy applause three times longer than
Gorbachev after a speech in which the Georgian demanded that Col.
Gen. Igor Rodionov, Caucasus military commander, be ousted from the
Congress for the assault.
   Half the Congress stood to applaud him.
   ``It is an insult to national feelings, the entire population of
our republic, that Col. Gen. Rodionov still sits in Moscow in the
Congress of People's Deputies,'' Gamkrelidze said.
   He said voters already had decided to recall the officer, and
added, ``Col. Gen. Rodionov does not have the political or moral
right to remain a people's deputy of the Soviet Union from
Georgia.''
   A Georgian report circulated at the session charged the military
with a ``planned mass massacre'' using clubs, shovels and chemical
substances against independence protesters who filled central
Tbilisi. Gamkrelidze's text closely followed much of that report.
   Taking the floor a few moments after Gamkrelidze, Rodionov
defended himself and his soldiers. He said the majority of Georgian
deputies had taken part in a Communist Party meeting April 8 that
approved the use of force.
   ``They supported the decision of the party bureau that the
situation was extraordinarily explosive, the outcome could not be
predicted, all measures of action and appeals to common sense had
been exhausted, and there remained only extreme measures, to use
force,'' he said.
   But after the violence, he said, everyone has denied being
responsible for using force.
   He said soldiers were armed with shovels only to protect
themselves, but that they did not expect ``such brutal and stubborn
resistance.''
   At least 19 people died in the clash with soldiers on Tbilisi's
Rustaveli Prospekt, and another was shot to death later that night.
   Sixteen of those who were killed outright were not marked with
wounds, he said. ``Not on one of them was there any wound from
puncture, cutting or bashing,'' he said, rejecting charges they had
been beaten with shovels and clubs, and suffered chemical poisoning.
   Rodionov denied using chemicals, and said the decision to send
in soldiers was made by such a small group of people that he
himself did not know when and how the assault was to take place.
   He was heckled, but also received long applause when he finished.
   After 80 minutes of impassioned debate, Gorbachev broke the
tension with humor and a promise that a parliamentary commission
would find those responsible.
   ``I've know this republic, these people for a long time,'' he
said of Georgia. ``They know me. I love them, and I hope they treat
me with respect.''
   Answering questions last week before the Congress, Gorbachev
said he only learned about the assault several hours after it
happened.
   ``We must get down to the roots, whatever this cost us and
whoever this might concern,'' he added. ``I was interrogated for
two hours yesterday. I am thankful to my comrades. This means that
there is democracy at the Congress. But this does not mean that
Gorbachev does not see. I see everything,'' he said to laughter and
applause.
   Dzhumber Patiashvili, the former Georgian Communist Party chief
who took responsibility for the assault and resigned, charged that
Rodionov and First Deputy Defense Minister Konsantin A. Kochetov
appeared at a party meeting and said they had been authorized
``from above'' to end the Georgian protests.
   He said that when he resigned, he did not know that chemicals
and shovels had been used. ``Even two or three days later, Rodionov
rejected the fact that shovels and gases had been used,''
Patiashvili said.
   ``I want to know who authorized the use of gas and shovels? Who
ordered this level of cruelty?'' he asked.
   After the debate, the deputies were invited to closed showings
of footage shot by Georgian activists and from the military about
events in Tbilisi.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
