<FIRST>r i AM-Bush-Students     05-30 0254</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Bush-Students,240</SECOND>
<HEAD>With AM-Bush Bjt</HEAD>
<HEAD>Bush Ends Summit Stay With Visit to American School</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BRUSSELS, Belgium (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   President Bush told U.S. students
Tuesday that western values of democracy and freedom ``are winning
the battle around the world'' as he concluded his NATO summit visit
with a stop at an American school.
   ``As we look at Eastern Europe and we look at other places
around the world we see that it's the American values that are
prevailing,'' Bush told about 500 high school students at the
Brussels American School.
   The president and his wife, Barbara, spent about 20 minutes at
the school, located on the outskirts of the city, before leaving
for West Germany, the next stop on their European trip.
   The flag-waving students greeted the couple with cheers and
applause.
   ``I love this enthusiasm ... Anything to get out of school,''
joked the president after the cheering had died down.
   In his remarks, Bush only mentioned the NATO summit briefly,
saying: ``One of the things that has been marvelous about this
summit is the understanding that our values, the alliance's values
... are winning the battle around the world.''
   On a lighter note, he read two welcome cards from elementary
school students.
   One began: ``Yo, President Bush. I think you are really cool.''
   Looking up from the card to say, ``I want the press to hear
this,'' Bush then continued reading:
   ``You make all the right decisions. And I am glad you are coming
to our school. I love your hair.''
