<FILEID>AP-NR-05-30-89 1431EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u i AM-Everyone'sVictory Bjt   05-30 0590</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Everyone's Victory, Bjt,600</SECOND>
<HEAD>Bitter Arguments, Some Concessions, And Everyone Says `I Won'</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MAUREEN JOHNSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BRUSSELS, Belgium (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The NATO allies argued bitterly,
antagonists yielded ground, and when they finally struck a deal on
short-range nuclear missiles in Europe everyone claimed victory.
   But two arch-rivals in the dispute, British Prime Minister
Margaret Thatcher and West German Chancellor Helmut Kohl, did not
forgive and forget.
   He called her ``tempermental.'' She said pointedly that
``wriggle as they may,'' the West Germans cannot extricate
themselves from the accord that dashed their hopes of eliminating
the weapons on their soil.
   President Bush sided with Mrs. Thatcher on most of the issues
but ended up sounding more like a mediator than an antagonist. ``I
don't think we ought to have winners and losers,'' he said. ``It is
an alliance victory, an alliance decision.''
   Kohl, backed by several other leaders, and Mrs. Thatcher, Bush's
closest ally, each focused on the points they'd won and glided over
their concessions at the end of the two-day summit of the 16-nation
alliance.
   Mrs. Thatcher had wanted NATO to rule out superpower
negotiations to reduce the short-range Lance missiles and to pledge
to replace them in the mid-1990s when the weapons will be obsolete.
   Kohl, politically sensitive to widespread opposition in West
Germany to the missiles, wanted early and unconditional
negotiations.
   The last-minute agreement calls for the United States to
negotiate ``partial'' reductions, but only after conventional
forces are cut.
   ``Partial'' was underlined for emphasis. Mrs. Thatcher said that
wasn't her idea, but she liked it.
   ``I am very, very satisfied with the total document. It is one
of the best I have ever seen,'' Mrs. Thatcher said, noting that the
deal specified NATO will retain nuclear weapons.
   ``You don't have to ask me or them (the West Germans), just read
what they have signed up to,'' she told reporters. ``When you sign
up to something, that's that. It's not a question of what we say it
means.''
   Kohl, meanwhile, said the outcome of the summit was
``fantastic.'' It showed ``a positive recognition of our special
concerns'' by, he added pointedly, ``most'' of the allies.
   ``Margaret Thatcher stood up for her interests in her
temperamental way,'' Kohl said. ``We do sometimes have differences
of opinion. We have different temperaments. And she's a woman and
I'm not.''
   At her separate, but equally upbeat news conference, Mrs.
Thatcher responded in kind.
   Asked if she'd made up with the West Germans, she retorted, ``I
haven't started a battle with them. I don't have any problems. If
they have, let them sort them out.''
   She added, ``It's all written there very firmly indeed and,
wriggle as they may, that is what they have all signed up for.''
   The impetus for the agreement, reached after NATO foreign
ministers argued until the early hours Tuesday, was a Bush
initiative to accelerate conventional arms negotiations for new and
sweeping cuts in troops, armaments and warplanes in Europe.
   Everyone dubbed the Bush plan a winner, and the U.S. president
was credited with marking his first NATO summit by regaining the
arms control and public relations initiative from Soviet leader
Mikhail S. Gorbachev.
   Kohl's backers, such as Belgian Prime Minister Wilfried Martens,
and others who tried to intercede in the nuclear missile dispute
all claimed that they, too, were leaving Brussels contented.
   ``The total elimination of nuclear weapons cannot be expected in
the foreseeable future,'' said Italian foreign minister Giulio
Andreotti, one of the conciliators. Then he added, ``But no hope is
excluded.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
