<FIRST>r w AM-US-Argentina     05-30 0201</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-US-Argentina,190</SECOND>
<HEAD>U.S. Calls for Talks on Resolving Economic Crisis</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The State Department called Tuesday on
Argentina's political and economic leaders to unite in formulating
a plan to ease the country's economic crisis.
   The statement by deputy spokesman Richard Boucher appeared to be
an appeal for government and opposition forces to revive their
effort to agree on economic measures.
   That effort broke down shortly after the Peronist candidate for
president, Carlos Menam, defeated the candidate of the ruling
Radical Party in national elections two weeks ago.
   Boucher expressed regret that the economic crisis has led to
disorder and said the state of siege instituted on Monday to halt
an outbreak of food riots was consistent with democratic procedures
established by the constitution.
   ``At this critical time, we believe it is important for
Argentina's political and economic leaders to work together to
implement measures to stabilize the economic situation,'' Boucher
said.
   He said the administration does not believe that the declaration
of a state of siege poses any danger to democracy.
   ``Despite serious economic problems, the people of Argentina
have made their commitment to democracy clear, most recently in the
election for president on May 14,'' he said.
