<FILEID>AP-NR-05-30-89 1514EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a AM-Lotto-Police     05-30 0473</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Lotto-Police,0490</SECOND>
<HEAD>Police Department Members Split Millions in Lotto Pool</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By PEGGY ANDERSEN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   More than half of a suburban town's police force
stormed state lottery offices Tuesday, but they weren't after
criminals _ just their one-third share of a $25 million jackpot.
   Sixteen employees at the Barrington Hills Police Department
kicked in to buy 90 $1 tickets for Saturday's drawing. The other 12
employees are kicking themselves, said Chief Robert Lamb, who is
one of the winners.
   ``It's been like pandemonium,'' Lamb said from lottery
headquarters, where the department's winning Lotto ticket was
verified. ``The adrenaline is flowing.''
   The winners' share is $8.3 million, paid out in 20 annual
installments. After the first $416,811 check, they will split
$414,000 a year, said lottery spokeswoman Carrie Worley.
   That works out to about $26,000 annually for each player, Lamb
said _ not enough for early retirement but ``enough to make life a
little more comfortable for all of us.''
   In addition to Lamb, the winners include Cmdr. Ed Fair, three
sergeants, two dispatchers, a mintenance worker and eight
patrolmen, officials said.
   The Barrington Hills police headquarters was quiet Tuesday
morning.
   ``Just us losers are here today,'' said dispatcher Cindy Olhava.
``We're just moping around.''
   Plans for spending the windfall are still up in the air, but
some of the winners ``have little kids and are already planning for
college days,'' Lamb said.
   As far as splurging, ``there is talk of buying a condo in the
Gulf for us'' in Texas or Florida, he said.
   Too many members of the force won to allow all the winners to
take time off together, the chief said, but ``I'm sure there will
be a lot of vacation requests coming in now.''
   Mayor James A. Kempe wondered if there would be a rash of
resignations on the force serving his northwest suburban community
of about 3,000. ``I hope they stay on,'' he said.
   The pool was organized by Officer Michael Wisniewski, who said
he started playing with two employees who work with him on the
overnight shift.
   He figured that if the entire department got in on it, they'd
have more chances to win.
   The idea ``went like wildfire,'' said Wisniewski, who plans to
use his share to pay bills and for education for himself, his wife
and their children.
   Right now, he said he wants to catch up on his sleep. Wisniewski
estimated he'd slept about four hours since Saturday's drawing,
fretting that he'd misread the numbers.
   ``It couldn't sink in that we actually won,'' he said, adding he
feels ``kind of sad to see everybody didn't get into it.''
   Lotto players buy $1 tickets with two chances to pick six
numbers from 1 to 54. The winning numbers in the weekend drawing
were 4, 19, 24, 25, 38 and 43.
</TEXT>
