<FIRST>u i AM-Cardinal 2ndLd-Writethru a0652 05-30 0442</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Cardinal, 2nd Ld - Writethru, a0652,0452</SECOND>
<HEAD>O'Connor Briefs Pope on Visit to Lebanon</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: SUBS 2nd graf to CORRECT spelling of Scandinavia.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By PIA HINCKLE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>ROME (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Pope John Paul II met Tuesday with Cardinal John
O'Connor for a briefing on the New York prelate's visit to Lebanon,
where he tried unsuccessfully to visit Americans held hostage.
   ``For the holy father to schedule an hour-and-a-half meeting on
the eve of his trip to Scandinavia, he must have been very
interested in hearing the cardinal's impressions,'' said Monsignor
James McCarthy, the cardinal's secretary.
   O'Connor traveled to Lebanon on Saturday in his capacity as head
of the Catholic Near East Welfare Mission and visited hospitals and
orphanages.
   He appealed during his three-day trip to see the nine American
hostages held by pro-Iranian extremists, but received no response
from the captors.
   In all, 18 foreigners are held hostage in Lebanon. The longest
held is Terry Anderson, chief Middle East correspondent for The
Associated Press. He was kidnapped March 16, 1985.
   O'Connor arrived in Beirut a day after an Arab League summit
renewed its call for Christian troops fighting Syrian and Druse
forces to honor a cease-fire.
   The latest round of fighting in the 14-year-old civil war began
11 weeks ago, and has overshadowed the hostage issue.
   O'Connor planned to visit Moslem west Beirut but called off the
trip on Sunday because he was told there was a fighting along the
city's dividing Green Line.
   He said later the information was inaccurate, but declined to
say where it came from.
   ``It was the cardinal's decision not to go, based on a number of
different reports, influences, people and the predominant physical
danger of his going at that time,'' said McCarthy, who accompanied
O'Connor to Lebanon. He would not elaborate.
   The decision offended some Moslem leaders, including acting
Prime Minister Salim Hoss. The cardinal later spoke with Hoss by
telephone to try to patch things up.
   He also met with a representative of Shiite Moslem Parliament
Speaker Hussein Husseini, McCarthy said.
   O'Connor flew to Rome on Tuesday from Larnaca, Cyprus, after
staying in Lebanon's Christian enclave at Bkirki monastery as the
guest of Maronite Catholic Patriarch Nasrallah Sfeir.
   Security at Larnaca airport was tight after police on Monday
found a cache of weapons near the beachside runway. They included
Soviet-made SA-7 shoulder-fired missiles, police said.
   Cypriot police arrested six Arabs suspected of planning to shoot
down Lebanese army helicopters that make daily flights from Cyprus
to the Christian enclave, under siege by shelling by Syrian forces.
   Government officials said the target was an ``Arab
personality,'' not O'Connor. They did not elaborate.
</TEXT>
