<FIRST>r a AM-GatorHunt     05-30 0213</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Gator Hunt,0219</SECOND>
<HEAD>Permits to Hunt Alligators Accepted This Week</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WEST PALM BEACH, Fla. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Applications for the state's second
alligator hunt in recent decades will be taken this week and
officials plan to open more areas and increase the number of gators
that can be taken.
   Last year was the first legal hunt in 26 years, with 2,960
alligators reported caught _ well under the 3,450 limit set the the
Florida Game and Fresh Water Fish Commission.
   This year that limit will go up to 3,900 _ out of an estimated
population of 1 million gators _ and game officials are preparing
to receive up to 26,000 applications for the 250 or 260 permits to
be issued.
   ``There are still really dense populations of alligators that we
didn't really consider last year,'' said Mike Jennings, a wildlife
biologist with the Alligator Management Office in Gainesville.
   Applications will be taken beginning Thursday and will be
accepted until June 15, Jennings said. Permits to hunt the gators
will be awarded by lottery.
   Thirty-two areas, including Lake Okeechobee and parts of major
canals in Palm Beach and Broward counties, will be hunted this year.
   The dates for the hunting season have not been set, officials
said. Last year the season began in September.
</TEXT>
