<FILEID>AP-NR-05-30-89 1541EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u i AM-China-Statue     05-30 0538</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-China-Statue,0556</SECOND>
<HEAD>`Goddess of Democracy' Statue Latest Sacrilege in Square</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-China, Bjt</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhotos BEJ4,8,21</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOHN POMFRET</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BEIJING (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The 33-foot-tall ``Goddess of Democracy,''
unveiled Tuesday, is the latest in a long line of blasphemous
additions to Tiananmen Square by students demonstrating for
democracy.
   First the students made fun of soldiers, messing up their timed
march by yelling numbers out of sequence. Then they hung flags for
freedom from the roof of the Museum of Revolutionary History.
   Next came balloons floating atop the Monument for Revolutionary
Martyrs, a massive obelisk in the middle of the square. ``Meet our
demands,'' they read, as they bobbed in the wind.
   With the visit of Soviet President Mikhail S. Gorbachev, the
students had their own welcoming ceremony _ 100,000-strong _
forcing the government to switch its ceremony to the airport.
   Last week, three people threw paint at the portrait of Chinese
leader Mao Tse-tung, covering it with blue, red and black dots, and
forcing authorities to replace the portrait of the Great Helmsman.
   On Tuesday, they put the ``Goddess'' _ a Statue of Liberty
lookalike _ in the middle of the vast expanse, the symbolic
political center of China.
   Fashioned from white Styrofoaom and plaster of Paris by students
from eight art schools around Beijing, the statue depicts a large
lady, hair blowing in the wind, holding a torch.
   Whereas the lady in New York Harbor holds a torch and a tablet,
China's version holds only a torch, in both hands, like a baseball
bat.
   Located smack on the Celestial Axis _ a line which runs from the
throne in the Forbidden City to the Temple of Heaven _ the statue
is a challenge, and some might say, an insult to China's imperial
and Communist tradition.
   The nightly TV news took a hard line on the statue.
   ``The people of the whole nation will resolutely oppose it,''
the news quoted a group called the Beijing Tiananmen Square
Administration as saying. ``The erection of a so-called `Goddess'
statue here is an insult to the national image and dignity.''
   A letter from an unidentified ``intellectual'' also was read.
   ``This is China, not America,'' he reminded the audience. ``But
even if it was America you wouldn't be able to build a so-called
statue in front of the Congress building.''
   He called the act ``illegal'' and asked the government to get
rid of the statue by Thursday. ``Otherwise there will be serious
unhealthy effects,'' he warned.
   For a government used to a monopoly on political symbols, the
statue's meanings must irk the leadership in several ways.
   The unwillingness of the builders to listen to the government's
warnings about the statue and the relish with which Beijing's
citizens treated its appearance must chafe.
   Indeed, although a hardline faction appears to be winning the
power struggle inside the halls of power, the statue proved that
for the time being the streets still belong to the people.
   On Tuesday, tens of thousands of people swarmed around the
statue, posing for pictures with the Goddess as a backdrop.
   ``This is not fine art,'' said a woman as she looked up at the
Goddess' face. ``But it is a symbol. It proves people want
freedom.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890530-0137 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-05-30-89 1544EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u i AM-Soviet-NATO     05-30 0521</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Soviet-NATO,0536</SECOND>
<HEAD>Officials Welcome Bush Proposal, But Say Progress Might be Slow</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Bush, Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOHN IAMS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MOSCOW (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Soviet officials Tuesday welcomed a NATO proposal
to negotiate reductions in short-range nuclear missiles but said
linking the issue to talks on conventional arms could cause an
unneeded delay.
   A Soviet TV commentator said the NATO agreement had only papered
over differences between President Bush and a majority of the U.S.
allies in the North Atlantic Treaty Alliance.
   The proposal, announced by Bush on Monday at the NATO conference
in Brussels, authorizes the United States to negotiate with the
Soviets ``to achieve a partial reduction'' of short-range nuclear
missiles.
   However, any missile reductions would be linked to East-West
talks in Vienna on reducing troops, tanks and artillery. The
missile negotiations could not begin until an accord was reached to
reduce those conventional forces and NATO and the Warsaw Pact had
actually started to carry out those reductions.
   President Mikhail S. Gorbachev did not comment on the proposal
in a major policy address Tuesday in which he disclosed that the
Kremlin spends about $118 billion a year for defense, nearly four
times the previous official claim.
   Foreign Minister Eduard A. Shevardnadze said upon arriving in
Paris for a human rights conference that the proposal was
attractive and ``a step in the right direction.''
   But he said ``it will take time to examine the American
proposals in detail and determine the position of the U.S.S.R.''
   Foreign Ministry spokesman Gennady Gerasimov said in Moscow that
Soviet officials had not yet seen the proposals, but welcomed the
opportunity to negotiate a reduction in battlefield nuclear
missiles.
   ``Generally speaking, we are for such negotiations and against
linkage of such negotiations with other talks and negotiations,''
Gerasimov said.
   ``If the United States is going to postpone the negotiations on
tactical nuclear missiles until we have agreement on conventional
weapons and start reductions, then we think that it is a
protraction, a protraction that we don't need,'' he said.
   Gerasimov said negotiations should be able to move ahead in
several areas simultaneously.
   ``Now we have an improved political climate in Europe. To state
in this situation that we should have some kind of linkage, these
statements become less and less convincing,'' he said.
   Maj. Gen. Vladimir Kuklev said an official position had not been
formulated to Bush's proposal to cut conventional forces by about
10 percent, but that in his opinion, it was ``a major step
forward.''
   Gerasimov interrupted to say, ``official opinion coincides with
your opinion.''
   In a report from the NATO conference, Soviet TV commentator
Valetin Zorin said on the news program ``Vremya'' that ``Soviet
proposals at last made Washington move off dead center, where it
was for the past several months.''
   ``The deep contradictions between the NATO members are not
solved, but pressed deep inside,'' he said. ``Not by chance
President Bush in his speech yesterday avoided a sensitive question
that divided him from the majority of his European allies. The
issue is tactical nuclear weapons and the compromise decision on
this problem was made at the very last moment.''
</TEXT>
