<FIRST>r i AM-Sudan-Relief     05-30 0266</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Sudan-Relief,0274</SECOND>
<HEAD>U.N. Seeking More Money for Sudan Relief</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NAIROBI, Kenya (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The United Nations is seeking $50 million
more for an emergency operation to save 100,000 people from
starving in a war-induced famine in southern Sudan, an official
said Tuesday.
   James Grant, head of the U.N. Operation Lifeline Sudan, said
$130 million that already has been donated by governments and
private organizations is not enough.
   The operation, plagued by political conflicts, logistical
problems and armed attacks, must start dropping food from planes,
Grant said.
   At a news conference in Nairobi, he said he will appeal for
money to carry the operation to the end of the year at a June 13
donors' conference in New York.
   The United Nations had hoped to stockpile 100,000 tons of food
in southern Sudan before the end of May, but only has delivered
about half that amount.
   Its operation has been plagued by political conflicts,
logistical problems and armed attacks by bandits and paramilitary
groups.
   Th most recent attack was Sunday, when bandits struck a truck
convoy and killed three people.
   With the start of a five-month rainy season already under way,
delivery of food by trucks, trains and airplanes is becoming more
difficult each day. Havey rains usually make roads, rail lines and
runways unusable, when Grant plans to start air drops.
   Rebels have been fighting six years for autonomy for the
minority Christians and animists of southern Sudan. They are
observing a unilateral cease-fire this month to permit in emergency
supplies and allow the Moslem-dominated government in the north
time to organize a peace conference.
</TEXT>
