<FIRST>r w AM-AbortionRights 1stLd-Writethru a0659 05-30 0609</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Abortion Rights, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0659,620</SECOND>
<HEAD>Abortion Rights Group Targets Legislators in Ad Campaign</HEAD>
<HEAD>EDS: SUBS 4th graf pvs, bgng: ``The ad...'' to CORRECT name of newspaper;
picks up 5th graf pvs, bgng: ``Among the...''</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JILL LAWRENCE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The National Abortion Rights Action League
launched a newspaper ad campaign Tuesday designed to let voters
back home read the ``outrageous'' comments their elected officials
are making about women and abortion.
   ``Many of the constituents in districts around the country do
not know what their congresspeople say and do regarding a woman's
right to choose,'' said NARAL executive director Kate Michelman.
``We believe that it will make a difference when they do know.''
   The league's first target was freshman Rep. Craig James, a
Florida Republican whose district covers an area from Jacksonville
south to Cape Canaveral. James last year narrowly wrested the seat
from veteran Rep. Bill Chappell, a Democrat whose name had come up
in connection with the Pentagon procurement scandal.
   The ad in the Daytona Beach News-Journal paraphrased comments
that James made during a May 10 hearing of the House Judiciary
subcommittee on civil and constitutional rights, according to the
abortion rights league.
   Among the statements the group attributed to James were that
pregnant women are too confused to make a rational decision about
whether or not to have an abortion; safe and legal abortions
promote promiscuity and increase the spread of AIDS; and if
abortion becomes illegal, women who seek abortions and all those
who help them would be criminals and should be punished.
   ``The Supreme Court is now reconsidering who will have the right
to decide if a woman can have an abortion. Politicians like Craig
James? Or you?'' the ad says. ``Ultimately you will. With your
vote.''
   Michelman said the ad is the first of its kind for the league
but ``we will see more of this.'' She said her group has gathered a
store of ``tremendously outrageous statements about reproductive
rights and women in general'' from other legislators and is
developing a list of targets, of which James is the first.
   ``We're going to educate the public and organize them into a
voting block,'' Michelman said. ``We intend to make this a decisive
issue for the public's voting decisions in 1989 and 1990. This is
not just about congressmen and senators. It's governors and state
legislators and county commissioners and the whole range of
political public office.''
   James' press secretary, Brian Flood, called the ad a
fund-raising ploy and said the congressman's position on abortion
has always been clear _ he is opposed to it except where a woman's
life is endangered or in cases of rape or incest.
   ``It is extremely improper and way out of line to interpret
anything said at this hearing as anti-woman,'' Flood said. ``This
is a despicable political effort to undermine his continued service
in Congress.''
   Flood called the NARAL ad ``the beginning of what will be a
nasty effort'' to unseat James by trying to find ``little bits of
information and take them out of context and present them in a very
radical way like this in an attempt to damage his credibility and
reputation. I don't think it's going to work.''
   Michelman said the timing of the ad so far in advance of the
1990 election is meant to coincide with increased public interest
in the abortion rights issue while the Supreme Court weighs a
Missouri case that could have profound consequences for women's
access to abortion.
   As for whether James' constituents will remember the ad come
November 1990, she said, ``They won't forget because we won't let
them forget.''
</TEXT>
