<FIRST>u i AM-Lebanon 1stLd-Writethru a0600 05-30 0622</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Lebanon, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0600,0641</SECOND>
<HEAD>Syrians Shell Christian Enclave</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: LEADS throughout UPDATING with U.S. envoy criticizing Syria,
shelling casualty, details. No pickup</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MOHAMMED SALAM</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BEIRUT, Lebanon (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Syrian army gunners shelled Lebanon's
Christian enclave with howitzers, mortars and tank cannons Tuesday
despite renewed calls to honor a cease-fire declared by Arab
leaders.
   Police said one civilian was killed in the barrage by Syrians
deployed in Moslem west Beirut and the capital's southern slums.
   That raised the overall toll to 360 killed and 1,396 wounded
since the latest round of Lebanon's 14-year-old civil war broke out
March 8.
   A police spokesman, who cannot be identified in line with
standing rules, said army commander Gen. Michel Aoun's 20,000
mostly Christian troops did not fire back.
   U.S. Ambassador John McCarthy said the Bush administration was
``discouraged'' by Syria's failure to enter into a dialogue with
Aoun, who heads the Christian Cabinet in Lebanon's dual government.
   ``We've been urging Syria privately ... and publicly ... that
given its description of its own role here as a peacekeeper that
its action should be more in line with those of a peacekeeper,'' he
said, ``that what is necessary in Lebanon is a political dialogue
to get under way, not have a lot of shelling.
   ``The Syrians and certainly the Lebanese Moslems should be
dialoguing with ... (Aoun) rather than criticizing him. I find the
Syrian position to date on that specific point has been unwise.''
   It was the strongest public criticism of Syria by a U.S.
official during the present confrontation between Aoun and an
alliance of the Syrian army and Druse leader Walid Jumblatt's
Progressive Socialist Party.
   McCarthy spoke after meeting with Foreign Ministry
Undersecretary Farouk Abillama in Christian east Beirut as Syrians
sporadically shelled the sector.
   Dozens of howitzer shells crashed onto the Christian coastline
north of Beirut, hitting the ports of Jounieh and Byblos, the
police spokesman said.
   Shelling of the coast is intended to prevent the Christians from
receiving war material and other supplies.
   Syrian gunners also opened up at the Christian suburbs of
Hadath, Kfarsheema and Baabda, southeast of Beirut, he added.
   Baabda houses the presidential palace. Aoun has been staying in
its bunker throughout the 11 weeks of shelling duels.
   The spokesman said the palace, ravaged by previous shelling, was
not targeted Tuesday.
   Shelling has increased despite a call by Arab heads of state for
a complete cease-fire as they ended a summit on Friday in
Casablanca, Morocco. The Arab League declared a cease-fire on May
11.
   The leaders formed a committee made up of the heads of state of
Morocco, Saudi Arabia and Algeria to try to resolve the Lebanon
crisis within six months.
   The committee was given a mandate to arrange for the Lebanese
Parliament to convene to draw up political reforms and elect a new
president who would form a government of national reconciliation.
   The summit pledged to support the new government in
re-establishing state authority with its own forces on Lebanon's
entire territory _ an indirect assertion that the Syrians should
withdraw.
   McCarthy called the Arab moves were ``encouraging developments.''
   Syria maintains 40,000 troops in Lebanon under a 1976
peacekeeping mandate from the Arab League. Aoun says the Syrians
lost their credibility as peacekeepers when they sided with the
Moslems in the civil war.
   Aoun, 54, a Maronite, complained in a weekend memorandum to the
Arab League that Syrian gunners were not respecting the truce
called by Arab leaders, his command said.
   King Hassan II of Morocco, who heads the committee on Lebanon,
told a news conference in Rabat the Arabs would make every effort
to solve the problem, but that the solution would have to come from
the Lebanese themselves.
</TEXT>
