<FIRST>r a AM-HotelTalks     05-30 0267</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Hotel Talks,0274</SECOND>
<HEAD>Union Chief Vows No Strike if Talks Progress</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ROBERT MACY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LAS VEGAS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The head of a hotel workers union said no new
talks are planned before a five-year contract covering 30,000
employees expires Thursday, but said there would be no strike as
long as owners keep talking in good faith.
   ``June 1 is not some magic date,'' Jim Arnold, head of Culinary
Union Local 226, said Tuesday. ``I'm not ruling out any
possibility. But as long as we haven't reached an impasse, we'll
continue to negotiate.''
   Leaders on both sides hope to avoid a repeat of the bitter 1984
hotel strike that left workers off the job for 75 days and affected
the city's lifeblood tourism industry.
   Negotiating teams made a breakthrough Friday night when the
union reached an agreement with six major hotels. The six signed an
agreement similar to a pact signed earlier this month with the
Golden Nugget Hotel and Casino.
   Officials at the six hotels say the new contract will cost them
$250 million over five years.
   Twenty-four other hotels still must continue negotiating. The
main issue is wages.
   The new contract with the six resorts covers 10,000 workers,
about one-third of the union's membership. Union members will vote
on the contract Wednesday.
   The six hotels signing Friday were Caesars Palace, Bally's, the
Flamingo Hilton, the Las Vegas Hilton, the Tropicana and Circus
Circus.
   The contract calls for a $1.25 hourly increase spread over the
five years of the agreement, along with a 95-cent-an-hour increase
in contributions to the health and welfare fund.
</TEXT>
