<FIRST>r a AM-JetDiverted     05-30 0234</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Jet Diverted,0239</SECOND>
<HEAD>Inspectors Trying To Determine How Close Plane Came to Ditching</HEAD>
<DATELINE>HONOLULU (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Federal investigators and airline mechanics
inspected a TWA jumbo jet on Tuesday to determine how close the
plane came to ditching after it started leaking fuel over the
Pacific Ocean.
   Investigators suspect a break in the fuel line feeding the
Lockheed L-1011's left wing engine caused the leak, said George W.
Harvey, a Federal Aviation Administration administrator.
   TWA Flight 235, bound from Los Angeles with 205 people aboard,
made an emergency landing early Monday at Hilo International
Airport on the island of Hawaii, about 200 miles southeast of its
destination of Honolulu.
   TWA spokesman Don Morrison in St. Louis said it was not known
how much fuel was left when the plane landed, but a televised news
report said the plane had enough for just four minutes of flight.
   Investigators had a general idea of how much fuel was left,
Harvey said, ``but we won't have anything ready to release on that
until tomorrow.''
   The plane was instructed to divert to Hilo when its pilot
reported the jet was running low on fuel when it was 450 miles from
Honolulu, according to FAA reports.
   The plane's left engine was shut down after the crew realized
fuel was leaking from the wing, but was unable to stop the leak,
Morrison said. The plane has two main fuel tanks.
</TEXT>
