<DOCNO> AP890530-0153 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-05-30-89 1858EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i AM-Poland 1stLd-Writethru a0653 05-30 0753</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Poland, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0653,0778</SECOND>
<HEAD>Warsaw Steps Up Charges of U.S. Interference</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: ADDS 4 grafs pro-Solidarity students suspend strikes.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOHN DANISZEWSKI</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WARSAW, Poland (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The government intensified its charges
Tuesday that the United States is improperly helping Solidarity's
election campaign _ a claim Solidarity and U.S. diplomats denied.
   A State Department spokesman said Congress has authorized $1
million annually for Solidarity trade union for at least two years.
But U.S. spokesman Richard Boucher added: ``We're not interfering
with the election campaign.''
   Zbyslaw Rykowski, the deputy government spokesman in Warsaw,
said an official statement Monday accusing Western diplomats of
helping the opposition before Sunday's elections referred to
``representatives of the embassy of the United States.''
   But he added he hoped the matter ``would have no influence'' on
President Bush's planned mid-July visit to Poland.
   ``The way of behaving of those diplomats unambiguously showed
that they were taking part in the electoral campaign in favor of
the opposition,'' Rykowski said.
   He told a news conference he had a dossier on alleged incidents,
but ``it's in no one's interest to say anything more.''
   In Warsaw, a U.S. Embassy spokesman read a response saying:
``Embassy personnel in keeping with standard diplomatic practice
are responsible for keeping abreast of important developments in
Poland, including the elections.
   ``However, the embassy emphatically denies that any of its
personnel have engaged in improper activities or that they have
actively supported one group or one candidate over any others.''
   The accusation came in the final days of the campaign for
Poland's first democratic elections since World War II.
   Poles vote Sunday for 100 members of a new senate that will be
the East bloc's first fully democratically elected legislative body.
   They also choose 460 members for the existing parliament, where
the opposition may compete for 161 seats. The rest are reserved for
the Communist Party and its allies.
   Solidarity has endorsed candidates for all contestable seats.
   Answering statements about Solidarity claims the opposition is
ahead in the campaign, Rykowski predicted the Communist Party
coalition would do well.
   He said the party's campaign has not had to be as visible as
Solidarity's because, ``One knows what one can expect from us.''
   ``The prognoses for our side are good,'' he said. ``All the data
presented by our opponents are only the result of their wishful
thinking.''
   He said the party and its allies were ``the guarantors of
certainty and stability of this country. We don't have to use
election techniques taken from an American movie.''
   Government polls show about 85 percent of the country's
approximately 26 million voters will participate, he said. In
Poland's last elections, for local offices in June 1988, the
official turnout was put at 56 percent but the opposition said it
was much lower.
   Monday's government statement alleged ``an unprecedented
violation of Poland's sovereignty.''
   It mentioned diplomats appearing at opposition election rallies,
financial donations flowing to Solidarity's campaign from the West
and U.S.-financed Radio Free Europe, which broadcasts without
interference to Poland in Polish.
   Solidarity said help received from abroad was consistent with
Polish law and accused the government of trying to frighten voters.
   ``They want to scare those who are undecided,'' the statement
said ``Scaring citizens does not serve it well, nor does abuse of
patriotic feelings or manipulation of facts.''
   Solidarity has not given details of money it has received, but
says most contributions are from Poles abroad who are entitled to
vote.
   City officials, meanwhile, announced the creation of a
free-speech corner from Thursday in the city's Agrykola park.
   Similar to London's Speaker's Corner, it will be open to orators
on any theme so long as they ``abide by the generally adopted moral
norms and good manners and international conventions signed by
Poland,'' the Warsaw daily Zycie Warszawy reported.
   Pro-Solidarity university students announced they would suspend
strikes they have staged for the past week because of ``the
approaching elections and the possibility of using the wave of
student strikes as propaganda against opposition candidates.''
   The strikes began May 23 after a Warsaw court denied an
application to charter the Independent Students Association,
closely linked to the Solidarity union movement.
   In denying the application the court said the association
illegally claimed it has the right to organize strikes.
   Association leaders said Tuesday they would appeal the court
decision and resume strikes in the autumn if authorities still
refuse to register the organization. They said students at 43
institutions of higher learning had participated in the strikes but
gave no further details.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
