<FIRST>r a AM-Obit-Friedheim     05-30 0374</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Obit-Friedheim,0383</SECOND>
<HEAD>Friedheim Dead at 89; Remedies Saved Millions</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RICK HAMPSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Dr. Ernst A. H. Friedheim, who developed a drug
to treat African sleeping sickness that probably has saved 2
million lives, has died of kidney cancer at the age of 89.
   Friedheim, who died at home Saturday, devised melarsoprol in the
1930s and '40s to treat trypanosomiasis, or sleeping sickness. The
disease, spread by the tsetse fly, remains a serious problem in
Africa and Friedheim's drug is still used to treat some more
advanced cases.
   He also developed drugs to treat many other parasitic tropical
diseases, and later in his career devised remedies for lead and
mercury poisoning. When he died he also was working on drugs to
treat cancer.
   ``He continued to work virtually until his death,'' said Thomas
Donnelly, a veterinarian who worked with Friedheim. ``When he was
in the hospital he kept asking me about the results of our
experiments. He said, `I have to know.' He knew he was running out
of time.''
   Born in Switzerland, Friedheim earned a medical degree as well
as a doctorate in chemistry. This training allowed him relative
independence in a field dominated by research teams.
   Rockefeller University, where Friedheim had been a professor
since 1978, issued a statement saying he ``single-handedly
performed chemical synthesis, laboratory evaluation, and clinical
testing in the field.'' The latter took him to Africa, Asia, South
America and Pacific islands.
   ``It was unusual the way he was able to take the (development
of) a drug from the laboratory to its application in the field,''
said Dr. William Trager, a leading malaria researcher. ``He had a
lot of drive. He went out to Africa in the old days, when it was
really Africa.''
   A month ago Friedheim was honored at the 26th meeting of the
International Council for Trypanosomiasis Research in Kenya. Peter
deRaadt of the World Health Organization's parasitic diseases unit
credited Friedheim's development of melarsoprol with saving the
lives of 2 million Africans.
   Donnelly said that, judging from estimates in various medical
texts, Friedheim's other drugs probably have saved an additional 1
million lives around the world.
   He is survived by his wife, Suzanne Hagerstrom-Friedheim.
Funeral arrangements are private.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
