<FIRST>r i AM-France-HumanRights     05-30 0322</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-France-Human Rights,0333</SECOND>
<HEAD>Month-Long International Human Rights Conference Opens</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ELAINE GANLEY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>PARIS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Bulgaria took the offensive Tuesday at the opening
session of an international human rights conference by blaming
Turkey for recent violence involving Bulgaria's ethnic Turks.
   The monthlong conference is to review human rights progress
among the 35 nations that are signatories of the 1975 Helsinki
Final Act.
   It also is expected to single out nations accused of specific
abuses, and Romania and Bulgaria are expected to take the brunt of
criticism.
   About 20 foreign ministers attended the opening of the monthlong
conference, the first of three mandated by the Vienna review
committee of the Conference on Security and Cooperation in Europe,
which ended in January.
   In one of the first speeches, Foreign Minister Petar Mladenov of
Bulgaria accused ``foreign circles'' of being behind recent
disturbances in his country in which ethnic Turks reportedly have
been killed.
   The Bulgarian delegation made available the text of a speech by
President Todor Zhivkov that said ``certain circles in the Republic
of Turkey'' have launched a ``continuously escalating
anti-Bulgarian campaign.''
   ``This policy represents a gross interference in the internal
affairs of a sovereign state,'' the statement said.
   The Bulgarian president, whose speech was broadcast on Monday,
urged Turkey to open its border to all ``Bulgarian Moslems'' who
want to go there.
   Bulgaria has been deporting ethnic Turks it considers
undesirable. An estimated 300 have been forced to leave, most to
Austria and Yugoslavia. Many also have been picked up by Turkish
airliners for resettlement in Turkey.
   According to an official report, three people died in recent
ethnic unrest. Deportees have put the figure at up to 30. The
reports could not be confirmed independently.
   Mladenov said Bulgaria wanted to discuss the problems with
``realism and good will.''
   The second human rights conference is to be held in Copenhagen
in 1990 and a third in Moscow in 1991.
</TEXT>
