<FIRST>u i AM-Bush-Summit 1st-LdWritethru a0605 05-30 0845</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Bush-Summit, 1st-Ld Writethru, a0605,840</SECOND>
<HEAD>Bush Uses NATO Summit to Send Message to Critics Back Home</HEAD>
<HEAD>EDS: subs 18th graf pvs, The NATO, to fix spelling of sow; picks
up 19th graf, With that</HEAD>
<HEAD>An AP News Analysis</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By WALTER R. MEARS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Special Correspondent</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BONN, West Germany (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   With his arms control challenge to
Moscow, President Bush also sent a message home _ an almost
taunting told-you-so to the political critics who said he was
lagging instead of leading.
   It is, of course, in loftier, more diplomatic language. And when
he was asked whether he'd intended that message, he said not. And
laughed.
   ``I'm not going to get into that game with the Congress,'' he
said during a news conference at NATO on Tuesday. ``Or anyone
else.''
   But there was no masking the president's satisfaction in telling
detractors and everyone else that he'd known what he was doing
during the long diplomatic dry spell.
   He said he'd been studying, planning and preparing what the
White House called the most far-reaching Western proposal for
conventional arms control since World War II.
   Bush noted that his administration took a bit of a hammering in
Congress and elsewhere for its go-slow, silent treatment of Mikhail
S. Gorbachev's Soviet peace offensive.
   But he said it hadn't bothered him. ``I haven't felt under seige
in the United States because I knew exactly what we wanted to do,''
the president said.
   After presenting his arms control proposal to the Atlantic
allies on Monday, Bush said ``this is the way we plan to lead _
lead the alliance and lead the Free World.''
   It was a measure of his mood. He'd been accused of a failure to
lead.
   Bush said at a news conference the criticism hadn't bothered
him, that he's weathered enough political criticism to become
immune. ``I just kind of write it off _ I was elected to do what I
think is right.''
   Bush emerged from the 40th anniversary NATO summit in Brussels
with a strengthened hand both internationally and domestically. His
call for swift East-West troop, tank and aircraft cuts was a
dramatic summit debut for the new leader at the NATO table. Bush
said he meant to ``transform the military map of Europe,'' and
whether or not his proposal achieves that aim, he is on the
initiative now. He relished the role.
   ``Here we go now, on the offense, with a proposal that is bold
and tests whether the Soviet Union will move,'' he said Monday.
   That was parlayed with a deal fashioned by NATO foreign
ministers early Tuesday, after a long night of negotiations, to
settle an intramural dispute about negotiations on short-range
nuclear missiles.
   It was a compromise on Bush terms, overriding earlier West
German demands for immediate talks with the Soviet Union on
short-range missile reductions. The NATO settlement calls for those
talks to await an East-West agreement to reduce troops and
conventional weapons. And the short-range missiles will stay put
until there have been actual cuts in conventional forces.
   ``The successful results of this summit have given us a double
hit,'' Bush rejoiced.
   But he crowed with care, so as not to rub it in for the West
Germans, his next hosts. His spokesman, Marlin Fitzwater, had
called the missile deal a victory for the United States and for
NATO. Bush amended that. ``I don't view it as a victory for the
United States _ I view it as a victory for the alliance,'' he said.
   The president also said the West Germans had strongly supported
the missile settlement.
   The NATO deal, said to have been designed largely by Secretary
of State James A. Baker III, cleared the table of an issue that had
threatened to sow discord at the summit.
   With that deal in hand, Bush and West German Chancellor Helmut
Kohl took separate commuter-length flights to Bonn for their
one-on-one meetings. After the first one, they joined in praise of
the NATO agreements.
   Kohl has been under political pressure to get negotiations going
immediately on the short-range missiles, almost all of them based
in West Germany, but he told Bush: ``You are a friend among
friends.''
   Neither admitted to any German misgivings about the short-range
missile compromise. ``I think we were all just winners in
Brussels,'' said Kohl.
   He also said Bush's visit would be helpful politically to him in
the West German elections that are due next year.
   Bush goes from West Germany to London, and returns to the United
States on Friday, strengthened politically as he confronts the
domestic agenda. He is likely to challenge the Democratic Congress
with his first veto even before he gets back to Washington, to
block a minimum wage increase he says is excessive and therefore
likely to cost jobs.
   He'll head home satisfied and, perhaps, a bit feisty. ``Whatever
political arrows might have been fired my way, it's all been worth
it,'' Bush said.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>EDITOR'S NOTE </NOTE>
<TEXT>
   Walter R. Mears, vice president and columnist
for The Associated Press, has covered politics and the presidency
for more than 25 years.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
