<FILEID>AP-NR-05-30-89 1912EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i AM-Argentina-Economy     05-30 0416</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Argentina-Economy,0430</SECOND>
<HEAD>Unrest is Outgrowth of Economic Crisis</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Argentina</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BUENOS AIRES, Argentina (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The looting and fighting in the
streets that have shaken more than a dozen Argentine cities and
towns stem from an economic crisis of the first magnitude _ one
that has been simmering for months.
   The Central Bank, which had been selling U.S. dollars to prop up
the austral and fend off inflation, stopped the practice in
February. Argentina's national currency has plunged in value by
more than 90 percent since then.
   Inflation rocketed from 9.6 percent in February to 17 percent in
March, 33.4 percent in April and possibly 70 percent this month.
Private economists say it may top 100 percent in June.
   Wages failed to keep pace. Suddenly, food, medicine and other
basics were beyond the reach of hundreds of thousands of Argentines.
   Doubling the national minimum wage on Tuesday to 8,700 australs
a month, about $50, is not likely to help much.
   ``What people are earning doesn't enable them to put even one
meal a day on the table. That's a basic fact that society has to
deal with,'' said Beverly Keene of the human rights group Peace and
Justice Service.
   Inflation is but one facet of the crisis.
   The national budget is in deficit. The government of President
Raul Alfonsin is hard-pressed either to lay off employees or
further increase charges for telephones, electricity and other
public services, which were raised 40 percent only two weeks ago.
   The foreign debt has climbed to $59 billion. Annual interest
payments of $6 billion amount to about twice the annual trade
surplus, removing that as a source of investment. Interest has not
been paid since last year.
   Economic deterioration is compounded by political paralysis. The
governing Radical Civic Union lost national elections on May 14,
but President-elect Carlos Menem of the Peronist Party is not due
to take office until Dec. 10.
   Alfonsin has the authority to rule, but Menem has the crucial
public support.
   Origins of the economic crisis date to the 1950s. Argentines
since that decade have lived with a state-managed economy, powerful
labor unions and political polarization between the two main
parties and the military. Inflation has been triple-digit since the
1970s.
   Alfonsin, 62, has tried since his inauguration 5{ years ago to
reduce the role of the state, diminish the power of organized
labor, curtail the military's political ambitions and spark an
economy that has stagnated for a decade.
   In almost every area, he failed.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
