<FIRST>r i AM-Panama     05-30 0557</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Panama,0574</SECOND>
<HEAD>Opposition Leader Says Regime Holds 89 Political Prisoners</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RICHARD HERZFELDER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>PANAMA CITY, Panama (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The government controlled by Gen.
Manuel Antonio Noriega is holding at least 89 political prisoners
including opposition party officials, two opposition leaders said
Tuesday.
   ``The prisoners are nothing more than hostages,'' opposition
presidential candidate Guillermo Endara said in an interview with
The Associated Press.
   ``They (the Panamanian Defense Forces commanded by Noriega) take
people prisoner for a while and then if things are quiet they just
let them go,'' he said. ``They take people off the street, people
who were just watching a parade.''
   First vice presidential candidate Ricardo Arias Calderon said
six people arrested May 24 while marching with the opposition
candidates to a meeting with a delegation from the Organization of
American States ``have not even been allowed to see their
families.''
   ``For most (of the 89) there has been no reply to habeas corpus
or other judicial petitions, showing how deeply the judiciary is
subordinated to the interests of the military dictatorship,'' Arias
Calderon told a news conference.
   International observers at the May 7 election said the
opposition, led by Endara, won the elections by about a 3-1 margin.
But the official returns were seized by troops and on May 10 the
vote was nullified by the government's Electoral Tribunal.
   The OAS, at a meeting in Washington, crticitized Noriega, the
nullification and the beating of opposition candidates. It urged a
quick transfer of power and sent a delegation to Panama.
   Arias Calderon distributed a list of 89 people he said were
political prisoners and it included opposition spokesman Luis
Martins; legislative candidate Felipe Escobar; Antonio Galvez, one
of Arias Calderon's bodyguards, and Jose Guillermo Lutrel, a
Panamanian Human Rights Committee election observer.
   He said the total held was more than 100 but some had not been
identified.
   Many of the prisoners were accused of threatening the security
of the state and were summarily sentenced to a year in jail by a
judge on the night of their arrest, according to Arias Calderon.
   He said such sentences often can be converted into fines payable
at the rate of a dollar a day but relatives of the prisoners had
been told nobody is available to collect the fines.
   Messages left for a Defense Forces spokesman for comment on
Arias Calderon's charges were not returned. The Defense Forces have
not commented on the issue despite previous requests.
   Endara said about half of the 170 to 200 people arrested during
and after the election have been released and it appears others are
being freed one-by-one and often without paying a fine.
   ``They haven't released anybody who is well-known, however,''
said Endara.
   Arias Calderon noted the OAS delegation is to file a report on
June 5 and the OAS council of ministers will meet the following day.
   He said again the opposition wants the OAS to recognize its
victory and impose a diplomatic and political quarantine on Panama
if Noriega and his hand-picked government refuse to surrender power.
   Arias Calderon said the opposition would continue to insist that
Noriega and the Panamanian Defense Forces be included in political
negotiations, saying they hold the real power.
   Noriega has said the political parties should settle the
dispute, and Arias Calderon said Noriega is ``trying to hide behind
a smokescreen.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
