<FILEID>AP-NR-05-30-89 1923EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r w AM-US-ThirdWorldDebt     05-30 0465</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-US-Third World Debt,470</SECOND>
<HEAD>Banks Look to Official Aid on Debt Forgiveness</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By CARL HARTMAN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Commercial banks expect to hear at a meeting
in Madrid, Spain, on June 7 what help they can expect from
governments in reducing Third World debt, an international banking
official told Congress Tuesday.
   Horst Schulmann, a West German, heads the Institute of
International Finance, a Washington-based organization that
represents 182 big banks in the United States and 38 other
countries.
   He was testifying at a hearing on progress under Treasury
Secretary Nicholas F. Brady's March proposal for debt reduction.
   ``Debt forgiveness is equivalent to foreign aid, but banks are
not in the foreign aid business,'' Schulmann said.
   ``If banks are coerced into taking large losses under the Brady
initiative, they will be unwilling to provide addditional ...
financing.''
   Third World countries owe about half their $1.2 trillion debt to
commercial banks, according to Rep. Sam Gejdenson, D-Comn. He
chaired the hearing as head of the subcommittee on international
economic policy of the House Foreign Affairs Committee.
   Members of Congress and Treasury Undersecretary David Mulford
have warned banks that unless they cooperate with Brady, there
could be action against them from the U.S. government.
   Schulmann said the Madrid meeting will include Michel Camdessus
of France, who heads the International Monetary Fund. The fund,
owned by 151 govwernments, has promised to aside a part of its
future loans for debt reduction. Directors of its sister
organization, the World Bank, met on Tuesday to decide what role it
will take. Barber Conable, the bank's U.S. president, will also go
to Madrid.
   ``We are not planning to do anything for the commercial banks,''
said Frank Vogl, chief spokesman for Conable. ``But there are many
things we want to do for our member countries.''
   Also expected at the Madrid meeting is E. Gerald Corrigan,
president of the Federal Reserve Bank of New York. The federal
reserve would have an important role in making the changes in
official regulations that U.S. banks would like to see as part of a
debt-forgiveness package.
   Another witness, Eugene H. Rotberg, executive vice president of
Merrill Lynch &amp; Co. Inc. and former vice president of the World
Bank, said debt reduction will not reduce the amount of interest
countries would pay from their own resources, unless the reduction
is greater than new loans the banks will be asked to make.
   ``The fact is, in recent years, many debtors have met only about
half of their debt service obligations _ the balance comes from the
banks themselves (as new loans),'' Rotberg added.
   Last year debtor countries paid out $26 billion as interest,
Gejdenson said, adding that the United States and other major
governments had helped by underwriting the World Bank and
International Monetary Fund.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890530-0161 </DOCNO>
