<FIRST>u a AM-WeatherpageWeather     05-30 0436</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Weatherpage Weather,0447</SECOND>
<HEAD>Strong Thunderstorms Over Wyoming and From Iowa To Michigan</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Strong thunderstorms brought locally heavy rain, hail and a
tornado to the upper Midwest on Tuesday, and in Wyoming
thunderstorms produced several tornadoes or funnel clouds.
   Thunderstorms extended from eastern Iowa to central and southern
Wisconsin and southern Lake Michigan, producing locally heavy rain
and large hail. The storms developed in moist, unstable air along a
stationary front stretching from southwestern Kansas to northern
Iowa and southern Wisconsin.
   A tornado was spawned by a severe thunderstorm during the
morning near Bradford, Iowa.
   Hail 2 inches in diameter was reported in Prairie Du Chien,
Wis., and hail as big as golf balls fell in Bowler, Wis.
   One to 4 inches of rain fell from central Wisconsin into Lower
Michigan, causing highway and street flooding in Wisconsin's Fond
du Lac County.
   Showers and thunderstorms fell in sections of Utah, southern
Idaho and western Wyoming.
   At least four tornadoes or funnel clouds were reported over
southwestern Wyoming, but no damages or injuries were reported, the
National Weather Service said.
   Up to an inch of rain fell on the Wind River Mountains in
western Wyoming, and higher elevations received 3 to 5 inches of
snow.
   Scattered showers fell over the northern Plains, the Florida
Peninsula, the lower Great Lakes, and sections of the middle and
northern Atlantic Coast.
   Temperatures were only in the 40s and 50s from the Great Basin
containing Nevada and western Utah to the northern Rockies, the
northern Plains, northern and western Nebraska, the upper
Mississippi Valley and the upper Great Lakes.
   Temperatures around the nation at 3 p.m. EDT ranged from 41
degrees at Pocatello, Idaho, to 98 at Carlsbad, N.M. Tuesday
morning's low in the 48 contiguous states was 19 at Truckee, Calif.
   The forecast for Wednesday called for scattered showers and
thunderstorms from New England to the upper Ohio Valley, the Great
Lakes, sections of the upper and middle Mississippi Valley and the
central Plains, and scattered showers across the northern Plains,
the central Rockies and the Great Basin.
   Highs were predicted in the 50s and 60s from the Great Basin and
the northern Rockies to the northern Plains and the upper
Mississippi Valley into Upper Michigan; in the 90s from inland
Southern California and the desert Southwest to the southern
Rockies, the southern Plains, much of Kansas, the lower Mississippi
and Missouri valleys, the southern half of the Ohio Valley and the
Gulf Coast states to the middle and southern Atlantic Coast; and in
the 70s and 80s across much of the rest of the nation.
</TEXT>
