<FILEID>AP-NR-05-30-89 1931EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r w AM-PlutoniumPlant     05-30 0343</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Plutonium Plant,350</SECOND>
<HEAD>Scientists, Arms Experts Urge Scrapping of Plutonium Project</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A group of 29 scientists and arms control
experts called on Congress Tuesday to reconsider plans to build a
plant in Idaho to produce plutonium for nuclear weapons.
   In a letter to the chairmen of the House and Senate armed
services committees and other key legislators, the experts said the
plant is not needed for national security and would undermine U.S.
efforts to limit the spread of nuclear arms.
   The Bush administration is seeking authorization to begin
building a Special Isotope Separation Plant at the Idaho National
Engineering Laboratory, near Idaho Falls. The plant would use a new
laser technology to convert fuel-grade plutonium from Energy
Department stockpiles to weapon-grade plutonium.
   The letter, dated May 26, was signed by Paul Leventhal,
president of the Nuclear Control Institute, a private group
concerned with nuclear proliferation problems.
   Among other signers were retired Adm. Thomas Davies, a former
assistant director of the U.S. Arms Control and Disarmament Agency;
Peter Bradford, a former member of the Nuclear Regulatory
Commission, and Peter Clausen, research director for the Union of
Concerned Scientists and a former CIA and Energy Department analyst.
   The group said it was concerned that the technology could spread
to other nations that could convert fuel-grade plutonium from
civilian plants to develop a nuclear arsenal. It also expressed
concern that the U.S. plant eventually could be used to purify
plutonium from U.S. commercial nuclear reactors, even though this
is specifically outlawed by the 1982 Atomic Energy Act.
   ``For both these reasons, going forward with the SIS plant could
severely compromise U.S. non-proliferation objectives,'' the letter
said.
   ``In view of the acknowledged surplus of plutonium in the U.S.
nuclear arsenal, there are no clear national security benefits that
offset the obvious nuclear proliferation and terrorism risks ...''
posed by use of the plant, they added.
   The isotope separation technology is still under development at
an Energy Department laboratory in California, although the
administration wants to break ground on the Idaho plant this year.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890530-0163 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-05-30-89 1937EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i AM-Palestinians-Iran     05-30 0697</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Palestinians-Iran,0720</SECOND>
<HEAD>Radical Arab Group Leader Meets Iranian Official In Syria</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ED BLANCHE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NICOSIA, Cyprus (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Ahmed Jibril, leader of a Palestinian
group U.S. officials suspect was behind the bombing of a Pan Am
jet, met Iran's Foreign Minister Ali Akbar Velayati in Syria this
month, diplomatic sources said.
   The May 22 meeting came as Jibril's radical group, the Popular
Front for the Liberation of Palestine-General Command, renewed
denials it was involved in the Pan Am bombing Dec. 21 that killed
270 people.
   U.S. and other Western intelligence officials believe the
Popular Front carried out the bombing at Iran's request in
retaliation for the U.S. Navy's downing of an Iran Air jetliner
last July in the Persian Gulf. All 290 people aboard died.
   The sources, speaking on condition of anonymity, said Velayati
and Jibril discussed Iran's support for the Palestinian struggle
against Israel.
   They said Jibril asserted that armed struggle was the only way
the Palestinians will regain their homeland.
   Like Jibril and other Syrian-backed Palestinian leaders, Iran
has denounced PLO chairman Yasser Arafat's peace initiative,
renunciation of terrorism and recognition of Israel.
   The sources said Velayati was in Damascus, the Syrian capital,
for consultations with President Hafez Assad before last week's
Arab summit conference, which endorsed Arafat's initiative and
sought ways to end the Lebanese civil war.
   Jibril denies involvement in the Pan Am bombing. But he has said
his group makes bombs similar to the one investigators believed
exploded in the plane over Lockerbie, Scotland on a flight from
Frankfurt via London to New York.
   Iran also denies involvement.
   Popular Front spokesman Fahd Shrourou said on May 21 in Damascus
in decrying U.S. allegations: ``We're not agents for Iran or anyone
else. They didn't ask us. They're not allowed to ask us for such
things.''
   He said that ``American insistence on blaming us is because
they've failed to get any evidence'' firmly linking his group with
the Pan Am bombing.
   Diplomats and counterterrorism specialists believe Jibril and
Palestinian terrorist mastermind Abu Nidal forged new links over
the last year with Iranian radicals and their Shiite Moslem allies
in Lebanon.
   The radical resurgence in Tehran; the confrontation with the
West over British author Salman Rushdie's novel, ``The Satanic
Verses,'' which many Moslem say blasphemes Islam, and opposition by
hard-line Palestinian factions to Arafat's initiative by the
Palestine Liberation Organization would provide fertile ground for
such an alliance.
   Iranian Parliament Speaker Hashemi Rafsanjani asked Palestinians
this month to kill five Westerners for every Palestinian slain by
Israelis in the uprising in the occupied territories and to attack
Western targets.
   He later claimed he was misinterpreted. But his remarks were
seen as reflecting the militancy of radicals now ascendant in
Tehran.
   The diplomatic sources said evidence against the the Popular
Front for the Liberation of Palestine-General Command in the Pan Am
sabotage ``is circumstantial, but it's there.''
   They cited the arrest of 14 Popular Front activists in West
Germany last October, including a top Jibril lieutenant, Kassem
Dalkamoni.
   The men had Czechoslovak-made Semtex explosives hidden in a
candy wrapper and a bomb hidden in a Japanese-made cassette radio
linked to a barometric device.
   Investigators have concluded the Pan Am bomb contained Semtex,
was hidden in a cassette radio packed in a suitcase and was
triggered by a barometric sensor.
   Popular Front officials said the men arrested in West Germany
were heading for the Middle East to attack Israeli targets.
   Shrourou said: ``We don't carry out attacks in Europe because
that would have a negative effect on the support of the EEC
(European Economic Community) nations for the Palestinian
struggle.''
   However, Western European governments have generally supported
Arafat's efforts to negotiate a settlement with Israel, a move
Jibril and his fellow radicals consider a betrayal of the
Palestinian cause.
   Diplomats and counterterrorism specialists doubt the Popular
Front's claim it would not hit targets in Europe.
   Police in Sweden last week arraigned three men they said were
linked to the Popular Front for the Liberation of Palestine-General
Command for suspected complicity in the 1985 bombing of a Danish
synagogue and similar attacks on U.S. and Israeli airline offices
in Denmark, Sweden and the Netherlands.
</TEXT>
