<FIRST>r p AM-CongressSuccessors     05-30 0451</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Congress Successors,0462</SECOND>
<HEAD>Candidates Lining Up Quickly for Coelho, Wright Could Run Again And
Win</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-House Leadership, Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Potential candidates began lining up quickly during the Memorial
Day holiday weekend to vie for the chance to succeed Rep. Tony
Coelho, the House Majority Whip from California who announced he is
resigning.
   But while House Speaker Jim Wright is thought to be planning to
resign in the face of an ethics investigation, the GOP chairman in
Wright's home county in Texas says that if the Democrat decided to
stay in office, it's unlikely anyone could oust him from the seat
he has held 34 years.
   A special election will be required to fill the San Joaquin
Valley congressional seat Coelho, a Democrat, is vacating.
   Democratic Assemblymen Gary Condit of Ceres, Jim Costa of Fresno
and Rusty Areias of Los Banos haven't said either yes or no yet,
but Condit and Costa at least are expected to run.
   On the Republican side, Modesto Mayor Carol Whiteside is firmly
in the race, and Assemblyman Bill Jones and Fresno County District
Attorney Ed Hunt are considering running for the office.
   California Gov. George Deukmejian will schedule a special
election in the 5th Congressional District, probably in late August
or early September, with a runoff, if needed, during the November
general election.
   In Wright's case, the Texas Democrat probably has a safe seat in
Congress as long as he wants it, despite the ethics investigation
that some say could force him to resign, says Steve Hollern,
chairman of the Tarrant County GOP.
   The Republican Party made its last concerted effort to oust
Wright in 1980, winning just 39 percent of the vote, and Wright had
no opposition when he sought re-election last year, months after
the ethics probe was launched.
   ``I think if Jim Wright decides not to stay in Congress ... the
whole ball game changes,'' Hollern said Tuesday. ``If he stays
there, I don't think we can beat him.''
   Wright has been charged with 69 violations of House rules. He
said Tuesday he will announce this week whether he will resign.
   In Congress, Rep. Thomas S. Foley, D-Wash., currently the
majority leader, is the only candidate to replace Wright as speaker
if the Texan gives up the job.
   A four-way contest is in the offing for Coelho's job as majority
whip. Reps. William H. Gray III, D-Pa., chairman of the House
Democratic Caucus; Beryl Anthony, D-Ark., chairman of the
Democratic Congressional Campaign Committee, and Rep. David Bonior,
D-Mich., the chief deputy whip, are all actively campaigning for
the post. Rep. Henry A. Waxman, D-Calif., a powerful member of the
Energy and Commerce Committee, also was eyeing the race.
</TEXT>
