<FILEID>AP-NR-05-30-89 1942EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i AM-Yugoslavia     05-30 0394</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Yugoslavia,0407</SECOND>
<HEAD>Protester Killed, Several Injured in Kosovo</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BELGRADE, Yugoslavia (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A protester was reported killed and
several were injured Tuesday during a confrontation with police in
Kosovo province, where more than two dozen people have died in
ethnic violence this year.
   A delegation from the European Parliament visited the southern
province to assess human rights abuses there.
   Tanjug, the official news agency, said the delegation would meet
with officials of the predominantly ethnic Albanian province about
human rights violations under a state of emergency imposed after
riots by ethnic Albanians in February and March.
   It said police and demonstrators used firearms Tuesday in
Podujevo, 20 miles north of Pristina, the provincial capital.
   About 50 ethnic Albanians were involved in the protest, Tanjug
said, but sources in the area said there were 80 people, some
carrying banners or Albanian flags.
   The Tanjug report did not give the number of people injured or
say whether the person killed was shot to death. It said protesters
hurled stones at police.
   ``Because of the aggressive behavior of the demonstrators, the
policemen were forced to intervene,'' Tanjug said. ``Witnesses said
both sides used firearms.''
   A source said privately it was believed to be the largest
Albanian protest in two months. Emergency measures imposed after
the February-March riots forbid public gatherings of more than
three people.
   Tanjug said earlier the five-member European Parliament
delegation, led by Julian Grimaldos of Spain, met on Sunday in
Belgrade with senior officials of the Serbian republic. Kosovo is
an automous province within Serbia, Yugoslavia's largest republic.
   Ethnic Albanians, about 85 percent of Kosovo's 1.8 million
people, oppose constitutional changes made by Serbia that give it
greater say in the province's affairs.
   Serbia says the amendments were necessary to protect minority
Slavs from what they describe as harassment and persecution by
ethnic Albanians.
   At least 24 people, including two policemen, were killed and
hundreds wounded in the riots earlier this year. About 800 ethnic
Albanians were arrested.
   Official sources say 237 other ethnic Albanians, including
former provincial Communist Party chief Azem Vllasi and other
prominent politicians, businessmen and intellectuals, were detained
without charges under national emergency laws.
   ``We have not been informed whether the delegation plans to
contact any of the detainees,'' Francoise Blondel, a spokesman for
the European Commission, told The Associated Press. He said
Yugoslav authorities prepared the delegation's agenda.
</TEXT>
