<FIRST>r i AM-Obit-Lacey     05-30 0183</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Obit-Lacey,0187</SECOND>
<HEAD>Battle of Britain Pilot Dies</HEAD>
<DATELINE>COTTINGHAM, England (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Ace fighter pilot James ``Ginger''
Lacey, who downed 18 enemy aircraft in the Battle of Britain, the
most for any pilot, and 27 planes in all during World War II, died
Tuesday, his widow said. He was 72.
   Lacey, who survived nine downings himself, was diagnosed as
having cancer of the throat four months ago and died at a hospital
in Cottingham, eastern England, said his wife, Sheila. He also is
survived by two daughters.
   The 18 planes that Lacey shot down during the 1940 battle
between British and German aircraft over London and southern
England included a Heinkel 111 aircraft returning from a successful
bombing raid on Buckingham Palace.
   Lacey was shot down nine times during the war while flying
Spitfire fighters as leader of 501 Squadron based near Kenley in
Surrey, and won the Distinguished Flying Medal and Bar, the Croix
de Guerre and other medals for courage.
   After the war, Lacey ran an air freight business and later
taught flying at an airfield near Bridlington in eastern England.
</TEXT>
