<FILEID>AP-NR-05-30-89 1908EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u w AM-PepperReax     05-30 0964</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Pepper Reax,900</SECOND>
<HEAD>Pepper Saluted as Enthusiastic Champion of the People</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOHN KING</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Congressional colleagues and elected officials
from around the country saluted Rep. Claude D. Pepper on Tuesday as
a tireless and tenacious advocate for the poor and elderly during a
more than half-century career in public service.
   ``In the bosom of that small, gentle man beat the heart of a
giant _ a heart that felt the pain of a world where children go to
sleep hungry and where the old die alone,'' Rep. Joe Moakley,
D-Mass., said shortly after the longtime Florida Democratic
congressman died at Walter Reed Army Hospital.
   President Bush took time out from a state dinner in Bonn, West
Germany, to salute Pepper, to whom Bush presented a Medal of
Freedom during a hospital visit last week.
   ``Claude Pepper gave definition and meaning to the concept of
public service,'' Bush said. ``He fought for the poor and the
elderly in his own determined way. Those who agreed with him were
proud to follow his banner. Those who disagreed with him always
respected him. Claude Pepper was a gentleman, a noble human being.
America will miss him. Barbara and I will miss him, too.''
   Former President Reagan, in a statement issued in California,
said, ``The lives of millions of Americans are better because of
Claude Pepper's work. He was a patriot who loved his country and he
will be deeply missed.''
   House Speaker Jim Wright said he expected the House and Senate
to adopt a resolution on Wednesday clearing the way for Pepper to
lie in state in the Capitol Rotunda on Thursday.
   ``For longer than the rest of us, he was a moving force in
American life,'' Wright said. ``He was always a voice for the
voiceless and a helping hand for the helpless,'' he said.
   Such sentiments were echoed by officials from Pepper's home
state of Florida and by his friends and colleagues in Congress,
where at 88 he was the oldest member. All spoke of his commitment
and inspiration to the elderly. Others spoke of his tireless
advocacy of other causes as well. Some commented on the mark he
left on them.
   ``Like all Floridians, I am deeply saddened by the death of
Claude Pepper,'' Florida Gov. Bob Martinez said. ``The sense of
loss we all feel is softened by the warm memory of a lifetime full
of achievements on behalf of all people. ... Through his words and
through his actions, Claude Pepper proved that older Americans need
not slow down, need not stop contributing, need not give up on
improving their lives and those of others. He was a rare human
being and we are all richer for his presence among us.''
   Florida's U.S. senators also paid homage to Pepper.
   ``Claude Pepper was one of America's political giants of this
century,'' said Sen. Bob Graham, D-Fla., adding: ``Throughout his
career, Pepper was a champion for justice _ for civil rights, for a
prepared America to defeat Nazi tyranny and for dignity for older
Americans. America will miss this champion, but we will honor his
memory by renewing our dedication to his ideals of justice and
human dignity.''
   Republican Sen. Connie Mack of Florida said: ``Congressman
Pepper will be missed _ not only by those of us who served with him
_ but by Americans everywhere whose lives are now better because of
his dedication and leadership. To say that Congressman Pepper was
an institution is an understatement of the commitment and
contribution he made to improving the lives of individual
Americans.''
   Horace B. Deets, executive director of the American Association
of Retired Persons, said of Pepper: ``More than anyone in our
lifetime, he helped us as a nation realize the contributions that
older Americans can make to our nation if given a chance.''
   Moakley was visiting Pepper last week when Bush presented Pepper
with the Medal of Freedom. Moakley said Pepper had summoned staff
members to his hospital bed to brief him on pending legislation.
   ``Claude was a fighter, and he died fighting,'' Moakley said.
   Many colleagues promised to advance Pepper's agenda.
   ``Congress has spent the past 50 years trying to keep up with
Claude Pepper and we will be spending many more years carrying on
his work,'' said Sen. Edward M. Kennedy, D-Mass. ``On issue after
issue, he was the conscience of Congress and the country.''
   Sen. John Heinz, R-Pa., said ``every American who believes in
integrity and honest public service will mourn his passing. ...
Claude Pepper leaves a legacy so alive and powerful that he is far
from lost.''
   Still others recalled Pepper's work dating back more than 50
years on the nation's major social programs.
   ``With his passing, so passes the last of the New Dealers who
reshaped our society with such programs as Social Security and,
later, Medicare,'' said Rep. Norman Mineta, D-Calif. ``Claude
Pepper embodied the hopes and aspirations of the American people to
build a better life for themselves by seeing to the needs of their
neighbors.''
   The tributes came from Democrats and Republicans alike.
   House Minority Leader Bob Michel, R-Ill., called Pepper's career
``certainly one of the most extraordinary in the history of
American politics. When Claude Pepper spoke on the floor of the
House during debate, the House was hushed, hanging on every
eloquent word. He was one of a kind and we will miss him.''
   Senate Majority Leader George J. Mitchell, D-Maine, said that
Pepper ``gave of his energy and his support for the cause of older
Americans, not only because it was the right thing to do but
because it was part of his view of our nation that the care of
those who built it should remain a concern of those who inherit
it.''
</TEXT>
