<FIRST>u i AM-Soviet 2ndLd-Writethru   05-30 0973</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Soviet, 2nd Ld-Writethru,a0722,0998</SECOND>
<HEAD>Gorbachev: Defense Spending Billions More Than Previously Reported</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: SUB grafs 11-17, `Leonid T...he said' with 7 grafs to ADD legislative
initiatives. Picks up 18th graf, `Gorbachev's announcement...' with minor
editing to trim; ADDS 3 grafs at end UPDATING with debate on Georgia.</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhotos MOSB2,5</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOHN-THOR DAHLBURG</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MOSCOW (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Mikhail S. Gorbachev uncovered one of the
Kremlin's best-kept secrets Tuesday by disclosing that the Soviet
Union will spend about $118 billion on defense this year, about
four times what it previously acknowledged.
   ``I am announcing this real figure of military expenditures to
the Congress of People's Deputies: 77.3 billion rubles,'' the
Soviet president told the 2,250-member national parliament to gasps
of astonishment.
   Gorbachev pledged defense spending would be cut by 10 billion
rubles ($15.3 billion) by the end of 1991 as the Soviet Union
redirects its resources to revive the Soviet economy and ease world
tensions by reducing arms.
   ``Today we can ensure security by political and diplomatic
means,'' Gorbachev declared during an address on foreign and
domestic policy. ``This makes it possible to cut down on military
expenditures ... without any detriment to the defense capability of
our country.''
   The Central Intelligence Agency estimates annual Soviet defense
spending at 115 billion to 125 billion rubles, roughly equivalent
to Pentagon expenditures of $300 billion, Richard Kaufman, an
expert with the Joint Economic Committee of Congress, said in
Washington.
   In Gorbachev's 95-minute address to the Congress on the state of
the country's foreign and domestic policy, he also:
   _ Proposed creation of a special legislative commission to
review the decades-old system of privileges for the elite.
   _ Acknowledged complaints that government ministries ``are
restructuring very slowly, if at all,'' and urged deputies to
question government ministers on why they are dragging their feet
on reforms,
   _ Announced local elections will be postponed from fall to the
spring of 1990 to give lawmakers a chance to correct problems in
the electoral system that arose during the spring campaign.
   _ Pledged that the ruling Communist Party he heads is open to
talks with any social group or organization backing reform.
   He also outlined a system of legislative oversight that would
invest the full-time legislature, or the Supreme Soviet, and
national parliament with broad powers to change the constitution,
question government officials and review state spending.
   Gorbachev said the Supreme Soviet should create a commission
that would act as a constitutional court to ensure the transition
to a nation ruled by law and respectful of individual rights.
   His moves seemed aimed at creating expert, policy-making bodies
independent of the Communist Party bureaucrats who have run the
country for decades and whom Gorbachev blames for slowing his
reforms.
   Leonid I. Abalkin, director of the official Economics Institute,
said Gorbachev's surprise disclosure on Soviet defense spending was
aimed at ending distrust in East-West arms reductions talks caused
by decades of Kremlin secrecy.
   As recently as October, allocations for the Soviet military in
the official 1989 government budget were listed to be the same as
in 1988: 20.2 billion rubles ($32 billion).
   Gorbachev did not say what his ``real figure'' embraced, but
Maj. Gen. Vladimir Kuklev, deputy chairman of the General Staff,
told a news briefing the sum ``includes expenses for purchasing
weapons ... as well as research and development.''
   Abalkin indicated some government operations with military
applications, such as space programs, still were not included in
the new figure.
   Gorbachev's announcement is unlikely to settle the question of
how much money the Soviets spend on defense. Many questions remain
about how the price of Soviet weapons are set, and the official
exchange rate for the ruble, which makes the 77.3-billion-ruble
defense budget equal to $118 billion, artificially inflates the
value of the ruble.
   Abalkin said Soviet defense spending was about 9 percent of the
country's gross national product, the sum of all goods and services
produced. Asked why previous official figures were much lower, he
said they represented only ``what we could call the budget of the
Ministry of Defense'' and not appropriations for ministries in
charge of producing weaponry.
   The Washington think tank PlanEcon has figured Soviet defense
spending at 122 billion rubles, or 13 percent of GNP. The U.S.
defense budget, by comparison, is $300 billion or 6 percent of its
much larger GNP.
   Gorbachev announced in a Dec. 7, 1988, address to the United
Nations that the Soviet armed forces would be unilaterally reduced
by a half-million men to 3.7 million. He later said there would be
a 12 percent reduction in military manpower, a 14.2 percent cut in
the defense budget and a 19.5 percent cut in weapons production.
   But Western leaders continued to question the impact of the
promised cuts, pointing to what they regarded as unrealistic Soviet
defense spending figures. Gorbachev's speech was coolly received by
Communist Party maverick Boris N. Yeltsin.
   ``I was expecting something new, something entirely and
radically new that would take into account the crisis state of
society and the party,'' the former Moscow party leader said in an
interview.
   More than 400 Congress deputies, including Yeltsin and human
rights activist Andrei D. Sakharov, asked for an opportunity to
reply to Gorbachev's speech, and deputies trooped to the
microphones Tuesday, mostly to offer their own points of view on
issues of concern to their constituents, rather than to respond
directly to the president's remarks.
   The debate later Tuesday over the April 9 military action
against a pro-independence demonstration in the Georgian capital of
Tbilisi aroused far more passion than Gorbachev's speech.
   Tamaz Gamkrelidze, director of Georgia's Institute of Eastern
Studies, won stormy applause after demanding that Col. Gen. Igor
Rodionov, Caucasus military commander, be ousted from the Congress
for the assault.
   At least 19 people died in the clash with soldiers and another
was shot to death that night.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
