<HEAD>Convicted Congressman Plans Statement</HEAD>
<DATELINE>COLUMBUS, Ohio (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   U.S. Rep. Donald Lukens, convicted of
having sex with a 16-year-old girl, plans an announcement on his
personal and political future by the end of the week, his chief of
staff said Tuesday.
   ``He has a couple more folks to meet with before he makes any
decision about that. At this point, I stand by my statement that he
will run again,'' William Jarrell said in a telephone interview
from the congressman's Washington office.
   Lukens' two-year term expires in 1990. His misdemeanor
conviction does not make him ineligible to seek office again.
   Lukens, 58, was convicted Friday on a charge of contributing to
the delinquency and unruliness of a minor. The four-term Republican
faces a maximum of 180 days in jail and a $1,000 fine.
   Thomas Tyack, Lukens' attorney, has said he will appeal.
   U.S. Rep. Chalmers Wylie, senior Republican in Ohio's
congressional delegation, on Friday called on Lukens to resign,
saying it would be the ``gentlemanly thing to do.''
   Jarrell said Lukens spent much of Tuesday _ his first day back
on the job after the trial _ talking with constituents and meeting
with legislative aides ``to find out what's happening as far as his
legislative work goes and what he missed last week.''
