<FIRST>r i AM-Israel-Tags     05-30 0586</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Israel-Tags,0607</SECOND>
<HEAD>Palestinian Workers in Occupied Town Will Have To Wear Alien Tags</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Israel</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By SERGEI SHARGORODSKY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>JERUSALEM (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The mayor of the Jewish settlement of Ariel in
the occupied West Bank said Tuesday Palestinians working in the
town will be required to wear ``alien worker'' tags.
   Some members of Parliament condemned the plan, comparing it to
the yellow Stars of David that Jews were forced to wear in Nazi
Germany.
   Plans to control Arabs also were reported or underway in two
Jewish suburbs of Tel Aviv.
   In Petah Tikva construction began on an encampment for Arab
workers outside the town. Municial officials in Ramat Gan were
considering an ordinance to ban all Arab workers.
   Ariel Mayor Ron Nachman said in an interview the tag system was
adopted for security reasons.
   He said Palestinians working in Ariel would undergo daily
security checks and then would be issued tags identifying them as
``alien workers.''
   ``We don't have any control over the hundreds of Arabs who come
every day,'' he said. ``We want to be sure that no terrorists enter
Ariel. Getting a job is a privilege, not a right.''
   Nachman said about 400 Palestinians work in construction and
municipal services in Ariel, which has a population of 8,000. Those
workers are threatened by other Arabs who want to stop them from
assisting the Jewish settlers, and they ``deserve protection,'' he
added.
   The plan was denounced in Parliament during a debate on the
Palestinian uprising in the Israeli-occupied West Bank and Gaza
Strip.
   ``Those who give tags to the Arabs walk around freely,'' said
Yossi Sarid of the Citizens' Rights Movement. ``I just hope these
tags aren't yellow.''
   ``They are yellow,'' said Shulamit Aloni of Sarid's party
speaking on Israel television. ``I'm amazed they just propose a
tag, why shouldn't we tattoo their skin?''
   About 6 million Jews perished in the Nazi Holocaust, and many of
the victims and survivors had concentration camp numbers tattooed
on their arms.
   Twenty-five legislators from seven parties signed a petition
demanding that the government denounce Nachman's step.
   Among the signers were members of the right-wing Likud bloc of
Prime Minister Yitzhak Shamir, lawmakers from the leftist Labor
Party and even members of the nationalist Tsomet party, Israel
radio reported.
   There have been various efforts to control the movement of about
110,000 Arabs working in Israel since the uprising began in
December 1988.
   After stone-throwing battles in the southern Israeli towns of
Ashkelon and Ashdod the army on May 15 ordered all 50,000 Gazans
who were employed in Israel to return to the Gaza Strip.
   Shmuel Goren, Israel's coordinator for the occupied lands, said
Gazans would be given a special permit for work in Israel and the
system probably would be expanded to cover the estimated 60,000
West Bank Arabs who work in Israel.
   Petah Tikva Mayor Giora Lev said construction is to be completed
by the end of the week for the encampment for Arab workers being
built in the Sgula industrial zone at the entrance to the Tel Aviv
suburb.
   He said the camp will be equipped with running water and toilet
facilities.
   Palestinians will be banned from Petah Tikva unless they are
brought in from the encampment ty Jewish employers.
   ``I think it's for the benefit of the public,'' Lev said.
``Everybody says it's about time we impose some order. The
residents ....don't want to see them (Arabs) in their courtyards,
inside their houses. And we had four bombs in the last three
months.''
</TEXT>
