<HEAD>New Georgetown University President Named</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Rev. Leo J. O'Donovan was named the 47th
president of Georgetown University on Tuesday.
   O'Donovan, a 1956 Georgetown graduate, currently teaches at the
Weston School of Theology in Cambridge, Mass., and is a visiting
fellow at Georgetown's Woodstock Theological Center. He will
succeed the Rev. S. Timothy Healy, who is leaving the school to
become president of the New York City Public Library system.
   O'Donovan served on Georgetown's board of directors during two
periods, from 1971 to 1978 and from 1984 to the present. He also is
on the board of the University of Detroit and is past president of
the Catholic Theological Society of America.
   Georgetown, founded in 1789, is the nation's oldest Catholic
university and is currently celebrating its bicentennial.
