<SECOND>AM-Israel, 4th Ld-Writethru, a0757,0723</SECOND>
<HEAD>Soldiers Kill Guerrilla; Jewish Settlement Designates Arabs `Aliens'</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: SUBS 19th graf, `In Ariel...' to CORRECT translation to alien
workers, sted foreign workers.</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Israel-Victim, Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By EILEEN ALT POWELL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>JERUSALEM (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Israeli soldiers and allied militiamen killed a
guerrilla Tuesday who apparently was trying to cross the border
into Israel, the army reported.
   Israel radio said police were questioning 20 students at a
Hebrew study center in Nablus about an attack by Jewish settlers on
a West Bank village Monday in which a 13-year-old girl was shot to
death.
   Leaders of the Ariel settlement, founded in the occupied West
Bank in 1977, said Palestinians who work there will have to wear
tags identifying them as ``alien workers.''
   Soldiers wounded at least 15 Palestinians in the occupied
territories _ nine in the Gaza Strip and six in the West Bank _
according to Arab hospital officials.
   Arab reports said 8-month-old Mohammed Hamdan was hit in the
head by a plastic bullet when Israeli soldiers dispersed a march by
about 350 West Bank Palestinians in Tulkarem refugee camp. He was
reported in critical condition at Muqassed Hospital in east
Jerusalem.
   In south Lebanon, a guerrilla wearing military camouflage was
spotted by Israeli soldiers and allied South Lebanon Army
militiamen east of Marjayoun, an army statement said.
   He was wounded in an exchange of gunfire, then was pursued and
killed by the militia, it said. One militiaman was slightly wounded.
   Army sources said he was a Palestinian trying to infiltrate
Israel. Middle East Television, run by the U.S.-based Christian
Broadcasting Network, said the guerrilla was a survivor of a squad
intercepted Sunday in the ``security zone'' Israel maintains just
north of its border.
   Two guerrillas were killed Sunday and two were wounded and
captured after Katyusha rockets were fired into the Israeli border
town of Matulla, slightly wounding an infant.
   Israel radio said 20 young settlers from the study center in
Nablus were being questioned about the attack on nearby Kifil
Harith in which Ibtisam Bozieh became the 500th Palestinian killed
in the uprising against Israeli rule that began Dec. 8, 1987.
Twenty-two Israelis also have been slain.
   Members of the student group said they were hiking to a
religious shrine in Kifil Harith when Palestinians began throwing
stones. Police reports said the students set fires in grain fields
outside the village and appeared to start shooting as soon as they
entered the village.
   The rampage in Kifil Harith was the latest retaliatory action by
settlers against Palestinian stonings or firebombings.
   Defense Minister Yitzhak Rabin told a Parliament committee it
was the job of the police and army to enforce the law.
   He noted that many of the 70,000 Jewish settlers have been given
weapons for protection, but added: ``They are ... forbidden to take
the laws into their own hands and carry out punishment raids.''
   Daniella Weiss, a leader of the settlers' Gush Emunim movement,
told Israel radio the Jews were being provoked to take action.
   ``If people react to attacks by Arabs, they should be praised
for it, and no one should speak against it,'' she said.
   The U.S. government condemned vigilante attacks by Jewish
settlers.
   ``We note the Israeli government's views that there could be `no
justification for people taking the law into their own hands.' We
certainly agree with that,'' State Department spokesman Richard
Boucher said in Washington.
   In Ariel, near Kifil Harith, Mayor Ron Nachmann said in a
telephone interview that the Palestinian workers would undergo a
daily security check before being issued tags identifying them as
``alien workers.''
   ``We want to be sure that no terrorists enter Ariel,'' Nachmann
said.
   About 400 Palestinians work in Ariel, a settlement of more than
8,000 Israelis. The Palestinians are mainly residents of the West
Bank, which was captured by Israel from Jordan in the 1967 Middle
East War.
   The tag policy was announced on Tuesday and is believed to be
the first of its kind in Israel.
   In the Tel Aviv suburb of Petah-Tikva, officials have begun
building an ``encampment'' for Arab workers. They are supposed to
be taken to and from work by employers without being allowed to
walk the streets freely.
</TEXT>
