<FIRST>r i AM-Poland-Television     05-30 0415</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Poland-Television,0431</SECOND>
<HEAD>State TV Airs Solidarity Program and Rebuttal Comments</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Poland</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WARSAW, Poland (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   State television aired a Solidarity
election program Tuesday featuring a former U.S. presidential
adviser and a comedian instructing voters how to choose candidates
in the June 4 election.
   It was followed immediately by an official commentator who
indirectly criticized Zbigniew Brzezinski, an adviser to former
President Jimmy Carter.
   The start of the Solidarity broadcast was delayed for 18 minutes
by the coverage of an election rally for Prime Minister Mieczyslaw
F. Rakowski.
   Brzezinski, seated in front of a Solidarity banner, said a truly
democratic Poland could benefit from ties with other democracies in
Europe.
   At the end of the Solidarity program an unidentified commentator
said, ``You just watched an interview with Zbigniew Brzezinski.
   ``We believe people who think in a proper way will assess
properly this interference in the Polish election campaign.''
   Poland's communist authorities accuse the United States of
improperly helping Solidarity.
   The Solidarity show included tapes of French singer Yves Montand
and American singer Stevie Wonder, both of whom visited Poland in
the past week.
   A major segment was a sketch by Polish comedian Jacek Fedorowicz
on how to choose Solidarity candidates in the complicated voting
procedure for the Sejm, or parliament, and new Senate.
   Fedorowicz is shown at a polling station equipped with glasses
to read the ballot and pens to show viewers how to mark it for
Solidarity candidates.
   Candidates will not be identified by party affiliation on the
ballot and the voter must remember the name of the person he wants
to support.
   To vote for a candidate the voter must cross out the names of
the other candidates.
   The commentator accused Fedorowicz of advising voters to cross
out candidates on the 34-member national list on which top
Communist Party and government officials are running unopposed.
   ``Fedorowicz's call to cross out all candidates from the
national list is a gesture against the agreement,'' the commenator
said. ``It rejects people who created and signed the agreement and
it breaks the rules, so it is better not to mix up a cabaret with
political instructions.''
   An April 5 agreement between Solidarity and the government
established procedures for Poland's first democratic elections
since World War II and allowed Solidarity access to state
television and radio.
   Tuesday's broadcast was the third Solidarity-produced show.
Authorities blocked an election show dealing with human rights that
was to have been shown May 23. They said it violated the April
agreement.
</TEXT>
