<FIRST>r a AM-MissionaryFunerals     05-30 0453</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Missionary Funerals,0467</SECOND>
<HEAD>Slain Missionaries Mourned</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SALT LAKE CITY (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Mormon Church leaders Tuesday eulogized
two missionaries gunned down last week in Bolivia as martyrs who
were ``two of the best God had to offer.''
   Todd Ray Wilson and Jeffrey Brent Ball, both 20, were killed May
24 as they walked to their apartment in La Paz. Their deaths were
believed to be the first politically motivated slayings of
missionaries of The Church of Jesus Christ of Latter-day Saints.
   A group calling itself the Armed Liberation Front of Zarate
Wilka claimed responsibility for the killings. An FBI team was
dispatched to Bolivia to help in the investigation.
   Art Kingdom, aide to Rep. Wayne Owens, said the State Department
informed the Utah Democrat's office about the FBI's involvement and
that the agency said it had no theory about the motivation for the
killings.
   Mormon Church President Ezra Taft Benson and Thomas S. Monson,
second counselor in the faith's governing First Presidency,
attended a funeral for Ball at the Coalville Stake Center about 40
miles east of Salt Lake City.
   ``Jeff has gone home to God on a missionary transfer. He carries
on his mission; he has not been released,'' Monson told the
gathering of 400 people. ``There is not a missionary parent in this
church whose heart has not grieved and whose eyes have not shed
tears over the passing of these two boys.''
   The frail, 89-year-old Benson, who did not speak, was helped to
his feet and went on to bless Ball's family.
   Following the service, Ball was buried at Coalville Cemetery.
   About 120 miles south of Salt Lake, more than 300 people packed
the Wellington Stake Center for Wilson's funeral.
   Gordon B. Hinckley, first counselor in the First Presidency, and
L. Tom Perry, a member of the faith's Council of the Twelve
Apostles, were keynote speakers.
   Hinckley, referring to the investigation into the slayings, said
while learning the truth is important, it is ``even more important
is that those who were murdered were two of the best God had to
offer.''
   ``As we weep today, the whole church weeps with you,'' Hinckley
said. ``Missionaries are so dear that when one is lost to death,
the entire church grieves.''
   The names of the slain would be ``engraved forever in the
history of the church as those who lived as faithful servants to
the Lord and died as martyrs to His eternal word,'' Hinckley said.
   ``I can't promise the family they will ever recover from the
loss of a son, but your memories of him will be strengthened and
the sweetness of this man's life will bless you in a way you can't
imagine,'' Perry said.
   Wilson was buried at Wellington Cemetery.
</TEXT>
