<SECOND>AM-Philippines, 2nd Ld-Writethru, a0631,0275</SECOND>
<HEAD>Unions Call Off Planned Strike</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: LEADS throughout to UPDATE with compromise on wages, strike
called off. No pickup</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By CLARO CORTES</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MANILA, Philippines (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A congressional committee reached a
compromise Tuesday on a new salary law, and labor unions agreed to
call off a nationwide strike set for this week.
   Sen. Ernesto Herrera, chairman of the committee, said the panel
agreed to a $1.19 per day increase in the minimum wage for workers
earning less than $4.76 daily.
   The Senate and House of Representatives are to vote Wednesday on
the proposal and send it to President Corazon Aquino.
   After the committee announcement, the Trade Union Congress of
the Philippines, with about 1.3 million members, and the Labor
Advisory Consultative Council, which represents about 900,000
workers, said they would call off a nationwide strike set for
Thursday.
   Both unions had demanded an increase of $1.42 per day.
   Mrs. Aquino had rejected that demand as inflationary and said it
would discourage foreign investment.
   Avelino Valerio, vice president of the Trade Union Congress,
said the compromise was ``the best we can get.''
   Thousands of workers affiliated with the militant Labor Advisory
Consultative Council went on strike Monday.
   Rep. Alberto Veloso, a member of the congressional panel, said
the compromise was reasonable to achieve labor peace, but employers
were ``cringing in pain about the decision.''
   The Employers Confederation of the Philippines said the increase
was too much. Some companies had said they would cut back on
expansion plans and lay off some workers if the government orders
unacceptable wage boosts.
</TEXT>
