<FILEID>AP-NR-05-30-89 2142EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a AM-WillieB     05-30 0341</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Willie B,0353</SECOND>
<HEAD>Zoo Atlanta's Lowland Gorilla Willie B. Meets Girls For First Time</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ATLANTA (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Willie B., the Atlanta zoo's 30-year-old
silverback lowland gorilla, went on his first date Tuesday and got
slapped for his trouble.
   The male gorilla, who has been isolated from his own kind for 28
years, was introduced to a pair of female gorillas Tuesday morning
in a room specially designed for the assignation.
   Neither Willie B. nor the two females _ 6-year-old Kinyani and
26-year-old Katoomba _ showed any shyness, said Zoo Atlanta
Director Terry Maple. Both females are from Emory University's
Yerkes Regional Primate Research Center.
   ``It couldn't be going any better,'' Maple said. ``So far,
Willie has proved to be very normal in the behaviors he has shown
during the socialization process.''
   The idea behind the meeting wasn't to get the gorillas to mate _
it's much too early for that.
   ``We wouldn't have expected that,'' said zoo spokeswoman Erika
Archibald. ``He has no experience in that.''
   ``This is just a period of socialization for Willie B.,'' she
said. ``We hope that (mating) might happen eventually.''
   A 37-by-20-foot room was prepared for the female gorillas. It
was filled with straw, bamboo and other items such as a large rope
and a tire.
   Kinyani and Katoomba were allowed to decide whether to join
Willie B. in the room by using an overhead door large enough for
them but too small for him. They waltzed right in, Maple said.
   There are two other doors just big enough for Kinyani and
Katoomba to escape if need be, and Maple said both used the doors
several times but always returned to the room.
   Then came a magic moment. Willie B. made contact with a female
gorilla.
   Actually, Katoomba gave Willie B. a little slap and acted a bit
aggressively, said Kenneth Gould, chief of reproductive biology at
Yerkes.
   ``This may be her social experience showing through,'' Gould
said. ``She's been through introductions before and has a history
of being able to look after herself.''
</TEXT>
