<FIRST>r a AM-DomesticPartners     05-30 0243</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Domestic Partners,0251</SECOND>
<HEAD>Domestic Partners Law Goes To Mayor After Second OK By Supervisors</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SAN FRANCISCO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A law recognizing the unions of homosexuals
and unmarried heterosexuals won unanimous approval from the city
Board of Supervisors, and went to Mayor Art Agnos for his signature.
   Agnos has promised to sign the ordinance, which was approved 9-0
by the board. Two supervisors were absent.
   The law allows unmarried couples, homosexual or heterosexual, to
register as domestic partners for a $35 fee, giving them a
certificate similar to a marriage license.
   The supervisors also voted unanimously for a second time to form
a task force that will examine the possibility of extending city
health benefits to the live-in lovers of city employees.
   Both measures were unanimously approved by the board last week.
   Board President Harry Britt, who sponsored the measures, said
the law will ``let people love as they will.''
   But some religious leaders, including Roman Catholic Archbishop
of San Francisco John Quinn, called the legislation an attack on
the family.
   Last week, gay rights advocates hailed the vote to adopt the
domestic partnership law. They also urged the mayor to consider
extending health benefits to the partners of city employees.
   A few other cities have adopted policies extending health
benefits to live-in lovers of municipal employees. But San
Francisco would be the first to allow any non-married couples in
the country to register their relationships the eay traditional
couples obtain marriage licenses.
</TEXT>
