<FIRST>r i AM-Korea-Student     05-30 0235</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Korea-Student,0242</SECOND>
<HEAD>Government Finds No Foul Play in Student's Death</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SEOUL, South Korea (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The government plans no further action
in the death of radical student leader Lee Chol-kyu after a major
investigation concluded he died accidentally, a spokesman said
Wednesday.
   The spokesman, who refused to be identified in keeping with
official practice, said prosecutors were satisfied that police were
not involved in the death of Lee, whose body was found May 10 in a
reservoir near Kwangju.
   Dissident groups claimed police tortured and killed Lee. They
mounted protests in the southern city of Kwangju and other cities
demanding that the government admit police were involved.
   They called the government report a coverup, but provided no
evidence backing up their charges of torture.
   About 300 protesters attacked a police station in Kwangju with
iron bars late Tuesday and injured five officers, police said.
About 50 people were hurt in running clashes with riot police in
the area of the government prosecutors' office, they said.
   A government report concluded Lee slipped, fell into the
reservoir and drowned on May 3 after running from a police
roadblock. It said no evidence of torture emerged.
   The report said police stopped Lee at a roadblock and while they
were radioing to police headquarters to check Lee's identity, he
ran away.
   Lee was wanted on charges of violating national security laws
for writing articles praising communist North Korea.
</TEXT>
