<FIRST>r a AM-Obit-Cipollina     05-30 0265</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Obit-Cipollina,0276</SECOND>
<HEAD>San Francisco Rock Musician Dead at 45</HEAD>
<DATELINE>GREENBRAE, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   John Cipollina, a founder of the 1960s
rock band Quicksilver Messenger Service and a guitar star of San
Francisco's ``Summer of Love'' in 1967, has died. He was 45.
   Cippolina, who suffered from emphysema, was rushed to Marin
General Hospital after he became short of breath Monday evening at
his home in Mill Valley, but efforts to save him failed.
   The Berkeley native, whose signature song was the Bo Diddley
classic ``Mona,'' is remembered for his flowing and melodic style
with Quicksilver, which he helped form in 1965.
   The group was never as popular as such San Francisco Bay area
contemporaries as the Grateful Dead or Jefferson Airplane. But
Quicksilver represented the San Francisco sound at its purest,
according to the Encyclopedia of Rock.
   Cipollina lived in El Salvador and Guatemala as a small child,
then moved to Mill Valley in the San Francisco Bay area when he was
6.
   He played guitar as a boy, and by 1964 was performing with folk,
blues and flamenco groups.
   Cippolina left Quicksilver in 1970, and later played with the
band Copperhead and a Welsh band called Man. He toured Europe
during the 1970s.
   Most recently, Cipollina played with the Dinosaurs, a band
composed of former members of Jefferson Airplane, Country Joe and
the Fish, and Big Brother and the Holding Company.
   His mother, who survives him, was a concert pianist and his
godfather was pianist Jose Iturbi. His younger brother, Mario,
plays bass for Huey Lewis and the News.
   Funeral plans were pending.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
