<FIRST>r i AM-Britain-Soccer 1stLd-Writethru a0745 05-30 0391</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Britain-Soccer, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0745,0398</SECOND>
<HEAD>Police Say Stadium Gates Opened to Prevent Deaths</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: SUB 6th and 8th grafs to read at start, Marshall said ... CORRECTING
name from Marshal to Marshall.</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SHEFFIELD, England (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A police chief said Tuesday he ordered
a stadium gate to be opened to prevent soccer fans outside from
being crushed, but minutes later in the surge of the crowd 95
people were killed.
   Superintendent Roger Marshall told an investigating panel he was
told by a senior officer that lives were in danger because of the
mass of people pressing against a gate at the Hillsborough Stadium
before a cup game between Liverpool and Nottingham Forest on April
15.
   ``There was no real alternative because there was nowhere for
these people to go,'' Marshall said. ``There was no escape route in
any way, shape or form other than into the stadium.''
   As the fans rushed through the open gate they piled into the
crowds in the standing areas in the early minutes of the game.
   Anti-riot fences barred the victims of the crush from escaping
onto the field of the stadium in Sheffield 150 miles north of
London.
   Marshall said when he heard of the casualties, ``I felt this
entire tragedy was my responsibility.''
   Half an hour before the 3 p.m. kickoff there was a carnival
atmosphere outside the stadium, but then as the crowd grew and
became impatient the situation ``deteriorated by the minute in a
big way,'' and the turnstiles had to be closed, he said.
   Marshall said that 15 minues later when he asked the police
control unit for permission to open the gate, ``the situation in
front of the turnstiles was becoming completely and utterly
untenable.
   ``People were crying out and fighting each other. Mounted
officers were working valiantly, but to no avail. They were totally
surrounded by people.''
   ``I have never come across anything like it in my life, and as
time went on we lost our ability to manage that situation,'' he
added. ``The late arrival of fans laced by drink and individuals
who had not got tickets and had an absolute determination to get
into that football (soccer) ground come what may were present that
afternoon.''
   He said that in opening the gate, ``I have to say it never
crossed my mind what the consequences would be.''
</TEXT>
