<FIRST>r a AM-Obit-Milanov     05-30 0228</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Obit-Milanov,0236</SECOND>
<HEAD>Zinka Milanov, Soprano At Metropolitan Opera, Dies</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Zinka Milanov, a soprano who sang with the
Metropolitan Opera for 28 years, died Tuesday at age 83.
   Mrs. Milanov, who suffered a stroke Saturday, died at Lenox Hill
Hospital, said hospital spokeswoman Anne Warner.
   A native of Zagreb, Yugoslavia, she studied in Zagreb, Milan,
Italy; and Berlin. She made her debut in 1927 at the Zagreb Opera
in Verdi's ``Il Trovatore.''
   After nine years with the Zagreb company, she went to the Vienna
State Opera. Her reputation spread through Europe as she made guest
appearances in Germany, Czechoslovakia and at the Salzburg
Festival, where in 1937 she was chosen by Arturo Toscanini as the
soloist in Verdi's ``Requiem.''
   That same year, she made her U.S. debut at the Metropolitan
Opera as Leonora in ``Il Trovatore.''
   She sang more than 400 performances with the Metropolitan Opera
during her tenure. She was one of the few principal singers to
inaugurate two successive Metropolitan Opera seasons, those of 1951
and 1952.
   She also had a successful concert career and recorded widely in
the Italian repertoire, especially works by Verdi and Puccini.
   She was most noted for the roles of Aida in the Verdi opera of
the same name and Desdemona in Verdi's ``Otello.''
   Born Zinka Kunc, she married twice, to Predag Milanov and L.
Jubomir Ilic.
</TEXT>
