<DOCNO> AP890530-0202 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-05-30-89 1011EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>a i PM-SellingLafayette Adv05   05-30 0673</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Selling Lafayette, Adv 05,0690</SECOND>
<HEAD>$Adv05</HEAD>
<HEAD>For Release Mon PMs June 5 or Thereafter</HEAD>
<HEAD>Sales of Lafayette Land Raise Furor in France</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MARILYN AUGUST</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>PARIS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A multimillion dollar plan to sell ``souvenir''
parcels of land near the chateau where the Marquis de Lafayette was
born and left behind to fight in the American Revolution has
infuriated a group seeking to preserve his name.
   ``It's nothing short of a land scam, destined to fool people
into thinking they're buying a piece of history, and they are
not,'' said Christian Malagies, secretary of the Memorial
Lafayette, the foundation that owns Lafayette's birthplace and
operates as a non-profit organization promoting French-American
friendship.
   The venture was launched earlier this year by a private company
with a name similar to the foundation's, L'Immemorial Lafayette.
One of thousands of commercial operations here capitalizing on the
200th anniversary of the French Revolution, it is one of the most
controversial.
   ``The name itself could mislead potential customers who might
think they were contributing to the foundation,'' Malagies said in
a telephone interview.
   L'Immemorial Lafayatte is the brainchild of Caroline
d'Amphernet, a 29-year-old marketing consultant who decided to turn
a 20-year-old dinner party conversation into a money-making concern.
   ``The idea comes from a well-known anecdote about cutting up te
Marquis de Lafayette's embroidered handkerchief and selling the
pieces. The story circulated in Paris for years,'' Ms. d'Amphernet
said in a telephone interview. ``After doing a market study in the
United States on Lafayette, we decided to do something about it.''
   She said the survey indicated that one in 10 Americans knew who
Lafayette was: the general and statesman who fought alongside
American revolutionary forces against the British.
   ``About 50 percent of the people polled had heard of him, but
many thought he was a notorious pirate,'' she said.
   Marquis Gilbert du Mortier de Lafayette (1757-1834) was born in
Chateau Chavaniac Lafayette and spent his youth there. He left for
the United States at 20, served with American forces at Brandywine
and Yorktown and became a close friend of George Washington's.
   In January, the company bought up 25 acres of untilled farmland
near the chateau. Ms. d'Amphernet said she told the farmers why she
wanted the land and why she was ready to pay $900 an acre, more
than three times its normal price.
   Since then, other farmers have expressed interest in selling
additional land in the village, she said.
   ``There is certainly no way we can prove that the land once
belonged to Lafayette since the regional archives were burned in
1860,'' Ms. d'Amphernet said. ``But the history books all agree
that the entire village of Chavaniac Lafayette was part of the
domaine that had belonged to the Lafayette family since medieval
times.''
   L'Immemorial Lafayette plans to divide up the land into pieces
roughly a foot square. Each piece will sell for $100, for a total
of $16.7 million.
   Malagies calls the venture ``too juicy to be honest. ''
   ``The whole operation is completely immoral,'' Malagies said.
``First, there is no evidence to support their claim that the land
belonged to Lafayette. The land is not contiguous to the chateau
but is farther away in the village itself.
   ``Secondly, it's using the bicentennial of the French Revolution
to take advantage of people who are gullible because they're far
away and have never laid eyes on Chateau Chavaniac Lafayette.''
   Ms. d'Amphernet said she has already sold a few pieces in France
but expects to sell the majority to Americans and Japanese. She
plans to contact American cities named for Lafayette along with
historical societies connected to both the American and French
revolutions.
   Each purchase will be accompanied by a hand-painted deed _ a
one-of-a-kind diploma-sized certificate edged in blue, white and
red, decorated with a seal in the form of Lafayette's profile and
bearing the number of the lot and the owner's name.
   ``It'll will be decorative _ the ultimate bicentennial souvenir
for history buffs and francophiles,'' Ms. d'Amphernet said.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv Mon PMs June 5</NOTE>
