<FIRST>a e BC-WKD--Stuart Adv02-04   05-30 0828</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-WKD--Stuart, Adv 02-04,0851</SECOND>
<HEAD>$Adv02 ^$Adv02</HEAD>
<HEAD>$Adv04</HEAD>
<HEAD>For Release Weekend Editions, June 2-4 and Thereafter</HEAD>
<HEAD>AP WEEKEND ENTERTAINMENT AND ARTS</HEAD>
<HEAD>Books and Authors: A Dying Son and a Difficult Book</HEAD>
<HEAD>With LaserPhoto</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By HILLEL ITALIE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   With 80 pages of his first novel completed,
Alexander Stuart received some tragic news: His 3-year-old son,
Joe, was dying of cancer.
   Feeling a ``huge rage at the injustice of it,'' Stuart divided
time between the hospital and the typewriter, throwing himself into
his work.
   The book he had started was hardly a sentimental love story.
Stuart wanted to write about the troubles of a seemingly ``normal''
middle-class English family and decided to use the teen-age son's
discovery of an affair between his father and sister as the central
plot.
   Stuart had originally conceived a low-key approach but changed
his mind after learning of his son's illness. Joe Stuart died in
January at age 5.
   ``It actually proved to be the perfect vehicle in a way to
release my feelings, because it pushed me closer to the edge,''
explained Stuart, whose book is called ``The War Zone'' ($16.95,
Doubleday).
   ``I wanted to write a book which would explore incest without
being too disturbing. The more I researched, the more I realized
it's a very destructive process. I don't think anybody could come
out of it without being damaged.
   ``My son's illness allowed me do it head on, to try and take it
all the way. I hope it's dangerous but in a responsible way. I hope
it challenges what you think and feel, but at the same time feels
true.''
   Stuart's wife was pregnant when the writer developed the idea
for ``The War Zone.'' With Stuart about to become a father, he
became curious about the relationships between parents and children.
   ``I was very fascinated by friends and their fathers, and
friends and their daughters and what seemed to be an electric
spark. I would watch the daughters with their fathers, flirting
with them and their friends. I wondered what it would be like to
have a teen-age daughter.''
   The book's narrator, Tom, is an alienated teen-ager enraged with
his father and sister and cynical about the world in general. The
34-year-old Stuart drew on his own disenchantment.
   ``I think it definitely comes out of something I felt at his age
and now. He certainly does experience disillusionment. He's
horrified by what his father is doing. What interested me in Tom's
character was that whole area of exclusion. All of us feel excluded
at some time.''
   Stuart, born in 1955, grew up in the English town of Bexley,
Kent. His childhood had little of the trauma suffered by Tom, but
Stuart learned that several people from his supposedly quiet
hometown eventually committed suicide.
   ``I do feel disillusioned in a sense. It's very hard to maintain
in life the excitement you had at 12, 13 or 14. Why can't it be as
wonderful as it seems to promise at that age? I suppose that's
partly what the book's about.''
   He did have a sister and remembered the shifting alliances when
confronting their parents.
   ``We used to side against them at times. At other times you sort
of chop each other to get out of something. Certainly, as a kid all
of us have played our father against our mother,'' the author said.
   ``It seems to me the passions within the family are
extraordinary to start with. The family is the environment in which
you tend to develop your relationship skills, if you like. The book
takes it one step further.
   He insisted, however, that the family portrayed in ``The War
Zone'' was purely fictional.
   ``Both my parents read the book and are somewhat stunned by it.
But at least they don't recognize themselves in it. Obviously, one
is influenced by one's childhood, but I did work hard in recreating
something fictional from my own experiences and friends I had
spoken to.''
   Film, not writing, was Stuart's first love. The author wrote the
screenplays for ``Ordeal by Innocence'' and Nicholas Roeg's
``Insignificance,'' and sees similarities between the written word
and moving pictures.
   ``I was fascinated by visual language,'' he said. ``I don't see
it as a division. To me, it's all about using the language that's
available. The camera can be used emotionally, like Martin
Scorcese's `Mean Streets.'
   ``When I write I think in terms of the emotion I'd want if it
were in a film, and than translate and get it onto the page.''
   He was struggling financially while writing ``The War Zone,''
but was too distressed about his son to notice.
   ``I had a huge overdraft, a huge mortgage and was really kind of
feeling worried financially,'' Stuart said. ``But once he was ill
the financial problems didn't matter, they became completely
irrelevant. It doesn't mean anything like seeing your son dying
from cancer.''
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv for Weekend Editions, May 26-28</NOTE>
