<FIRST>a e BC-WKD--RecordReviews Adv00   05-30 0521</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-WKD--Record Reviews, Adv 00,0542</SECOND>
<HEAD>$Adv00</HEAD>
<HEAD>For Release Anytime</HEAD>
<HEAD>AP WEEKEND ENTERTAINMENT AND ARTS</HEAD>
<HEAD>In the Groove: Record Reviews</HEAD>
<TEXT>
   
   
   Ein Heldenleben, Four Last Songs, by Richard Strauss; Vienna
Philharmonic Orchestra; Arleen Auger, soprano; Andre Previn,
conductor (Telarc).
   
   Some works are so powerful and interpretations of them so
distinct and beautiful that it is difficult to compare other
versions. That's the problem here. Arleen Auger's recording of the
Four Last Songs is quite good, but it must contend with the
memorable interpretation of Elizabeth Schwartzkopf.
   Schwartzkopf sings these songs with such clarity and personality
that it's difficult for anybody else not to sound on the blander
side of the character meter.
   But there's a lot of good to be said for this disc.
   Auger always sings prettily, except for a surprising coarseness
in the long phrase of the words ``freien Flugen Schweben'' (``free
flight soaring'') of the song ``Beim Schlafengehen'' (``Time to
Sleep.'') The American soprano also sings with an appealing
simplicity.
   Strauss wrote these sometimes melancholy, sometimes soaring and
always beautiful songs the year before his death in 1949 at 86. If
you're looking for a recording of them specifically, look to
Schwartzkopf, who recorded them twice for Angel. If you're looking
for something from the latest crop of new releases, think about
this disc.
   The Vienna gives a polished and rousing performance of Ein
Heldenleben and sounds great throughout. Previn, in the songs,
keeps the long lines moving and has a sense of drama in ``A Hero's
Life.''
   _ By Daniel Wakin, Associated Press Writer.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   
   ``Boingo Alive'' (MCA) _ Oingo Boingo
   
   Live albums have a unique sort of energy. Unfortunately, they
also have crowd noise, which can distract from the performance and
discourage cranking of the volume knob.
   Oingo Boingo, a veteran eight-piece band with a reputation of
being better on stage than on record, has overcome the problem of
unwelcome audience participation with ``Boingo Alive.'' The double
album was recorded live, but on a soundstage, sans audience. The
strategy works _ the music has the spark of a live performance and
captures Oingo Boingo at its best.
   The band careens at a breathless pace through 10 years of
material, delivering 21 songs on the LP, 30 on compact disc. Two
are tunes never previously recorded.
   ``Alive'' naturally kicks off with ``Dead Man's Party'' (``Leave
your body and soul at the door''). Led by a three-piece horn
section, the Boingos quickly establish a killer groove. Other
highlights include the rocking ``Just Another Day,'' a guitar tour
de force; the catchy call of distress ``Private Life,'' a hit in
1982; and ``Only Makes Me Laugh,'' which shows off the band's great
singing.
   Lead vocalist Danny Elfman is the big star, although some of his
mannerisms make you wonder if he's really Freddie Mercury. (After
all, when is the last time you saw or heard anything about the
singer for Queen?) Anyway, this is a great primer from a good band,
and about half the cuts are capable of charring your turntable.
   _ By Steven Wine, Associated Press Writer.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv for Release Anytime</NOTE>
