<FIRST>a e BC-WKD--Etheridge Adv9-11   05-30 0944</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-WKD--Etheridge, Adv 9-11,0968</SECOND>
<HEAD>$Adv09</HEAD>
<HEAD>$Adv10</HEAD>
<HEAD>$Adv11</HEAD>
<HEAD>For Release Weekend Editions, June 9-11 and Thereafter</HEAD>
<HEAD>AP WEEKEND ENTERTAINMENT AND ARTS</HEAD>
<HEAD>Music Makers: Etheridge Takes the Slow Road to Overnight Success</HEAD>
<HEAD>With LaserPhoto</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DAVID BAUDER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LATHAM, N.Y. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Melissa Etheridge may have attended the
prestigious Berklee College of Music in Boston, but she's getting
her education in a series of one-night stops in crowded music clubs
across the country.
   It's been an eye-opening experience for many music fans, too.
   The emotionally intense rocker, whose debut album last year was
largely overlooked in a flood of records by female
singer-songwriters, is building a following with energetic live
shows that are quickly selling out through word of mouth.
   ``Looking back, I like how it happened,'' said the 27-year-old
Etheridge, shortly before stepping on stage for another sold-out
show. ``But when I'm there and in it, I was thinking, `why isn't
this getting noticed?'''
   Maybe it was the downbeat tone of her spare-sounding first
album, fueled by stories of jealousy and rejection in love. Her
vivid songwriting also teeters on the edge of cliche, with
prominent fire and steel metaphors.
   But her concerts are a revelation, which a national audience
learned when she sang her Grammy-nominated ``Bring Me Some Water''
on the national awards show in February.
   The tiny Etheridge bounces across the stage, belting out her
songs in a gruff voice that recalls Tina Turner, and fixing her
audience with a piercing stare and smile. Increasingly, audience
members are shouting her lyrics back at her.
   Etheridge grew up in Leavenworth, Kan., and was given her first
guitar at age 8. Like many in her generation, one of her first
musical memories was listening to the Beatles' ``I Want to Hold
Your Hand'' through a transistor radio.
   Her parents didn't dissuade her from a musical career _ her
father even drove her to performances before she got her driver's
license _ but said if she was serious, she had to get a serious
education. So they sent her to Berklee.
   ``I learned some things, but for what I do it wasn't all that
useful,'' she said of her formal music education. ``I knew it was a
way out of a small town.''
   She knew the real way to learn her craft was to take her
acoustic guitar onstage. Etheridge did that in Boston and later in
the Los Angeles area, where Island Records founder Chris Blackwell
spotted her in a tiny Long Beach club and signed her to a contract.
   Etheridge swears it wasn't a conscious decision to put out a
record that deals almost exclusively with the dark side of love.
   ``It wasn't until after I recorded them and sat down and
listened to them 1 through 10 that I said, `people are going to
think I'm pretty upset about something,''' she said.
   On ``Bring Me Some Water,'' Etheridge is ``burning alive'' with
jealousy over a lover who's abandoned her for another. The anger on
``Like the Way I Do'' is directed outward, with Etheridge asking an
old flame whether a new lover can ``shock and electrify and rock
you ... like the way I do.''
   All of her songs are autobiographical. The ones on her first
album traced from a ``dark period'' in her life, she said.
   ``I was in a real learning situation,'' she said. ``I was
learning a lot about relationships and my career. It was a whole
lot of things going on at once. ... I'm a little older now. I've
learned some of those lessons now.''
   Etheridge jokes about her image during concert appearances.
   ``Everywhere I go people ask me, `Melissa, why are you so sad?'
I tell them I'm not so sad,'' she says with a sly grin. ``I'm just
experienced.''
   Her unreleased material, which accounts for about half her live
show, doesn't stray much from her basic sound. But many of the
songs are cheerier and, encouragingly, even stronger than those on
her debut.
   Etheridge's second album, with the working title ``Brave and
Crazy'' is already recorded and is scheduled for release this fall.
She'll be on the road for most of the summer, usually as an opening
act for Little Feat.
   Her track record on the road is even surprising some veteran
promoters. Jim Koplik, a promoter for Cross Country Concerts in
Connecticut and upstate New York, said Etheridge sold out three
separate venues at least three weeks in advance, usually with
little advance publicity.
   ``Her Grammy performance was one of the few good Grammy
performances this year,'' he said. ``She's a tough rock 'n' roller
and there aren't too many females who are tough rock 'n' rollers
out there.''
   Etheridge admitted she practiced a Grammy acceptance speech in
her shower. She didn't win _ Tina Turner took the award in the
female rock category _ but she said she was pleasantly surprised
just to be noticed.
   ``My goals are just to get better,'' she said. ``I want to write
better. I want to sing better. I want to perform better. Success to
me is the opportunity to just keep doing what I love to do. Knowing
I've made my second album means I've been successful with my first
one.''
   The lack of instant album sales makes the current success all
the more satisfying, she said.
   ``The biggest selling point of this album was a friend telling a
friend _ word of mouth,'' Etheridge said. ``That's the way I buy
most of my music, from a friend telling me it's something good. It
takes a lot longer that way, but you can really see it multiply.''
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv for Weekend Editions, June 9-11</NOTE>
