<FIRST>a e BC-WKD--Just Adv9-11   05-30 0804</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-WKD--Just, Adv 9-11,0824</SECOND>
<HEAD>$Adv09</HEAD>
<HEAD>$Adv10</HEAD>
<HEAD>$Adv11</HEAD>
<HEAD>For Release Weekend Editions, June 9-11 and Thereafter</HEAD>
<HEAD>AP WEEKEND ENTERTAINMENT AND ARTS</HEAD>
<HEAD>Books and Authors: The Private Man Becomes Public</HEAD>
<HEAD>With LaserPhoto</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JAMES REINDL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Ward Just's latest novel of political intrigue is
drawing critical acclaim and focusing attention on its
former-journalist author, which raises an interesting question.
   Does success mean waking up to discover one has become _ at
least partly _ the character one wrote about?
   For Just, former Newsweek and Washington Post reporter and son
of an Illinois publishing family, the answer is yes and no.
   ``All my books really have to do with people who have two lives
_ a private life and a public life,'' Just said in a recent
interview over coffee and cigarettes in a Michigan Avenue cafe. ``I
mean a public life in the way that say you and I don't have a
public life. I didn't used to have one. I guess I'm getting one now.
   ``When you are in that kind of world, half public, half private,
and the two things bear on each other, it makes the choices a
little more difficult and often a whole lot more interesting ...
than sort of ordinary people. And since we live in this world of
glaring media attention, that makes anybody who is involved in that
kind of life a very modern man.''
   ``Jack Gance'' is Just's 12th book and he is quick to point out
he is not the title character.
   The book examines the life of Chicago-born Jack Gance, son of a
successful real estate developer who winds up disgraced and jailed
in a scandal. Gance parlays his University of Chicago education and
contacts, and his accumen for deciphering the numbers of politics,
to land work in the early 1960s with the operatives in the city's
political machine.
   Gance becomes an operative himself. He moves to the White House;
new locale, same job of making things happen. The book ends with
Gance making a successful bid for the Senate from Illinois. The
private man becomes public.
   That is the background, and as Just pointed out, ``Jack Gance''
is a book about politics with a small ``p.''
   ``It's a novel with politics as its background,'' he said. ``You
know it could have just as easily been with the Army, retailing,
the news business. I just chose politics because it's a world that
interests me and I know a little bit about it, almost entirely from
my experience as a journalist.''
   The politics of ``Jack Gance'' are more the politics of people
than of parties.
   As the book explores Gance's troubled relationship with his
father and the attraction for a workaholic lawyer's wife, ``Jack
Gance'' throughout examines the motives of its central character,
looking for what propels him to make his choices.
   ``The show (politics) in Washington is very attractive to an
Illinois boy like Jack or like me,'' Just said. ``I think it is a
book maybe more about attractions than about compromise _ what
attracts people.
   ``And, I want to explore also in this country, this large
capitalist country, the nature of work _ what work does to people,
the kind of work that you have, what bearing that has on your
character and what bearing your character has on your work,'' the
author said.
   What Just finds is that compromise is more symmetrical than
defiance, that loyalty has its rewards at a price. It is laid out
in the last lines of the book when he writes that Washington ``was
a great city, always giving more than it received. It gave and gave
and gave and gave and expected nothing in return except loyalty.''
   Loyalty, Just said, is the greatest thing that can be given.
   ``To expect nothing except loyalty. Well that is expecting
everything. That is what he's given and his reward is the United
States Senate. What he gives in return is his loyalty to this
really rather appalling system.''
   Just is looking for the novel to build a more loyal readership.
Nine of his 12 books are out of print and he hopes that success
with ``Jack Gance'' will help get the books back into print.
   The gestation period for Just's books is about two years, he
said. He works from a base in Paris, where he lives with his wife,
and is planning a book about a group of Americans in Paris.
   ``I've always worked very well in foreign countries,
particularly foreign countries where I didn't speak the language,''
Just said. ``I sort of like to work on the margins like that, and
it's fun for me to be in Paris not even speaking the language very
well.
   ``It enhances something. I can't even say what.''
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv for Weekend Editions, June 9-11</NOTE>
</DOC>
