<HEAD>$Adv09</HEAD>
<HEAD>$Adv10</HEAD>
<HEAD>$Adv11</HEAD>
<HEAD>For Release Weekend Editions, June 09-11 and Thereafter</HEAD>
<HEAD>AP WEEKEND ENTERTAINMENT AND ARTS</HEAD>
<HEAD>Nashville Sound: Lacy J. Dalton Is a Survivor</HEAD>
<HEAD>With LaserPhoto</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOE EDWARDS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NASHVILLE, Tenn. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Adversity has taught country singer Lacy
J. Dalton about being positive in her life.
   And her new LP, ``Survivor,'' sums it up.
   ``I am a survivor. This was a healing process,'' she said.
   ``I've learned that no matter how tough things get and how
unfairly you think you are being treated, if you get your mind off
that, if you think about your goals and feel you can attain them
... things turn around for you a lot faster.''
   Dalton began a country music career five years after her husband
died in a swimming pool accident in 1974. She was 27 and had an
infant son. Food stamps and a brief stint as a topless dancer
helped them get by.
   Determined and dedicated, she launched her career, and was voted
most promising female vocalist in 1980 by the Academy of Country
Music.
   Although she had hits with such tunes as ``16th Avenue'' and
``Hillbilly Girl With the Blues,'' her career slipped and, until
this year, she had not cut an album for three years.
   But 1989 brought an upswing. The new Universal Records signed
her and released ``Survivor.'' She's back on the country singles
charts with ``The Heart'' and ``I'm a Survivor.'' She's also
recorded a duet with Glen Campbell, ``Woodcarver.''
   And on Valentine's Day she married Aaron Anderson, her tour
manager for the past four years.
   ``I felt like a big arm had been put around me,'' she says about
her new recording contract. Still, the husky-voiced 42-year-old
performer adds, ``I'm a little scared.''
   Born Jill Byrem into a musical family in Bloomsburg, Pa.,
Dalton's songs often are about hope and strength and are frequently
aimed at women.
   ``I never sing from a negative point of view,'' she said. ``I
try to look for something to entertain or enlighten or uplift. The
underlying emphasis on everything I'm doing is to be positive.
   ``I think about women a lot. I feel that they can open doors. If
you feel you are equal, you automatically are treated that way. The
most important thing to me is if I can believe the song, if it's
real to me. Will I want to be singing this song for 20 years?''
   Despite her emphasis on looking at the bright side, she felt
compelled to quit recording for three years because of a dispute
with her former record label. It came down to a matter of
principle, with Dalton contending that her work was not being
promoted enough.
   ``Careers come and go in three years,'' she said. ``My lawyer
told me I was committing career suicide. Management went crazy and
everyone went nuts. But it was the only thing I knew to do
honorably to save the career in the long run.''
   She says Universal took a chance by offering her a contract.
   ``When you haven't been heard from in a major way for a few
years, it's like starting the career all over again,'' she said.
``A lot of people have come in since I went out. A lot of fans
don't know who I am. I am so grateful and amazed they (Universal)
would give me a home and a shelter. I hope I can be worthy.
   ``It had been a long, long time since I had a big hit. I didn't
know if anyone would be interested in signing me.''
   One of the country singers who became very successful during
Dalton's hiatus was K.T. Oslin, who has had No. 1 hit records with
candid, female-oriented songs such as ``80s Ladies'' and ``Hold
Me.''
   ``I love her work,'' Dalton said. ```80s Ladies' was one of the
best records I ever heard. When I heard it, I went `halleluiah,
praise God!' She has tremendous honesty and courage.
   ``There is so much young talent that's come in since I started
in 1979. They have fresh ideas and wonderful talent. People coming
in now are very sophisticated and very polished.''
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv for Weekend Editions, June 9-11</NOTE>
