<HEAD>$adv01</HEAD>
<HEAD>For release Thursday, June 1, and thereafter</HEAD>
<HEAD>Multiple Queen Discovery Means Worse Fire Ant Woes</HEAD>
<DATELINE>GAINESVILLE, Fla. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Fire ant colonies with hundreds of
queens are making it harder for people to get rid of the pests than
the previously found colonies with only one queen, experts say.
   ``When a queen dies in a single-queen nest, the whole nest
dies,'' said Mike Glancy of the U.S. Agriculture Department's
Agricultural Research Service. ``But with multiple-queen mounds,
they just scatter. The workers do not have loyalty to a single
queen and will accept any queen.''
   The development also means four times as many ants, and almost
one solid ant nest, said entomologist Phil Koehler of the
University of Florida's Institute of Food and Agricultural Sciences.
   An IFAS-USDA study in Ocala found 30 to 40 fire ant mounds per
acre in the days of single queens. Now, there are 5,000 mounds per
acre _ about every 5 feet _ with 200 queens per mound.
   Multiple-queen fire ants live in greater concentrations and are
more aggressive in hunting for food than single-queen fire ants.
They have been known to attack sick people in hospital beds and the
nipples of nursing goats.
   ``This is a more aggressive insect, which means more human
contact, which means more health problems,'' Glancy said. Fire ants
also cause trouble by eating foam expansion joints in highways and
insulation in machinery.
   Queens from multiple-queen nests fly eight to 10 miles on their
mating flights, compared to a half-mile for queens from
single-queen nests.
   Multiple-queen fire ants were discovered in 1981 in Louisiana
and in Ocala and Texas in 1983. Since then, multiple queen colonies
have spread throughout Florida and are found all over the
Southeast. Koehler said that as single-queen colonies are killed
off, it clears the way for the multiple-queen nests.
   Fire ants were accidentally imported from Brazil and Argentina
in the 1920s and 1940s in the ballast of ships.
</TEXT>
<HEAD>Scientist Puts Ties To Test As Railroads Look For New Materials</HEAD>
<DATELINE>URBANA, Ill. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A good railroad tie can withstand 30 years
of freight trains and snow storms, but only a few weeks with
scientist Poo Chow.
   Chow, a University of Illinois professor of wood science,
delivers a concentrated dose of Mother Nature's fury. ``We soak
them and make them swell, we dry them and make them shrink. We put
them in the freezer to simulate winter and in the oven to simulate
summer.''
   A dozen treatments produce the kind of cracking, splitting and
rotting a tie would show after 40 years on the track.
   ``We are all looking for a tie that will last longer and give us
some economic savings,'' said Don Gallery, roadway engineer for the
Illinois Central Railroad. He said Chow's research should tell
railroads how ties made from new types of woods will hold up over
long periods.
   The nation's railroads spike their steel track to more than 1
billion ties _ blocks of wood about eight inches square and eight
feet long. They transfer the weight of the trains to the roadbed
and keep the tracks at the correct angle so trains don't derail.
There is a tie every 19 inches.
   A typical tie, made of domestic wood and treated with creosote
to preserve it, lasts about 30 years depending on climate and
traffic. Evaluating new tie materials on the track is impractical
so Chow, with financial support from the Association of American
Railroads, devised a lab to simulate weathering and the effects of
squeezing, bending and movement of spikes.
   Raymond Wingard, executive director of the Railway Tie
Association in Mars, Pa., said Chow's tests will tell railroads
which ties offer the best service potential, so they can be tested
further in the field.
   Two promising woods are tough oak varieties from West Africa and
Southeast Asia, Chow said. He predicted domestic wood will continue
to be used for most ties, though the preservative may change
because of environmental concerns.
</TEXT>
