<FIRST>r f PM-Kinder-CareRestructuring     05-30 0462</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Kinder-Care Restructuring,0479</SECOND>
<HEAD>Kinder-Care To Separate Day Care, Educational Units From Financial,
Retail</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MONTGOMERY, Ala. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Kinder-Care Inc., the nation's largest
operator of day-care centers, says it will separate its day care
and education operations from its financial and retail division to
reduce its overall debt.
   A key part of the restructuring announced Monday will be the
distribution of shares of Kinder-Care Learning Centers to
Kinder-Care shareholders, said Perry Mendel, the Montgomery-based
company's chairman and founder.
   ``This separation of Kinder-Care Learning Centers, the original
company, from the financial services and specialty retail group
will help us tell working parents that we are totally focused on
child care and educational services,'' said Mendel.
   The boards of directors of Kinder-Care and Kinder-Care Learning
Centers Inc. have approved the restructuring, Mendel said.
   Under the restructuring, Kinder-Care expects to realize gross
proceeds of about $215 million, of which about $108 million will be
used to repay debt payable to Kinder-Care Learning Centers. The
remainder will be reinvested in Kinder-Care's core business
sectors, the company said.
   Richard Grassgreen, president of Kinder-Care, said that as a
result of the restructuring, he will be able to devote his full
time to financial services and specialty retailing.
   The company operates 1,235 day-care centers. In addition, it
operates 350 retail stores _ Simply 6, Bargain Town and Shoe City _
in seven Southeastern states, along with the American Savings and
Loans Association of Florida, the second-largest thrift in the
state and the 35th largest in America, and Western Reserve Life
Insurance Company, Grassgreen said.
   In connection with the restructuring, Grassgreen will not
continue in his positions with Kinder-Care Learning Centers and
Mendel no longer will be chairman and a director of Kinder-Care.
Mendel was elected chief executive officer of Kinder-Care Learning
Centers.
   The restructuring will enable Mendel to devote his full time to
child care while acting as chief executive officer until his
retirement, which is expected by Dec. 31, 1990, the company said.
   In the first step of the restructuring, Kinder-Care will offer
its shareholders the right to purchase 28 million newly issued
shares of Kinder-Care common stock at $5.75 per share.
   For each of the 54.9 million currently issued and outstanding
shares, a shareholder will be entitled to purchase .5099 shares of
Kinder-Care at $5.75 for each full share.
   Following the expiration of the rights offering, Kinder-Care
will distribute in a tax-free transaction one-half of a share of
Kinder-Care Learning Centers for each of the 82.9 million shares of
Kinder-Care to be outstanding following completion of the rights
offering.
   After the restructuring is completed, the per share book value
of Kinder Care will be approximately equal to the $5.75 exercise
price of the purchase rights.
   The company anticipates that the rights offering will be made in
July.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
