<FIRST>r f PM-GoldStar     05-30 0169</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Gold Star,0176</SECOND>
<HEAD>Korea's Gold Star To Produce Videotapes In U.S.</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SEOUL, South Korea (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Gold Star Co. will produce videotapes
at its electronics plant in Huntsville, Ala., beginning in
September, the leading South Korean electronics maker said.
   Officials said Monday that production facilities, capable of
turning out 1 million tapes a year, are being installed at the
plant, which has been in operation since 1982.
   The videotape production will fill the gap created recently when
three out of six color television production lines at the plant
were relocated to Mexico to take advantage of lower-cost labor and
parts supplies there.
   The three remaining color television production lines, capable
of assembling 500,000 sets a year, will remain at the plant,
together with microwave oven production facilities with an annual
capacity of 600,000 units, the officials said.
   They declined to say how much investment was requirement for the
videotape production project.
   The Huntsville plant is operated by a wholly owned Gold Star
subsidiary, Gold Star of America, Inc.
</TEXT>
