<FIRST>r f PM-Libya-Oil     05-30 0346</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Libya-Oil,0359</SECOND>
<HEAD>Libyan Talks With U.S. Oil Companies Deadlocked, Survey Says</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NICOSIA, Cyprus (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Talks between Libya's National Oil Corp.
and five U.S. oil companies on resuming operations in the North
African country are deadlocked, the Middle East Economic Survey
reported.
   It said Monday that the negotiations, which began in Vienna last
month, are continuing, with both sides aiming for an agreement by
June 30, the deadline set by the Libyans.
   But the respected Nicosia-based oil industry newsletter noted
that the Libyans are unhappy with U.S. sanctions that ban American
technology exports to Libya and imports of Libyan oil.
   The five companies _ Marathon Oil Co., Conoco Inc., Amerada Hess
Corp., Occidental Petroleum Corp. and W.R. Grace &amp; Co. _ all have
equity holdings in Libya.
   The negotiations began after the Jan.19 decision by
then-President Ronald Reagan to modify trade sanctions imposed on
Libya in 1986 because of Col. Moammar Gadhafi's alleged support for
international terrorism.
   The U.S. companies' assets in Libya were frozen when the
sanctions were imposed and the companies face seizure of the assets
by the Libyans if no agreement is reached by June 30.
   The Libyans are particularly interested in securing U.S.
expertise and technology for their oil industry amid Tripoli's
efforts to expand exploration and production.
   But they see no advantage ``in taking back the U.S. companies if
they are not allowed to import American oilfield equipment and
technological services,'' the survey reported.
   The newsletter also noted that Libya does not want to see the
Americans shipping crude to Europe, Libya's main market, if the
companies resume operations.
   The Libyans ``would like a full unconditional return by the
companies concerned, supported by a clear U.S. commitment on the
matter and freedom to ship Libyan crude to the U.S. market,'' the
survey said.
   ``However, it seems unlikely that such U.S. clearance will be
forthcoming in the near future, given that the Department of
Treasury Office of Foreign Assets Control has shown no flexibility
... and Libya is not high on the agenda of President Bush's current
priorities,'' the newsletter said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
