<HEAD>London Shares Lower at Midday in Light Trading</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Share prices were lower at midday Tuesday, as
persistent weakness in the pound continued to unnerve traders.
   However, traders said they saw little evidence of substantive
dealing.
   After a long holiday weekend in Britain, ``people are standing
back from the market at the moment and hoping to pick up on a new
theme,'' one London dealer said.
   At about 12:15 p.m. in London, the Financial Times-Stock
Exchange 100-share index was off 10.7 points, or 0.5 percent, at
2,129.6, also its lowest point. The index started the session at
its best level of 2,139.7, off just 0.6 point.
   Volume came to a light 195.9 million shares at midday, compared
with 274.6 million shares at the same time Friday.
</TEXT>
