<FIRST>r f PM-Australia-Hooker     05-30 0256</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Australia-Hooker,0265</SECOND>
<HEAD>Hooker Corp. to Sell $740 Million in U.S., Australian Assets</HEAD>
<DATELINE>Sydney, Australia (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Hooker Corp., an Australian retail and
property company, plans to sell 1 billion Australian dollars ($740
million) worth of Australian and U.S. assets to reduce debt.
   In a statement to the Australian Stock Exchange on Monday,
George Herscu, Hooker's executive chairman, said the company would
sell its U.S. Merksamer Jewelers Inc. jewelry store chain, U.S.
housing interests, all Australian retailing activities, property
funds management and sand-mining and brickwork resources in
Australia.
   It will also offer for sale or joint venture a number of real
estate assets which were not disclosed.
   Herscu said that in addition to reducing debt ``significantly''
the company wanted to concentrate its efforts on its profitable
core businesses. The sales would reduce the proportion of the
company's investments in the United States where returns are
longer-term in nature, Herscu said.
   In the United States, Hooker also controls retailers B. Altman &amp;
Co., Bonwit Teller, Sakowitz and the speciality fashion chain
Parisian Inc.
   The Hooker announcement follows recent cash flow problems in its
U.S. operations that caused the company to fall behind in payments
to several apparel suppliers which halted shipments to Bonwit
Teller and Altman, analysts said.
   Herscu said some of the sales already have taken place and
others are nearly completed.
   Hooker will retain its Australian businesses in land
subdivision, housing, project development, and real estate
management. In the United States, Hooker will keep its project
development concerns, department stores and real estate brokerage
activities.
</TEXT>
