<HEAD>Grain, Soybean Futures Prices Lower in Weather-Driven Market</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Grain and soybeans futures prices opened lower
today on the Chicago Board of Trade.
   The market was weather-driven and contracts for old crops fared
better than the new-crop months. Weekend rains, coupled with a
five-day forecast calling for more in prime corn and soybean
growing regions, put traders on the defensive from the opening bell.
   Wheat opened lower in sympathy, but soon after establishing a
floor, both soybeans and wheat recovered slightly. Corn however
remained stuck near its early lows. A strong dollar also helped
dampen any price climbing.
   On the open, wheat was 1{ cents to 3 cents lower, with the
contract for delivery in July at $3.90} a bushel; corn was 1 cent
to 5\ cents lower, with July $2.60 a bushel; oats were 3 cents to
4{ cents lower, with July at $1.66{ cents a bushel; and soybeans
were 6{ cents to 13{ cents lower, with July at $7.04{ cents a
bushel.
   Cattle future prices were mixed, but pork lower on the Chicago
Mercantile Exchange.
   On the open, cattle were .25 cent lower to .50 cent higher, with
June at 68.86 cents a pound; feeder cattle were .10 cent lower to
.05 cent higher, with August at 77.12 cents a pound; live hogs were
unchanged to .30 cent lower a pound; and frozen pork bellies were
.37 cent to .52 cent lower, with July at 30.55 cents a pound.
