<FIRST>u f PM-PanAm-Northwest 1stLd-Writethru f0056 05-30 0609</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Pan Am-Northwest, 1st Ld-Writethru, f0056,0624</SECOND>
<HEAD>Pan Am Says It Has Secured Financing for NWA Bid</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: To UPDATE with Northwest saying it would have no comment for
now on Pan Am's announcement, INSERTS new graf after 4th graf pvs, `These
commitments ...</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MARCY GORDON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Pan Am Corp. announced today it has secured bank
financing for its proposed $3.6 billion bid for NWA Inc., the
parent of Northwest Airlines and the target of a bidding contest.
   In an announcement, Pan Am stated it has received commitments
from five banks: Bankers Trust Co., Citibank, First National Bank
of Chicago, Morgan Guaranty Trust Co. and Security Pacific National
Bank.
   Pan Am declined to specify the amount of the banks' commitments.
Sources close to the company, however, said it exceeded the $1.6
billion which Pan Am said last week it was seeking.
   ``These commitments, together with the equity commitment of at
least $400 million from Prudential-Bache and the Airlie Group, will
enable Pan Am to put forward a very attractive offer to the
shareholders of NWA,'' Pan Am Chairman Thomas Plaskett said in the
statement.
   Northwest public relations spokesman Bob Gibbons said today the
airline would have no immediate comment on the Pan Am announcement.
   NWA, meanwhile, prepared to open bids from suitors for the
company. NWA had set a 3 p.m. CDT deadline today for takeover
offers and said last week that it planned on a single round of
bidding. The NWA board of directors, however, could decide not to
accept any of the bids and some analysts say the process could
start over if a higher bid came in later.
   Sources close to Pan Am said the company planned to submit its
takeover proposal to NWA by the deadline.
   Once the bids are in, a committee of four outside directors must
scrutinize each offer, a complex financial proposal that must
include not just a price per share but a host of details about who
is providing equity or loans, how much and in what form, as well as
the purchaser's plans for NWA once it is bought.
   An NWA spokesman has said the board may issue a decision by the
end of June.
   Other likely bidders for NWA include oil billionaire Marvin
Davis, whose first offer of $2.72 billion was rejected, and an
investment group led by financier Al Checchi.
   After Davis made his bid, the NWA board said it would explore
restructuring alternatives. The board said last Thursday it had
appointed a special committee to oversee that process.
   Possible alternatives include acquisition of another company, a
partial or complete liquidation of the airline, a repurchase of
shares, a special dividend or a sale of equity to third parties.
   Plaskett has said he is not contemplating layoffs of union
employees at Northwest, which is much larger than Pan Am.
Cooperation from Northwest's unions is considered crucial to the
bid.
   Industry analysts have been cautious about Pan Am's prospects
because of its $900 million in debt, $535 million in outstanding
pension liabilities and continuing losses.
   In a meeting last week with investment fund managers, Plaskett
outlined plans for Pan Am's bid, which would include the sale of
high-yield notes and bank financing for the $3.6 billion package.
   He said the offer would be all cash and fully financed.
   Plaskett told investors he plans no sales of operating assets
and no sale or lease-back of existing planes.
   He said he is not assuming any revenue from a sale of
Northwest's Japanese real estate, but expects to save $240 million
by streamlining the new carrier's corporate headquarters, marketing
operation, maintenance and other support services.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
