<SECOND>BC-Dollar-Gold,0366</SECOND>
<HEAD>Dollar Mixed, Gold Lower</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: An AMer expected by 5:30 p.m. EDT</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The U.S. dollar rose to a two-year high against
the British pound but was mixed against most other major currencies
Tuesday in European trading as Japan moved to raise its interest
rates.
   Gold prices fell.
   Dealers said the dollar shrugged off concerted dollar-selling by
central banks and the Bank of Japan's decision to raise its
official discount rate on Wednesday to 3.25 percent from 2.5
percent.
   Dealers said traders speculated that the West German central
bank would follow suit by raising its discount rate of 4.5 percent
at a council meeting on Thursday.
   ``The market sentiment remains positive on the dollar despite
all this talk of higher German rates,'' said Karl-Heinz Elsen, a
senior foreign exchange dealer at Chemical Bank AG in Frankfurt,
West Germany.
   The British pound appeared to bear the brunt of the
interest-rate hikes, slumping to a 25-month low against the dollar.
   British banks raised their base lending rates last week to a
four-year high of 14 percent, partly to support the sliding pound.
Sterling fell to $1.5570 from $1.5710 late Monday.
   Dealers said trading remained thin after Monday's holidays in
the United States and Britain.
   In Tokyo, the dollar rose 0.22 Japanese yen to a closing 143.10
yen. Later, in London, it rose further to 143.25 yen.
   Other late dollar rates, compared with late rates on Monday,
included: 2.0100 West German marks, down from 2.0101; 1.7545 Swiss
francs, down from 1.7550; 6.8085 French francs, up from 6.8025;
2.2630 Dutch guilders, up from 2.2625; 1,452.50 Italian lire, down
from 1,454.00, and 1.2055 Canadian dollars, up from 1.2047.
   Gold bullion fell in London to a late bid of $362.25 a troy
ounce, down from $363.75 late last Friday. London markets were
closed on Monday.
   In Zurich, the metal fell to $362.10 an ounce from $363.35 bid
late Monday.
   Earlier, in Hong Kong, gold fell 43 cents an ounce to $362.73.
   Silver bullion fell in London to a late bid of $5.20 a troy
ounce, down from $5.27 bd late Friday.
