   Stock prices fell broadly in choppy trading
today following a wave of computerized program selling.
   The Dow Jones average of 30 industrials was off 29.06 to
2,464.71 at 3 p.m. EDT, after rising as much as 14 points following
the opening bell. The closely watched index ended Friday with an
11.18-point rise.
   The financial markets were closed on Monday in observance of the
Memorial Day holiday.
   In the broader market, about two stocks declined for every one
that rose on the New York Stock Exchange, with 970 down, 484 up and
487 unchanged.
   Volume on the Big Board came to 128.51 million shares with one
hour to go.
   Stock prices started out higher due largely to lower interest
rates in the credit markets, but they declined later on
profit-taking and worries about the long-term effects of a rising
dollar on the economy.
   Facilitating the market's decline was a rash of selling by
professional traders engaged in computer-program strategies
involving options and futures on stock indexes, analysts said.
   ``The stock market is not responding to the stronger dollar and
good bond market the way it did in prior weeks,'' said Hugh
Johnson, senior vice president for First Albany Corp.
   ``The principal concern is that further increases in the dollar
might start to cloud the economic outlook.''
   Investors are particularly concerned about whether the strong
rise in the dollar's value in foreign exchange during recent weeks
could hurt the U.S. economy sensitive to trade.
   Among the most actively traded blue-chip stocks, Texaco was up {
to 51{; American Telephone and Telegraph was down ] to 35];
