<FILEID>AP-NR-05-30-89 1930EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r f AM-LTVBuyout     05-30 0346</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-LTV Buyout,0361</SECOND>
<HEAD>Bar Division to be Sold to Employees</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By M.R. KROPKO</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CLEVELAND (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   LTV Steel Co. said Tuesday that parent company
LTV Corp. has agreed to sell its bar division as part of an
employee stock ownership plan.
   The presidents of United Steelworkers union locals in the steel
division last week voted 5-3 for the plan. One local president was
not at the vote.
   About 4,700 salaried, hourly or senior management employees in
the bar division initially will work for the new company, which is
expected to produce about 1.2 million tons of steel annually.
   Details of the stock ownership plan, including its total value,
were not revealed.
   The division makes continuously cast and ingot-poured billets
for hot rolling mills in Canton and Massillon, Ohio, and Chicago.
   The Canton plant also provides steel to cold-finished bar plants
in Massillon; Gary, Ind.; Willimantic, Conn., Beaver Falls, Pa.;
and a plant in Canton that makes alloy steels for aerospace and
defense applications.
   The deal is subject to a rank-and-file vote of about 4,000
Steelworkers in the division and approval of a federal bankruptcy
judge in Dallas-based LTV's Chapter 11 reorganization.
   Officials said they hope the deal can be completed by June 30.
   The sale completes divestiture of steel operations that
Cleveland-based LTV Steel had sought in its plan to emerge from
reorganization as a smaller company concentrating on flat-rolled
and tubular products, LTV Corp. Chairman Raymond A. Hay said in a
statement.
   Russell W. Maier, president of the Canton-based bar division,
will be chief executive of the new company, to be known as Republic
Engineered Steels Inc.
   He said the name honors the former Republic Steel Co., which was
part of a 1984 merger that created LTV Steel.
   Maier said the division is profitable but needs at least $400
million in capital improvements to stay competitive.
   Joseph Coyle, Canton's USW District 27 director, said
Steelworkers would transfer about $4,000 worth of LTV stock each
into the new venture, for a total of about $17.6 million, with
other contributions coming from management.
</TEXT>
