<DOCNO> AP890530-0277 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-05-30-89 1827EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u f AM-Panhandle-Quantum     05-30 0352</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Panhandle-Quantum,0367</SECOND>
<HEAD>Quantum Chemical Buys Panhandle Propane Unit</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A partnership of Quantum Chemical Corp. and the
investment firm First Boston Inc. has agreed to buy the Petrolane
propane gas business from Panhandle Eastern Corp. and public
shareholders in a deal valued at $1.18 billion, it was announced
Tuesday.
   QFB Partners, the newly formed combination, will pay $450
million to Panhandle Eastern for Petrolane Inc., which consists of
a 44 percent interest in Petrolane Partners L.P. and a 100 percent
interest in a company that owns and leases propane tanks to the
partnership.
   In addition, it will spend $394.5 million for the 56 percent of
Petrolane Partners that is owned by public shareholders. It also
will take on $335 million in Petrolane debt.
   To acquire the portion owned by the public, QFB will begin
immediately a cash tender offer for the 13.15 million partnership
units of Petrolane owned by the public at $30 a share.
   On the New York Stock Exchange Tuesday, the stock rose $2.87{ to
close at $29.62{ a share.
   Quantum spokesman Richard A. Tilghman said the debt would
probably be refinanced.
   The agreement is subject to approval by antitrust regulators.
   Panhandle Eastern acquired Petrolane as part of its purchase
earlier this year of Texas Eastern Corp. Houston-based Panhandle
sold Petrolane to reduce its own debt.
   New York-based Quantum, whose main product is polyethylene,
recently undertook a partial recapitalization that left it with
$2.1 billion in debt. The joint venture with First Boston will
reduce the size of its investment and keep the new debt off its
books.
   Quantum until January 1988 was known as National Distillers
Corp. In 1987, it sold its liquor assets and bought Enron Corp.'s
polyethylene business. Its 1988 revenue totaled $3 billion.
   First Boston plans to make a $1 billion loan to finance the
purchase temporarily. The two companies each will put up $100
million for their share of the equity.
   Quantum's Suburban Propane Division will manage the Petrolane
propane business for QFB under a management agreement. Also under
the deal, Quantum can buy out First Boston's interest in five years.
</TEXT>
