<DOCNO> AP890530-0278 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-05-30-89 1902EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u f AM-Scotus-OldCourt     05-30 0397</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Scotus-Old Court,0412</SECOND>
<HEAD>Court To Consider Reviving Lawsuit Against Maryland S&amp;L</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JAMES H. RUBIN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Supreme Court on Tuesday agreed to
consider reviving a federal lawsuit stemming from the collapse of
Old Court Savings &amp; Loan Association in Maryland.
   The court said it will review a ruling that barred depositors
from using a federal anti-racketeering law to sue Old Court's
former owners and others.
   Old Court's collapse helped trigger a savings and loan crisis in
Maryland in 1985 and led to the criminal convictions of former
owners Jeffrey Levitt, Jerome Cardin and Allan Pearlstein.
   Levitt was sentenced to 30 years for stealing $14.7 million from
the thrift institution; Cardin 15 years for stealing $385,000;
Pearlstein eight years for stealing $640,786.
   Civil suits seeking hundreds of millions of dollars were filed
against the owners in federal and state courts. There have been
multi-million-dollar settlements of some of the state claims.
   Old Court owners and the others _ including a law firm and
accounting firm that worked for the institution _ were accused in
the suits of the largest financial fraud in Maryland's history.
   The 4th U.S. Circuit Court of Appeals last January upheld
dismissal of the federal suit.
   The appeals court rejected depositors' arguments that
certificates of deposit issued by Old Court were securities _ as
defined by the federal Securities Exchange Act of 1934.
   The appeals court relied upon a 1982 Supreme Court ruling that
said a long-term certificate issued by a federally insured bank is
not a security within the meaning of the 1934 law.
   The 4th Circuit court said the 1982 ruling means ``the existence
of a comprehensive regulatory and insurance system governing the
issuer removes certificates of deposit issued by it from the
general definition of securities.''
   Maryland had such a regulatory system, the appeals court said,
even though it failed to protect Old Court's depositors.
   The appeals court also said that the federal Racketeer
Influenced and Corrupt Organizations Act does not provide an
automatic basis for a federal lawsuit against Old Court. The lower
court said since the Old Court owners and others were sued in state
court for violating the anti-racketeering law, the federal courts
properly may decide to step aside.
   The justices today limited their review to the 4th Circuit
court's dismissal of the RICO allegations.
   The case is Tafflin vs. Levitt, 88-1650.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
