<FIRST>u f AM-CommodityRdp 1stLd-Writethru f0238 05-30 0697</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Commodity Rdp, 1st Ld-Writethru, f0238,0712</SECOND>
<HEAD>Cocoa Prices Plummet After Ivory Coast Announces Significant Cuts</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: SUBS 13th graf, `Precious metals ...,' to CORRECT price of platinum
by fixing misplaced decimial point.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JIM LITKE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Cocoa futures prices plunged Tuesday following a report that the
Ivory Coast, the world's largest cocoa producer, will cut by almost
40 percent the prices it pays farmers for the crop.
   The strong U.S. dollar, which also contributed to the drop in
cocoa futures, helped depress grain and soybean futures and
contributed to a mixed performance by precious metal futures.
   On other markets, frozen pork bellies turned sharply lower
because of rising inventories and petroleum futures were mixed.
   The July cocoa contract on the New York Coffee, Sugar and Cocoa
Exchange settled $79 lower at $1,141 a ton, with deferred months
showed drops ranging from $26 to $49 a ton.
   ``Cocoa may have ended off the day's lows only because of some
late short-covering,'' said Kim Badenhop of Merrill Lynch Capital
Markets Inc. in New York. ``It was plummeting for a while.''
   According to projections, Ivory Coast will sell an estimated
685,000 tons of cocoa this year, compared with 385,000 tons for
Brazil, the world's No. 2 marketer, and its producers already are
the highest-paid in Africa.
   Analysts had been anticipating that Ivory Coast President
Houphouet-Boigny would announce a cut in the producer prices soon
to save government funds and ease overproduction.
   Reports that Houphouet-Boigny would announce the cuts _ from
about $1,190 per ton to $744 _ later this week apparently
originated with remarks to that effect by a World Bank official
Tuesday in Washington.
   The U.S. dollar's continued rally in foreign exchange helped
nudge prices lower because significant amounts of cocoa are bought
and sold on the London Mercantile Exchange and the dollar improved
its position relative to the British pound.
   The stronger dollar _ which makes U.S. exports more expensive _
helped depress the grain markets on the Chicago Board of Trade,
although the principal market feature was weather, analysts said.
Grain and soybean futures prices closed lower nearly across the
board.
   Traders said wet weather that touched key growing areas over the
three-day holiday weekend and forecasts calling for more of the
same helped push prices lower.
   Wheat settled 3{ cents lower to 1 cent higher, with July at
$3.91 a bushel; corn was 2{ cents to 6{ cents lower, with July at
$2.61} a bushel; oats were 3{ cents to 4} cents lower, with July at
$1.65\ cents a bushel; and soybeans were 6 cents higher to 19 cents
lower, with July at $7.18 a bushel.
   Precious metals futures were mixed. Gold was 20 cents lower to
$1.50 higher on the Comex, with June at $365.70 a troy ounce;
silver was 2.5 cents to 3.4 cents lower, with June at $5.23 a troy
ounce. Platinum, traded on the New York Mercantile Exchange, was
$1.40 to $1.90 higher, with July at $509.360 a troy ounce.
   Frozen pork belly futures fell to life-of-contract lows at the
Chicago Mercantile Exchange because inventories are not shrinking
fast enough, analysts said.
   ``Because there's so much stockpiled, about 130 million bellies
have to go out between June 1 and October 1, or it's competing
against whatever's being produced in the fresh market,'' said Chuck
Levitt, an analyst with Shearson Lehman Hutton Inc. in Chicago.
``...everybody's seeking lower and lower levels until they find the
right price.''
   Frozen pork bellies were 1 cent to 1.6 cents lower, with July at
29.47 cents a pound; live hogs were .33 cent to .95 cent lower,
with June at 47.27 cents a pound; live cattle were .55 cent lower
to .28 cent higher, with June at 68.70 cents a pound; and feeder
cattle were .52 cent to .70 cent lower, with August at 76.52 cents
a pound.
   Crude oil traded on the New York Mercantile Exchange was 16
cents lower to 43 cents higher, with July at $19.95 a barrel;
heating oil was 5 cents to 25 cents lower, with June at 49.15 cents
a gallon; and unleaded gasoline was 22 cents to 95 cents higher,
with June at 66.61 cents a gallon.
</TEXT>
