<FIRST>r f BC-BoeingSale     05-30 0130</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-Boeing Sale,0136</SECOND>
<DATELINE>SEATTLE (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Malaysia Airlines ordered 16 Boeing 737s for
about $510 million and took options on 16 more Tuesday, Boeing Co.
officials said.
   A statement issued by Boeing said Malaysia's orders included 10
737-400s and six 737-500s, with delivery to begin in May 1992. The
types of jets to be bought under the options are to be decided
later if the options are exercised.
   CFM56-3C1 engines, made by a joint venture of SNECMA of France
and General Electric Co., were selected for all the firm orders and
options, the statement said.
   Airline officials said the new planes would replace 737-200s and
leased 737-400s in its fleet.
   Boeing's total orders for the year now stand at 568 planes
valued at about $31 billion, the statement said.
