<FIRST>r f BC-LeadingEdge     05-30 0245</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-Leading Edge,0253</SECOND>
<HEAD>Leading Edge Agrees to Be Purchased by Daewoo Telecom</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CANTON, Mass. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Leading Edge Products Inc. and Daewoo
Telecom Ltd. Inc. have signed a contract that will lead to the
purchase of Leading Edge by the South Korean company under a
reorganization plan, a bankruptcy court official said Tuesday.
   The plan, which requires court approval, would assure the
continued availability, sale and servicing of Leading Edge personal
computers and repayment in full of money owed by Leading Edge to
its dealers, according to Stephen M. Richmond, counsel to the
Chapter 11 reorganization trustee, Stephen Gray.
   Daewoo has been the exclusive manufacturer of Leading Edge's
Model D Series personal computer since 1985. Since then, Leading
Edge has sold $470 million worth of the machines, which use
software designed for International Business Machines Corp.
computers.
   The reorganization plan outlined in the contract will be filed
in U.S. Bankruptcy Court in Boston, and subsequently presented to
the creditors for approval, Richmond said.
   Leading Edge will be discharged from bankruptcy proceedings upon
approval of the plan by its creditors and confirmation by Chief
Judge James N. Gabriel of U.S. Bankruptcy Court in Boston.
   Leading Edge, founded by Michael Shane in 1980, sold $470
million worth of Leading Edge brand computers made by Daewoo in the
last 3{ years. The company, headquartered in this Boston suburb,
filed for reorganization Feb. 10.
   Daewoo Telecom is a manufacturer of computers and other office
automation and telecommunication products.
</TEXT>
