<DOCNO> AP890530-0285 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-05-30-89 2304EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r f AM-Lincoln-Donations     05-30 0370</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Lincoln-Donations,0384</SECOND>
<HEAD>Head Of Troubled Bank Company Donated Heavily to Politicians</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The head of financially troubled American
Continental Corp. of Phoenix and a circle of relatives and
associates donated more than $700,000 to political officeholders
over six years, the Los Angeles Times reported Tuesday.
   The contributions of Charles H. Keating Jr. and about 75 people
close to him have come under scrutiny since American Continental
filed April 13 for protection from creditors in U.S. Bankruptcy
Court.
   Lincoln Savings &amp; Loan in Irvine, American Continental's
principal subsidiary, was seized the next day by federal regulators
who alleged Keating and his company were operating the bank in an
unsound manner.
   The money from Keating and others went to 36 federal and state
politicians including more than $50,000 to U.S. Sens. Alan
Cranston, D-Calif., and Pete Wilson, R-Calif., the Times said.
   More than $100,000 went to U.S. Sen. John McCain, R-Ariz., more
than $55,000 to U.S. Sen. Dennis DeConcini, D-Ariz., and about
$20,000 to U.S. Rep. Jon Kyl, R-Ariz., the Times said.
   In addition, Ohio Democrat John Glenn received more than $34,500
from Keating associates, the paper reported.
   All of the senators involved said there was no impropriety in
taking money from Keating and his fund raisers and then later
taking up his cause in a dispute with federal savings and loan
regulators.
   At the California Capitol, where gubernatorial appointees
oversee Lincoln operations, more than $41,000 from Keating and the
others went to Republican Gov. George Deukmejian's campaign coffers
in the last four years, the paper said. Altogether, the Keating
group has given the California GOP $97,500 in the last four years,
the Times reported.
   In an Orange County Superior Court lawsuit, bondholders who
purchased $200 million in American Continental debt securities
claim Keating used his political connections to distract regulators
while he continued to sell junk bonds to depositors.
   Keating has denied the allegations in the lawsuit, one of
several class-action suits filed in Southern California and Arizona.
   Keating, as chairman of American Continental, a Phoenix real
estate development firm, bought Lincoln in 1984 and transformed it
from a traditional thrift to a more loosely structured S&amp;L that
ventured from home loans to investments in junk bonds.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
